<HEADLINE>BUYING TIME TO RESTORE CONFIDENCE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MALCOLM DICKSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Budget raised more questions about prospects for the next General Election
than it answered. The Chancellor failed to come out with his guns blazing as
many had predicted. The prudent spread of proposals for both spending and
taxation seems to offer a little to most, but not the great battle cry that
many of his own Conservative foot soldiers would have liked.
What may now be clear, however, is that the Tory Party has decided its best
hope for an election victory lies in its timing. This was a Budget that
suggested more than ever that Mr John Major would like to hold on until the
last possible moment - May 1997. If the Tories can hold out, that means another
Budget next year and a further opportunity to restore trust and confidence in
the Conservative Party.
The spread of tax cuts, allowance increases, and spending increases on key
services point to an incremental approach to winning back support. There is no
quick fix in this Budget. Nor could there have been because consistent evidence
has existed in recent opinion polls that spending increases were likely to be
just as popular as tax cuts.
A recent survey, carried out for James Capel and Company among previous
Conservative voters, showed that even loyal Tory supporters favoured spending
increases on health and education over tax cuts by a margin of two to one. This
key group was evenly divided over whether tax rate cuts or increases in tax
allowances would be better.
Mr Kenneth Clarke has tried to address each of these concerns to some degree.
But the previous Tory voters, who have now ditched the party, favoured spending
increases over tax cuts by a massive nine to one. The modest increases in
public spending may not be enough to win them back.
A more subtle strategy for the Tories may lie in the hope that lower interest
and mortgage rates could be the key to winning back voters' confidence and
trust. This Budget keeps the possibility of lower interest rates clearly in the
picture.
Yet two events loom so large in the minds of British voters that this Budget
may be too little, too late. The ERM crisis of 1992, and the subsequent tax
rises equivalent to 7p on the basic rate of income tax, destroyed key elements
in keeping Tory support solid. After the ERM crisis, the Tories lost the
initiative to Labour over which party was viewed as being more competent to run
the economy. Tax rises, especially after the promise of no increases during the
1992 General Election campaign, have restricted the ``feel good factor'' and
accompanying feelings of optimism about the economy.
As a result, the Tories are struggling to regain lost ground. Tax cuts may
reverse pessimism about family financial circumstances but the key ingredient
of trust on running the economy will not return overnight.
Yet it could be argued that this Budget does offer a possibility of a greater
degree of trust in the Government's handling of economic affairs. It could even
be described as a ``listening'' Budget. While the clamour in certain sections
of the media might have been for headline tax cuts of perhaps as much as 3p off
the basic rate, many voters' concerns are for public services as well as for
some evidence of action to reverse unwelcome tax increases.
What then is the likely impact of this Budget over the coming year? It
certainly is not going provide a significant improvement in the Conservatives'
electoral strength immediately. Labour's lead is too wide for any swift hope of
a Tory revival. What is more likely is that the combination of factors included
in the Budget will give a boost to middle income voters who are the key
constituency that the Tories need to win back. The changes in direct taxation
still tend to favour these and higher earning groups.
Voters tend to use only a short-term memory, perhaps of around one year, in
their assessment of the economy. As the effects of a modest tax-cutting Budget
build up, perhaps boosted by lower interest rates, the expectation will be
that, by the end of 1996, voters' perceptions of the Tories performance will be
greatly enhanced and that the memory of previous tax increases will fade.
Middle-income Tory voters with mortgages who have defected or abstained in the
last two years are the key to a possible Conservative success. Win this group
back and Mr Tony Blair will find life increasingly difficult. Mr John Redwood
described this Budget as a ``down payment''. Many voters are likely to agree.
The full test is yet to come.
While some commentators might have considered that only a Budget which slashed
income tax rates was ``political'', it might be the case that yesterday's
Budget was the only real political Budget that Mr Clarke could have come up
with.
q Dr Malcolm Dickson lectures in politics at Strathclyde University.
</TEXT>
