<HEADLINE>CLARKE'S STOCK FALLS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By R E DUNDAS Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142914</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOPES of a cut in interest rates before Christmas were back in the melting pot
last night after the City was taken aback by the public borrowing forecasts
announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke, in his Budget
statement.
The Public Sector Borrowing Requirement for the fiscal year to the end of March
is now expected to be #29bn, much higher than the #21.5bn forecast in last
year's Budget.
Even worse was the #22.5bn forecast for the new tax year beginning in April.
This had been pencilled in at #13bn last November.
The slowdown in economic activity is hitting the Government's revenues. The
City had been prepared for the PSBR figures to be revised up. But the extent of
this came as a shock, especially as Mr Clarke limited his net tax cuts to just
over #3bn, much less than the #4bn to #5bn that had been anticipated.
Gilts and sterling both fell after the Chancellor indicated how much he would
require to borrow over the next two years. The price of Government stock
dropped by three-quarters of a point from the levels before Mr Clarke took his
place at the Despatch Box.
Sterling retreated from DM2.2196 to DM2.2162 on the news and continued to drift
lower in North American trading. The trade weighted index fell 0.3 points to
82.9, just 0.4 points above its all-time low.
By contrast the stock market, which had become increasingly nervous before the
Budget, retrieved some of its losses after the Chancellor ruled out a windfall
tax.
Drinks and gaming shares mostly benefited from the Budget measures, which cut
some excise duties and froze the duty on wine and beer. The FTSE-100 share
index ended the day down 0.2 points at 3648.8, well above its low point of
3636.1.
Adam Cole, UK economist at City stockbroker, James Capel, said the PSBR figures
were disappointing and the Chancellor should have done more to cut public
spending.
As a result there was less scope for an early reduction in interest rates, and
any cut was more than ever dependent on the performance of sterling and what
Germany and the US did. ``I am not so optimistic as I was,'' he added.
The Bundesbank and the US Federal Reserve Board are both thought to have the
scope to cut rates, with the Germans expected to lead the way with a reduction
tomorrow.
Mr Clarke meets the Governor of the Bank of England, Eddie George, on December
13 to decide monetary policy. Had the Chancellor been able to confine his PSBR
forecast for next year to the City's consensus forecast of #20bn, he might have
been able to force through a cut in rates. The prospect of this was receding
last night.
Eyebrows were also raised at some of his economic assumptions. He cut his
forecast for this year's growth rate from 3% to 2.75% and then increased next
year's figures from 2.75% to 3%.
Independent economists were susprised at the strength of his growth forecasts.
If they turn out to be too optimistic it could further exacerbate his
difficulties over public borrowing.
Some economists said that a reduction in rates would be needed if activity was
to pick up next year. The Bank of England, however, might argue that if the
economy was to grow at above its trend rate of 2.25% then there was no need for
rates to be reduced.
The Treasury is expecting the growth in consumer spending to increase from
2.25% this year to 3.5% next year. It also expects underlying inflation to fall
from 3% in the final quarter of this year to 2.5% by the end of next year. This
would be in line with the Government's own inflation target for the end of the
Parliament.
</TEXT>
