<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DEVALUATION OF A BRIBE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN the dismal science of economics has to give reality a passing nod now and
then. Chancellor Clarke, bluff as an auctioneer of fine second-hand motor
vehicles, recites the happy mantras with the best of them, but he knows where
rhetoric ends and the real world begins.
``Spectacular efficiency savings,'' he said; ``policies of change''; ``popular
capitalism''; ``a property-owning democracy''; ``the enterprise centre of
Europe''. Yet even as these visions swam before the eye, it was clear this
Budget was just another small skirmish fought over Middle England, and one,
moreover, launched by a Chancellor so hemmed in by dismal facts he could
neither galvanise his party nor put Labour to flight.
With its close attention to privatised care, small businesses, employee share
options, and the like, Clarke's Budget was precisely as class-specific as you
might expect. This is not a Chancellor who lies awake at night wondering how to
defeat poverty or rejuvenate the inner cities, rather one who ponders how to
win back the flocks of middling sorts who have strayed in Mr Blair's direction.
They're still worried about the NHS? Chuck them a billion. Law and order? Order
up a few more bobbies. Schools? Give them something - but not too much. And if,
in a country in which 60% of the workforce now lacks true job security, they
still need a spoonful of sugar, try a penny off the basic rate and hope they'll
forget about indirect taxes.
In truth, this was tinkering, a little of everything and great deal of nothing.
Clarke may put his faith in 3% growth (he and Gordon Brown have a panacea in
common, if nothing else) but the markets see a PSBR that refuses to lie down
and die. And on past form predictions of zero borrowing will be like snow unto
a dyke come the millennium.
Only a suicidally-loyal Tory MP could imagine that this was an election-winning
prescription. There are few things more poignant than a politician who can't
scrape together the price of a bribe, and the stubborn truth is that, on the
day, Clarke simply did not have the wherewithal to buy his party out of trouble.
Then again, this dull Budget may have marked the real end of the Conservative
adventure. Having shifted so much of the country's burden on to consumption
taxes like VAT, it is now near-impossible for a Tory Chancellor to dazzle the
voters with the money he is putting back into their pockets ``to spend as they
like''. The old shell game doesn't play any more. Or as Blair correctly said,
people have caught on: what goes in one pocket leaves from the other.
All the signs are that Middle Britain, if such a place really exists, neither
wants nor needs a comfort blanket. The Budget does not address the real fears
glibly mis-named ``the feelgood factor''; it does not encourage anyone to
believe their home, job, or old age is secure.
It is neither Thatcherite revolution, with its fanatic self-belief, nor decent
one-nation Toryism: the whiff, distinct and unmistakable, is of low-grade
expediency.
Business will be content, not ecstatic. The whisky trade wins a measure of
simple justice; the privatised utilities escape to pillage again another day.
Property-owning democrats will discover, meanwhile, that the doubling of the
upper assets limit for long-term care is irrelevant when your home is your only
asset; single mothers and those under 25 trying to achieve an independent life
will find that Tory morality comes brutally cheap.
The rest of us might ponder why, with the economy going so well, a quarter of
taxpayers earn only enough to qualify for the 20% band. If this is something to
boast about, the pickings are slim indeed: paid so little, how do they afford
all those VAT-rated goods? If there was a philosophy underlying all this you
could describe it as the conviction that Government could be run as a business
and that, therefore, it might as well be handed over to business.
Clear from Clarke's speech was the idea that much of what was once the
responsibility of elected representatives should be farmed out to private
enterprise, that governments should do less governing.
Why, then, should anyone applaud a Chancellor who boasts of what he isn't going
to do, and who promises what we know he can't deliver? Tories will have hoped
for much more; the rest of us (that growing band) probably expected nothing
less.
</TEXT>
