<HEADLINE>Father John Conway, Priest, 64</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142916</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Father John Conway, 64, Parish Priest at St Flannan's Roman Catholic Church in
Hillhead Road, Kirkintilloch, near Glasgow.
Budget hopes: Father Conway, who estimated that as many as 30% of young people
in some parts of Kirkintilloch were jobless, is particularly concerned about
unemployment and homelessness. He said this had lead to a lack of self-worth,
the breakdown of family life, and abuse of alcohol and drugs, and crime. He
would have liked the Chancellor to announce that the Government intended
devoting more resources to job creation and that cash-strapped local
authorities would be capped less and allowed to invest more in housing. He said
political expediency would inevitably be a factor in the Budget - ``there are
always a few carrots before a general election'' - but added that genuine
concessions to young people and the elderly and greater support for
professionals such as teachers was more important than short-term tax cuts.
Budget reaction: Father Conway described it as ``a cautious but disappointing
budget with no reference to unemployment or the long-term care of pensioners''.
He said he believed what Mr Clarke had given in education could have been much
better. He said the Budget was as he expected born of political expediency - Mr
Clarke did not want to ``rock the boat'' before the next General Election - and
that the average family would not be much better off as a result.
</TEXT>
