<HEADLINE>FORSYTH IN TOAST TO THE UNION</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, Political Reporter and ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECRETARY of State Michael Forsyth last night praised a Budget that delivered a
27p cut in whisky duty and tax cuts for all Scots as ``tangible proof'' of the
benefits of Scotland's place in the Union.
However, Labour claimed the Scottish Secretary failed to protect the country's
interests by accepting a 2.1% cut in next year's Scottish Office budget,
despite presenting himself as ``Scotland's man in the Cabinet''.
Mr Forsyth said: ``The Chancellor will be the toast of Scotland tonight and I
am delighted he has responded to the representations to cut the tax on Scotch
whisky. He has done us proud and the industry which is so important to jobs,
exports, and our national prosperity will be delighted.''
He emphasised that next year's Scottish budget would be the ``highest ever'' in
cash terms, adding: ``My budget represents an average #2838 per person next
year, well over a third more than the equivalent provision in England.
``It is tangible proof of the benefits to all Scots of our present
constitutional position within the Union.''
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson dismissed his interpretation. ``The
financial settlement for Scotland confirms that spending will be cut in real
terms,'' he said.
``Scots will have to pay the price of the Tories' economic failure through
poorer quality public services.
``The Secretary of State has clearly failed to protect Scotland from the
Treasury hawks. This Budget gives the lie to his claim that he is Scotland's
man in the Cabinet.''
He added: ``Today's `7p up, 1p down' Budget will not alter the fact that Scots
families are still worse off under the Tories and better off with Labour.
People are still #670 a year worse off after this Budget.''
He added: ``People in Scotland's rural areas will suffer from the rises in
petrol duties.''
Scottish National Party leader Alex Salmond accused Mr Clarke of reinforcing
the unfairness of previous Budgets. ``Instead of the Budget for growth, jobs,
and social justice demanded by mainstream Scotland, we have the start of the
Tory tax drive at middle England,'' he said.
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace criticised the Chancellor for
failing to do anything to help Scotland's education system in what he described
as a ``Tory Save Our Seats Budget''.
He said: ``Last year, with a lower prediction for borrowing, the Government
said it was unable to cut taxes. This year, with higher predicted Government
borrowing, the Chancellor has cut taxes, bowing to back-bench pressure in a
desperate bid to save their seats.''
The opposition parties were unanimous in dismissing the cut in whisky duty as
an overdue reversal of previous increases.
Mr Robertson called it a ``humiliating U-turn'' that ``comes too late for those
workers in the whisky industry who lost their jobs as a result of last year's
tax hike''.
Mr Wallace said: ``The Chancellor has simply reversed the tax he imposed last
year in a fit of pique. He has accepted the argument for lower duties but has
not been bold enough to will the means''.
Mr Salmond said the cut was inadequate. ``The Chancellor has merely cancelled
the rise the Tories imposed in January,'' he added. ``He should have reduced
duty by 10% as the SNP proposed. This would have given the industry the boost
it so desperately needs.''
The leading Scottish Conservative who advocated a windfall tax on privatised
utilities yesterday conceded that the companies would now take action to avoid
any future attempt to claw back their profits.
Mr John Godfrey, the Perth and Kinross candidate who led the economic debate at
the party conferences in both Glasgow and Blackpool, said he stood by the view
that excessive profits should be returned to consumers but said it was
``ridiculous'' for Labour to assume that the ``utility cash pile'' would be
there by the time of the next General Election.
Mr Godfrey said: ``Having had a narrow escape this time, the companies
concerned will be all the keener to tax-plan the surplus away over the next
year.''
His remarks were seized on by Mr Salmond who said Mr Godfrey had ``blown the
gaffe'' on Tory tax anomalies, with the utilities being given a yellow card
warning them to take action to avoid future taxation. He claimed both the
Government and Labour should have looked at SNP sugestions to make permanent
cuts in standing charges for pensioners.
Scots Tory chairman Sir Michael Hirst called the Budget ``sensible and
balanced'' - a description which was used as a criticism by opponents.
Sir Michael insisted that the elderly, savers and the less well off would
benefit.
He also praised the Chancellor and Scots Secretary for responding to the pleas
of the Scotch Whisky Association by cutting duty on spirits and claimed the
average family in Scotland would be #9 per week better off as a result of the
Budget.
STUC general secretary Campbell Christie described the Budget as ``the most
socially divisive since 1988''.
He added: ``It has failed to address the fundamental problems of the British
economy. It will do little for job generation in Scotland and heralds a new
assault on public services and benefits claimants.
``This is a good Budget for someone living in a #200,000 house, driving a
vintage Rolls-Royce. It is a bad Budget if you are under 25 and homeless or
unemployed and seeking work.''
</TEXT>
