<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Soft-shoe shuffler takes care not to trip</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142918</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KENNETH CLARKE may not go down as Britain's greatest Chancellor, but his
antennae are so acute he could probably pick up the Princess of Wales's
mobile-phone conversations.
For weeks, the juxtaposition of economic expectation and political peril had
lain before him like a minefield. Yet yesterday he picked his way through it
with greater dexterity than that of a retreating Iraqi soldier.
Many thought it was beyond our Ken to dance to the tune of those disparate
constituencies: the electorate, the Tory back bencher, and the City. In the
event, his soft-shoe shuffle was carried out with reasonable aplomb and must
surely raise the share value of his beloved Hush Puppies. It might well, in
restrospect, do the same for the Government.
It might not have been the bravura performance of which he is capable, but it
did unsettle and surprise the Labour front bench, giving credence to the joke
circulating in Westminster that Tony Blair, after all those years, is finally
developing an attachment for Gordon Brown - it fits over his mouth.
Ken Clarke is no Harold Macmillan but there was a tinge of ``Super Mac'' -
albeit a Midlands version - in the way he teased and taunted despite having so
little in the locker. But for once the baying Opposition were akin to hungry
wolves in the desert rather than hounds round an entrapped fox as in the
debates over Europe.
Although his understanding of economic minutiae is allegedly on a par with that
of the House of Windsor on fidelity, Mr Clarke's Budget was nevertheless shrewd
and sensible. It underpinned the one great success of the Government, the
strength of the economy and the commitment to low inflation which are the
precursors to any possible feel-good factor.
But if anyone had any doubts that Mr Major intended to run this parliament to
the line and hold an election in 1997 then this should settle it.
This Budget was the prequel. The real pre-election Budget is 12 months away.
What it has done is hold the line and test the water at the same time.
According to the opinion polls, the public were keener on more public spending
in targeted areas than tax cuts. Well they got it - in the ultra-sensitive
areas of schools, hospitals, and police - note the use of the words, not
``education'', ``NHS'', and ``law and order''.
He also addressed the concerns of the burgeoning ``grey vote'' - the pensioners
who are afraid of losing everything they have worked for by seeing it gobbled
up in long-term residential care costs.
He was also able to make a concession on lower direct taxes with the 1p off
income tax, higher personal allowances, and one million taxpayers held within
the 20% tax limit. This is the area he will build on at the next Budget, which
he already has in his sights by deliberately raising the Public Sector
Borrowing Requirement for the following year by #10bn over his previous
estimate. If this does not pave the way to a 20% rate for us all by the next
election then my name is James Hewitt.
What his ``neutral'' Budget means is that by keeping the City sweet there
should be an imminent cut in interest rates, probably within the next week or
two in the run-up to Christmas. Next year, with billions of pounds expected to
be pumped into the economy when the merging of building societies releases cash
to thousands of individuals, along with extra in the Treasury coffers from
privatisations, the economy should recover from its semi-comatose state.
Further cuts in interest rates will be an additional stimulus to the economy.
This will result in a lower borrowing requirement. However, having declared
such a hefty sum, the Chancellor will be determined to use it for genuine,
swingeing tax cuts and more specific public spending.
His extra taxes on the road fund licence, petrol, and cigarettes, far from
being criticised by the public, will be welcome in this environmentally dotty
age. It is a well he will return to again.
As Mr Clarke likes to say: ``It's not all over till the fat lady sings.'' Or,
even, a portly Chancellor.
</TEXT>
