<HEADLINE>Blair hails milestone on the Tories' road to defeat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR,  Our Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142919</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair last night branded Chancellor Kenneth Clarke's package
as the ``7p up, 1p down Budget'', and said it was another milestone on the
Tories' road to electoral defeat.
He described reaction on the Tory benches as ``the shortest-lasting cheer we
have witnessed'', and added: ``If this was supposed to relaunch the
Conservative Party, it will fail.''
A clearly angry Mr Blair told the House that the British people were not
novices in dealing with the Tories, but were battle-hardened and had learned
hard lessons. He branded the Tories ``masters of political deception''.
He said: ``Over 16 years they know that what they are given with one hand is
taken away with the other. One hand may hold open the public purse but the
other is there in the citizen's pocket.''
Rounding on the Tory benches, he said they claimed income taxes had been cut
over the years, but there had been rises in other areas such as rail fares, bus
and Tube fares, rent rises, water charges, and insurance premiums. Roared on by
his own side, he said: ``They don't like to be reminded of it, but that is
Conservative policy.''
For 16 years Conservative politicians had been standing in the House saying
there would be an economic miracle, but for 16 years, living standards had been
falling compared to other countries, with Britain now down from 13th to 18th in
the economic league.
The Tories knew that a higher proportion was taken in taxation than 16 years
ago, despite the benefit of #120bn in North Sea Oil revenues, and they knew
that, whatever promises had been made before the last election, there had been
the largest peacetime tax rises in British history.
Mr Blair said there were some things in the Budget that were welcome including
improvements in long term care.
But he said: ``Taken as a whole, this is not a Budget for Britain's long-term
future. It gives with one hand what it takes with the other in a host of costs
and charges.
``It ignores completely the fundamental weaknesses of the economy. It does
nothing about unemployment, social division and decay in Britain today.
``It doesn't deal with, but avoids, the key issues on welfare.
The Labour leader accused the Government of winning power by promising not to
raise taxes and then doing the opposite.
He said: ``People after this Budget will still remain, since the last election,
as a result of the tax rises, #700 a year worse off. That is a fact, they can't
deny it.''
He said the Chancellor should have introduced a windfall tax on the privatised
utilities, but he was afraid to do so.
``Because these are the vested interest of the Tory Party, and they do not dare
challenge them . . . the case for taking on these vested interests and funding
a decent education and employment programme for our young people is
overwhelming.''
Mr Blair said there were three things the Budget had to do - tackle the
problems of the economy, increase investment and skills, and tackle the
problems of social division, but nothing of that sort had been done.
He added: ``If Tory MPs think as the result of this Budget, the inspiration
will come to the British people to re-elect them again, I can only assume they
have been out of touch for so long, they do not know what to do to get back in
touch with the electorate again.
``Tory MPs have given up on any serious vision for this country's future. They
wanted to hail this Budget as a turning point, but the British people know
better.
``It is another milestone on their road to defeat and the sooner, the better,''
he said to Labour cheers and waving of order papers.
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown said: ``This should have been a Budget to
save our schools. It is a Budget instead, for the Conservatives, to `save our
seats'.
``We have just heard the last shot in the locker of the Tory Party. There is
nothing more.
``The message of the Government was simple and brutally clear: please can we
buy your vote for a penny cut in income tax. We've nothing further to offer
you.''
He warned: ``In deciding how to respond to that offer from this Government, the
people might do well to remind themselves of an old Russian proverb, borne out
in this Budget: free cheese only comes in mousetraps.''
Mr Ashdown said Mr Clarke had produced the tax cut by a ``sleight of hand'', by
increasing borrowing, risking the economy's long-term future.
</TEXT>
