<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The politics are more fascinating than the economics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142920</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WAS to be the Budget where Kenneth Clarke would relegate thoughts of
economic statesmanship to more pressing political considerations.
Not for him the historic symbolism of the battered red box this year. Rather
the looming judgment of the thousands of black boxes into which the electorate
will deliver their final verdict on the Government within the next 18 months.
The Chancellor, we were told, was set to stuff our pockets with pound notes in
a blatant last-ditch attempt to buy our votes for a fifth successive Tory
victory. However, although there were tax cuts, yesterday's package was modest,
even mean in places. Tony Blair called it the 7p up-1p down Budget, a reference
to the thumping tax increases in the last three Budgets.
However, was it also the statesmanship in - opportunism out Budget?
For the Tory Party's natural constituency - the middle England, Scotland, Wales
and Ulster the Chancellor says he is targeting - the net effect of the income
tax changes and the rise in petrol and other duties leaves them with up to #450
extra in next year's household piggy bank.
Enough for an off-season week for two in Benidorm perhaps. Or a rock-bottom
personal computer for the kids. That does not look, on the face of it, the kind
of electoral bribe which might assuage years of middle-class unease over
negative equity, job insecurity, and the evaporation of inheritance hopes when
the grandparents go into residential care.
Each time Mr Clarke came to a specific announcement - the 27p a bottle sop to
the embattled Scotch whisky industry; the doubling to #16,000 of the asset
threshold above which the elderly have to pay for their own residential care;
the rise in the inheritance tax threshold to #200,000; and that final 1p off
basic rate income tax - the numbers he produced patently underwhelmed even
those sitting on the benches behind him.
And yet the politics underpinning yesterday's ``broadly neutral'' package are
fascinating. The Chancellor knew from some distance out that a reckless
giveaway would bring down the wrath of the markets. A worsening Public Sector
Borrowing Requirement this year, which had surpassed last November's full-year
forecast within six months, had them watching his every move like hawks.
Now we know that the year-end forecast for the gap between what the Government
raises in revenue and what it spends has been revised upwards again to #29bn
for this year, an even higher figure than most City economists expected. And
even two years from now the PSBR is now expected to be #10bn above what the
Chancellor was predicting just 12 months ago.
That gap could grow if the economy starts to flirt with recession again, and
tax revenues take a further dive. On growth, the Treasury remains remarkably
bullish, forecasting a 3% rise in GDP next year at a time when some in the City
are pushing their own forecasts well below 2% and even, in extreme cases,
contemplating a mild bout of recession, as demand in Europe and the United
States cools down and stocks here are run down.
If, despite the official Red Book forecast, the Chancellor recognises that
downside recessionary risk, was this prudent Budget a prelude to greater
excitement in monetary policy? Are we and the markets being softened up for a
dramatic full point cut in interest rates, say, in the days ahead?
Because of its immediacy, its impact on mortgage costs and its kick-start
effect on a stalling economy, such a move on interest rates would have far more
impact in the real economy and on the persistent feel-bad factor in the middle
lands of the kingdom than up to #8.50 a week extra in our pockets, money which
will not start appearing until next April.
That is one reading of what the Chancellor is up to. However, this cautious
package could also mean that Ministers are now reconciled to going the full
distance, hoping against hope that Labour's public consensus will fall apart
and leaving Mr Clarke free to unveil the real giveaway next November.
However, if the Cabinet is bracing itself for the really long haul, it will,
given its perilously small overall majority, have to take its own most
recalcitrant back benchers with it.
Before yesterday they were demanding really dramatic spending cuts to pay for
substantial tax cuts. They want a significantly smaller state where people keep
a lot more of what they earn.
Whatever those back benchers say in public, yesterday's package must have
disappointed them. After all the talk of a really bloody public expenditure
round, with William Waldegrave wielding a stylish cleaver, he has managed to
carve just #3200m from the #263.4bn control total pencilled in for 1996-97 a
year ago. And that is fully accounted for in the #3200m cut in next year's
contingency reserve.
Additional resources for schools, hospitals and the police were highlighted in
the Chancellor's speech. However, there are modest increases elsewhere too.
Big losers among the spending departments, apart from defence, housing and the
non-schools side of education and employment are hard to find.
The Chancellor will try to persuade them that he is on course to get public
spending below the 40% of GDP threshold by 1997-98. He will claim that the
private finance initiative is at last on track for take off, with #14bn worth
of contracts to be let by early 1999. He will insist that the welfare monster
is now under control. But will they believe him?
In this Budget, Kenneth Clarke has behaved as if he really believes in a
balance between personal incentives and a State which still provides for basic
needs. He may be planning a big and early cut in interest rates.
He and John Major may be in this for the long haul. Is he also, in an age when
the currency of politics has been devalued in the public mind, trying to
reassert some sense of principle and statesmanship? And, in one small corner of
his mind, could he also be contemplating an election already lost and,
thereafter, a fight for the soul of the Tory Party?
As I said, the politics of this grudging Budget are far more fascinating than
the economics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
