<HEADLINE>Ten tips on how to beat Budget</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142921</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q.Don't die before April 6. You relatives won't be able to benefit from the
increase in inheritance tax exemption from #154,000 to #200,000.
q.Go and fill up your car at Sainsbury's and Tesco's. They are both holding
their petrol prices until after the weekend.
q. Roll your own fags. Hand rolling tobacco escaped the Chancellor's clamp down
on smoking which pushed up the price of a packet of cigarettes by 15p.
q.Trade in your car for an old banger to avoid the new #140 tax disc -
increased by #5. Cars and motorcycles over 25 years old are exempt to help
owners of vintage and classic vehicles.
q.If strong cider is your tipple, start stocking up soon to avoid the 8p a pint
increase from next October.
q.Unlucky lottery players may think about returning to doing the pools or
having a flutter on the horses thanks to a reduction in betting duty - one
prediction that escaped Mystic Meg's crystal ball. Chancellor Clarke said he
was cutting pools betting duty by 5% from November. And Littlewoods was
delighted, saying the savings would be spent on promotion and prizes. Pools
firms have been pleading for help over the past year because of the damage the
National Lottery has done to the industry. In August, Littlewoods said it was
closing an office in Cardiff with the loss of 320 jobs as a result of
competition from the lottery.
q.Hang on before fixing your mortgage as all the experts are now forecasting an
early cut in interest rates to meet Mr Clarke's optimistic economic growth
target.
q.Don't worry if you are facing redundancy - Mr Clarke said he never was
planning to tax the first #30,000 of your pay-off as many pundits had suggested.
q.Top up your bank and building society deposit accounts where the tax rate is
going down from 25% to 20%. ``This change makes deposit-based saving more
attractive in terms of taxation than share-based products,'' said Building
Society Association director-general Adrian Coles.
q.Celebrate the forthcoming income tax reductions with a bottle of whisky,
which will be 27p a bottle cheaper. Tesco is aiming to cut the price of a
bottle of Scotch by 27p from today. Sainsbury's says prices will fall from
Friday and Asda is promising to undercut all its rivals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rural drivers bear the brunt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH BUIE, Environment Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORISTS are the Budget's biggest victims, with 19p extra on a gallon of
petrol and Scotland's rural drivers paying even more, the AA said last night.
Highlands and Islands Enterprise added to the warnings about how rural
communities would be affected, claiming that Budget tax cuts for small
businesses in the North of Scotland could be offset by increases in fuel prices.
While reductions in tax for small businesses, which comprise 90% of companies
in the area, were welcomed, increased duties on petrol and diesel were likely
to push up transport costs.
HIE's senior economist, Tracey Slaven, said: ``Many firms depend on
long-distance road transport for importing raw materials and exporting finished
goods, while the area's #500m-a-year tourism industry relies heavily on
car-borne visitors.''
The Scottish Licensed Trade Association said: ``We are appalled at the savage
increase in the cost of petrol and diesel. This really does affect Scotland and
can have a devastating result on tourism, and to residents and visitors in our
more rural areas.''
The Chancellor's increases in motoring costs are likely to cost the motorist
who does about 8000 miles a year an additional #55 per annum.
Mr Neil Greig, the AA's road and environment officer in Scotland, said: ``We
have seen petrol duty rise by more than a third in the last three years. This
has a huge effect on rural Scotland, because motorists do not benefit from the
competition between petrol retailers in the Central Belt - and with lack of
public transport many have no alternative but to use their cars.''
Environmentalists claimed the Chancellor's measures lacked imagination and
would do little, if anything, to help transport related environmental problems.
Dr Richard Dixon, head of research for Friends of the Earth Scotland, said:
``We welcome the increased duty on super unleaded petrol, but it is not enough.
It should have been banned straight away. Even motoring organisations say there
is no real benefit in using it.''
Despite the rises, Chancellor Clarke said petrol prices in the UK ``should
remain lower than in any major European country''.
However, Mr Adam Wurf, speaking on behalf of the Freight Transport Association,
said that Britain had the highest fuel duty and VAT in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>THE PENNY PINCHER</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ronnie Dundas, Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke had much less scope for tax reductions than had been
widely assumed.
As a result, his Budget, much of which had been heavily leaked, turned out to
be a damp squib. He now desperately needs the Government to survive for another
year so that he has a second chance to establish his reputation as a
tax-cutting Chancellor.
The slowdown in activity is having a much bigger impact on Government revenues
than had been predicted and the public sector borrowing requirement forecasts
of #29bn for the current fiscal year and #22.5bn for the year beginning in
April were disappointingly large.
Although there are modest cuts around the wicket for the spending departments
to pay for the extra resources allocated to the priority areas of health,
education, and the police, the tax cuts announced in the Budget have been
financed by raiding the contingency reserve.
In 1996/97, this has been reduced from #6000m to #2500m.
The latest PSBR forecast for the current year is #7500m higher than the one
made in last year's Budget, and the one for 1996/97 #9500m more. Having been
caught out once by his projections, the Chancellor may have been more cautious
in this year's forecasts.
The big disappointment is that he is now forecasting a higher PSBR for 1996/97
than the one originally forecast for the current year.
The net cut in taxes (from an indexed base) amounts to #3140m and this has been
financed by comparable reductions in Government spending. Accordingly, the
Budget is broadly neutral.
The centrepiece is the 1p cut in the basic rate of income tax to 24p at a cost
of #1600m, which represents a little more than half of the total available for
tax reductions. There was no way the Budget arithmetic could ever have been
squared with the 2p reduction sought by some of Mr Clarke's hawkish back
benchers.
Indeed, there is a strong case for arguing that the Chancellor did not have
enough money at his disposal to justify the 1p cut, the first reduction since
1988. The increases in allowances and in the higher rate threshold are
niggardly. The married couples' allowance, the value of which has been savaged
in recent years, has only been indexed for inflation.
Personal allowances are being increased by #100 more than inflation at a cost
of #480m. The higher rate threshold, which had been frozen in three successive
Budgets, is only being raised by #200 more than inflation at a cost of just
#40m.
The number of 40% taxpayers is thought to have increased by 700,000 to
2,200,000 over the last six years. This was a natural constituency for Mr
Clarke to have courted and he could have done so without a substantial loss of
revenue.
The lower rate band, where tax is charged at 20p, has been increased by #500
more than indexation and will now cover the first #3900 of taxable income. This
is fine but it seems absurd to represent it as significant progress towards the
objective of reducing the basic rate to 20p. The cost is #370m.
The most imaginative proposal in the Budget is the decision to cut the tax on
savings for basic rate taxpayers to 20p in the pound. Some may say it is the
only imaginative proposal. The new savings rate is in line with the 20% tax
credited to dividend cheques and will be of substantial benefit to large
numbers of retired people.
The tax system formerly discriminated against investment income but now it has
swung full circle to discriminate in its favour. Those with savings and
investments have become a large constituency whose interests will continue to
demand the attention of future Chancellors.
At a cost of #800m, it was the second biggest measure in the Budget.
Mr Clarke was able to increase the exemption limit for inheritance tax from
#154,000 to #200,000. The cost was #130m but there will be disappointment that
he could not do more to limit the impact of this tax on families who by no
stretch of the imagination could be described as rich.
The decision to cut the basic rate by 1p as the first instalment of what looks
like being a long haul to a 20p rate tied the Chancellor's hands, especially on
allowances.
Freezing allowances in earlier years played an important part in raising the
extra revenues needed to reduce public borrowing after the ravages of the
recession.
A significant reversal of this disguised method of raising the tax take would
have required the Chancellor to be much tougher on public spending or to have
foregone the 1p cut in the basic rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business incentives rate limited aproval</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142924</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Business incentives rate limited approval
THE Budget contained several incentives for small businesses, including a 1p in
the pound reduction in corporation tax and a lower cap on annual rate rises.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke also reduced the qualifying age for capital gains tax
relief for selling on a business from 55 to 50.
He raised the threshold for inheritance tax from #154,000 to #200,000 and
exempted all shareholdings in unquoted companies from death duty, making it
easier to pass on small businesses from one generation to another.
The Federation of Small Businesses gave a guarded welcome to these measures but
said the tighter rate cap did nothing to redress the complaint of Scottish
businesses that they generally paid higher rates than their English
counterparts.
``We give the Budget a muted, limited welcome,'' said Mr Bill Anderson, the
Scottish secretary of the federation. ``It is not everything we hoped for but
at least some things are good.''
The standard rate of corporation tax on small businesses was reduced to 24%
from 25%, in line with the Chancellor's 1p in the pound cut in the basic rate
of income tax.
Mr Anderson, whose federation represents 80,000 small businesses in the UK,
including 8200 in Scotland, said this tax cut was ``helpful''.
There was no change in the #1m allowance against capital gains tax given to the
owners of businesses selling up on retirement. Mr Anderson said the reduction
of the qualifying age by five years to 50 would make it easier to sell small
businesses, which generally employed less than 20 people and had a turnover of
less than #1m.
However, he was scornful of the Government's measures to place tighter curbs on
business rates, despite the favourable treatment meted out to small businesses.
The Chancellor reduced the general cap on annual increases in business rates
from 10% to 7.5% in real terms with effect from April 6, 1996, but for small
firms the cap was halved to 5%.
Mr Anderson said these measures would benefit English companies, many of which
suffered a sharp increase in rateable value last year, much more than Scottish
firms, which had always paid higher rates. Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
said the tighter caps would reduce Scotland's business rate bill by #21m over
the next three years and would benefit 74,000 small non-domestic properties in
Scotland.
He announced that poundage for Scottish non-domestic rates would be 44.9p in
the coming tax year.
But Mr Anderson said the Government was just putting ``sticking plaster'' on a
problem that often led to Scottish companies paying 50% more in rates than
their English counterparts.
Mr Anderson called for the rating system to be scrapped and replaced with a
system of progressive taxation by local authorities, based on a percentage of
company profits.
He welcomed the increase in the threshold for inheritance tax to #200,000 and
the 100% exemption granted to shareholdings in unquoted companies, most of
which were small firms.
``That allows us to hand on from one generation to another and gives stability,
not only to the owners, but also to the workforce,'' he said.
The 27p a bottle cut in duty on whisky was seen as giving a filip to small
businesses in the Highlands and Islands, where distilleries featured
prominently in the local economy.
However, Mr Anderson said the extra 3.5p a litre tax on petrol and diesel would
penalise small firms in remote rural areas. Petrol was already about 10p a
litre dearer in northern Scotland than in the densely populated central belt,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CBI criticises reduction in public expenditure</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor was bound to emphasise the Private Finance Initiative which was
introduced two years ago but has been roundly criticised as faltering, not
least by the CBI which is undertaking its own study into how the situation can
be improved.
The aim is for private companies and organisations to help fund public sector
projects across a wide range and, at the same time, bring in their management
expertise. However, many companies have complained of excessive red tape,
delays, and, in some cases, too high a risk factor. There have also been
complaints that there has not been enough focus on key projects and heavy
initial costs.
Mr Clarke, though, argued that the initiative delivered infrastructure projects
of higher quality at a lower overall cost to the taxpayer precisely because the
private sector put its own money at risk and brought its own management skills
to bear.
He backed his case by announcing a substantial new package of privately
financed roads, five projects with a capital value totalling #500m. Full bids
will be due on December 5 for #45m water schemes in Inverness and Fort William.
A minimum of #14bn of private finance contracts is expected to be agreed by the
end of 1998/99, including the #5000m of private finance contracts on course to
be agreed by 1995/96.
For Scotland, the estimated capital spending from the Private Finance
Initiative is #140m for 1996/97, #360m for 1997/98, and #420m for 1998/99. The
total of #920m compares with a UK total of #7240m.
CBI director general Adair Turner gave general approval to the Budget but said
his organisation was concerned about the cut in public capital expenditure,
which was to be supplemented by trying to attract private investment in capital
projects under the Government's Private Finance Initiative plan.
``We will need to see the details to assess this in full. The Chancellor has
set a very aggressive private finance initiative target to counterbalance that
cut and it is up to the Government to deliver on this,'' he said.
Transport Secretary Sir George Young, commenting on the #500m extension to the
Design, Build, Finance, and Operate (DBFO) roads programme, said the national
roads network would benefit from more than #1000m of private sector investment
in DBFOs, which together delivered 37 separate schemes in the revised road
programme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Who'll gain what from the tax changes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
couple
with two incomes:
AS both are earning there will be two increases in personal allowances as well
as the increased married couple's allowance.
With the reduction in tax rates their overall benefit will be around #400.
Running two cars will be more expensive as well as the cost of smoking, if they
indulge.
They can continue to save through Peps and Tessas.
Low-earning couple with baby:
THE fof benefit by more than 3% should help as family credit is not taxable.
They may be able to take advantage of the inreased allowance for child care
allowing the mother to look for work.
The income tax changes will help the low earner and should ensure that tax at
only the 20% rate is paid.
Unemployed couple with children:
THE uprating of benefits should help on a general basis.
It is hoped the changes announced prior to the Budget for the long term
unemployed as well as the reductions in Employers National Insurance
contributions could open the way back to work.
Married couple on a pension:
THE increase in allowances and reductions in tax rates will help considerably
and, if they have money invested in the bank or building society, the reduction
of tax on interest to 20% will be very welcome.
The increase asset threshold when calculating who pays for residential care
will go some way to relieving worries about the future.
Married couple with two children:
WITH no additional relief on their mortgage unless interest rates fall in the
near future, any benefits will come from the income tax changes.
They will get the full benefit of the reduction in tax rates, amounting to some
#340.
No changes in airport duty at least means no added bills at holiday time.
Single man with own car:
WHILE the single man will benefit from the increase in personal allowances, the
extension of the lower rate band and the 1p reduction in the basic rate, making
him better off to the tune of #184, he will have to pay more for his motoring
and, if he is a smoker, there's the additional 15p on a packet of twenty
cigarettes.
Overall he still be better off by around #120.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Retailers see signs of hope</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BTHE British Retail Consortium, which represents 90% of the UK retail industry,
last night hailed the Budget as ``good and prudent'' for shops and their
customers.
Its director-general, Mr James May, said: ``Retailers will see positive
incentives in the Chancellor's proposals and consequently will expect customer
confidence to receive a significant boost.''
Mr Gerald Weisfeld, chairman of the recently-opened Weisfelds department store
in Glasgow, said the Budget would have a neutral effect, bordering on the
positive.
However, he believed the Chancellor could have done more to resurrect the
``feel-good'' factor, by cutting taxes more heavily or by stimulating the
housing market.
Mr Weisfeld, who founded the nationwide chain of WEW discount stores from a
single clothing shop in Glasgow nearly 25 years ago, said: ``I would have liked
to have seen 2p off (the basic rate of income) tax. However, we have got a
penny off tax so we have to be thankful for that.''
Referring to the Chancellor's failure to do anything to kick-start the housing
market, Mr Weisfeld said: ``I think everybody would have benefited. The
feel-good factor would have benefited greatly from something to boost that
particular area.''
Mr Weisfeld believed the Budget would be seen internationally as conservative,
paving the way for a reduction in UK interest rates and further tax cuts.
The British Retail Consortium said decreases in personal taxation, the freeze
in excise duties on wine and beer, the cut in duty on spirits, and the increase
in resources for town-centre security were among the measures which retailers
had pressed for and warmly welcomed.
The consortium was thankful that there had been no increase in VAT.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>House builders `disappointed'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142928</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE building industry felt let down last night by what it described as a lack
of direct action to help first-time buyers.
The chief executive of George Wimpey, Mr Joe Dwyer, said it was
``disappointing''.
However, he said that the general tax reduction would mean that real,
disposable income should rise for the first time in years and thereby help
confidence.
Mr Dwyer also suggested that there was still time for a Christmas present for
the industry.
``It would be of further assistance to the housing sector if interest rates
were reduced before Christmas,'' he said.
``As the Chancellor himself pointed out, houses are more affordable now than
they have been for a long time, so now is a good time to buy.''
From the selling sector, Mr Donald MacLellan, divisional sales director of
General Accident Property Services, said: ``There is really nothing at all that
would do anything to stimulate the market place.
"It would have been nice to have seen a bit more on the Miras tax relief and an
increase in the threshold for stamp duty.''
Only last week, the housing market in Scotland was described as remaining
``resolutely flat'' by Mr Fred Goodwin, chief executive of the Clydesdale Bank.
Writing in The Herald, he said it was unrealistic to expect the Chancellor to
restore Miras to its former levels, even temporarily.
``What seems more realistic would be some form of enhanced Miras relief for
first-time buyers,'' Mr Goodwin  said.
He added that such relief would be seen as a clear sign from the Chancellor
that there was ``still support for the notion of private home ownership''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Landfill tax `will act as catalyst'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE, Environment Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142929</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE confirmation of a landfill levy came as no surprise to the industry since
it was first signalled by the Chancellor last November.
Mr Brian Fitzgerald, CBI Scotland's vice-chairman and the chairman of its
environment committee, was pleased that the Government had heeded its
representations to make the tax weight-based - #7 a tonne - rather than based
on value.
He predicted it would encourage the industry to consider new methods of waste
minimisation.
Friends of the Earth Scotland, however, criticised Mr Kenneth Clarke for not
making the tax cover all forms of waste disposal.
Dr Richard Dixon, FoE Scotland's head of research, described the landfill tax
as a ``missed opportunity''.
``It will have some positive effects, but also some negative effects by making
incineration more attractive, which we are opposed to for a number of reasons.
If he had imposed a waste tax, he would have encouraged the recycling of
material instead of making people dispose of it in a different way,'' he said.
He added that landfill was still relatively cheap in Scotland compared to parts
of Britain like London. A charge of #7 a tonne in London would be barely
noticed, whereas in Scotland it might well double the cost of landfill.
Mr Ian Wakelin, managing director of UK Waste, one of the country's largest
environmental service companies, said the landfill tax would act as ``an
important catalyst for waste minimisation, recovery, and recycling in the UK''.
``By setting the level of tax at #7 per tonne for most waste, the Chancellor
has dramatically raised the cost of waste disposal by landfill. Waste producers
now have a financial as well as environmental incentive to seek ways to reduce
the amount of waste which they send to landfill,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lenders let down by inaction on home front</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORTGAGE lenders expressed disappointment at Mr Clarke's refusal to stimulate
the depressed housing market and help the UK's 16 million homeowners.
Mr Clarke confirmed that mortgage interest relief would remain unchanged at the
present 15% on a #30,000 loan.
He said he had considered carefully the case for special measures to revive the
housing market but believed that none of the ``affordable proposals'' would
make any difference.
An average mortgage costs #180 a month, a figure which was much cheaper than
renting, making house purchases more affordable now than for years, Mr Clarke
said.
``I remain convinced that what the housing market needs above all is steady
growth and low inflation.''
But the Building Societies' Association said it was disappointed no specific
measures for the housing market were announced, although it welcomed the news
that interest from savings would now be taxed at 20% for basic rate taxpayers.
``It is hoped that the cut in basic-rate tax will assist the feel-good factor
and help rebuild confidence, which would in turn encourage households to take
advantage of the current excellent affordability of home ownership,'' said
director general Adrian Coles.
The UK's biggest mortgage lender, the Halifax Building Society, expressed
disappointment that Mr Clarke chose not to abolish stamp duty on house sales.
It agreed that house prices and interest rates were low, but abolishing stamp
duty would have helped confidence - an important factor in the housing market.
Peter Birch, chief executive of the Abbey National, the UK's second biggest
mortgage lender, said: ``It is too early to predict a return of the
``feel-good'' factor but this Budget should boost optimism, which will feed
through to the housing market.
``By being prudent, the Budget has also left the way open for a base rate cut
in the months ahead.''
Birmingham Midshires Building Society said it regretted Mr Clarke had chosen
not to help the housing market.
Chief executive Mike Jackson said: ``The Government's commitment to homeowners
remains extremely muted.
``The Chancellor has failed to recognise that by supporting the housing market
he would be providing a catalyst for growth by boosting employment and high
street spending, rather than opting for small tax cuts.
``We would repeat our calls for the Government to follow the lead of the
housing market and cut interest rates.''
The UK's leading home removal company, Pickfords, called the Budget a ``wait
and see'' one for home-owners.
``Pickfords is disappointed that he has taken no direct measures to stimulate
the housing market, such as abolishing stamp duty,'' it said.
``We are, however, pleased he has decided to freeze Miras rather than pursue
the Government's long-term policy of reducing it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Muted welcome for #1bn prescription for NHS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID, Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142931</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STEPHEN Barrett, chairman of the Institute of Health Services Management in
Scotland, said any increase in the the NHS budget was always welcome, but
pointed out that the impact would depend on what proportion went to Scotland.
The Scottish health service allocation last year topped #4000m for the first
time, but a growth rate of only 0.6% over four years was officially predicted
at that time.
``A billion pounds is only a small proportion of the overall UK health
budget,'' said Mr Barrett.He said there was a myth about management costs in
the NHS - one of the targets for trimming set out by the Chancellor.
The British Medical Association's Scottish council accused the Government of
undermining the stability of pay in the NHS by insisting that any salary
increase for doctors would have to be funded by increased efficiency.
``Doctors already work excessive hours every day of the week in the NHS,'' said
a spokesman. ``Asking them to do more may increase the number of patients
treated but it won't save the Government any money.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>PFI spells delight for Scots Secretary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND is set to benefit from more than #2bn of major investment over the
next three years under the Government's Private Finance Initiative.
This was stated last night by Scots Secretary Michael Forsyth when he responded
to the Chancellor's Budget reference to a #45m water project which will provide
sewerage treatment facilities for Inverness and Fort William.
Around 51,000 people will benefit from the North of Scotland project which is
the first Build, Own, and Operate scheme of its type.
Potential contractors due to submit tenders by December 5. It is hoped to let
the contract by the end of March.
Mr Forsyth was delighted the Scottish Office was one of the three leading UK
departments pioneering the PFI ``with a major boost to capital spending and
investment in Scotland's infrastructure''.
He added: ``Our success so far in identifying and bringing forward projects
demonstrates the major contribution that the PFI will make to delivering high
quality services in Scotland.''
Major projects being considered include the new Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh -
estimated capital value #140m - M6/A74 completion (approximately #100m),
Hairmyres Hospital (#60m), and Law Hospital (#115m).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cautious approach does little for jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS ROBERT POWELL and CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRY's reaction to the Budget was mixed. CBI director general Adair Turner
said his organisation was pleased the Chancellor appeared to have limited tax
cuts to reductions in spending and resisted the temptation to go for excessive
tax cuts.
Public borrowing remained higher than the CBI would have liked, ``but we are
satisfied it still appears to be on a downward path''.
CBI Scotland chairman Andrew Cubie said the Chancellor's comparative
inattention to the provision of national infrastructure was disappointing.
Scottish Chambers of Commerce said the Budget would do little to boost business
or create jobs and nothing to encourage construction or tourism.
Mr Peter Dunn, acting director-general of Scottish Chambers of Commerce, said
the Chancellor should have refrained from cutting taxes and invested more in
training, business support and education.
``This is undoubtedly a Budget with slightly more good news than bad news, but
my fear is that it will do little to help businesses and virtually nothing to
create additional jobs.''
He said the 3.5p a litre rise in fuel prices would discriminate against
businesses in remote rural areas and the speeding up of the Private Finance
Initiative, which aims to finance public works with private capital, offered
``too little, too late'' to be of any real help to the construction sector.
Mr Dunn said the decision to reverse last December's increase in duty on
spirits was one of the few bright spots. He said the 27p a bottle cut would
bring ``good cheer to the Scotch whisky industry''.
His main hope was that there would be an early cut in interest rates. ``This
will have a more positive effect on business,'' he said.
Mr Geoff Runcie, chief executive of Glasgow Chamber of Commerce, dismissed the
Budget as ``pretty mediocre''.
``In all, a bland Budget without any fire - a cautious Chancellor acting under
some pretty tight restraints,'' he said.
The engineering industry in Scotland were bitterly disappointed.
The Budget had done ``absolutely nothing'' to encourage the investment culture
in plant and equipment, nor moved towards encouraging long-term investment with
allowances for longer term investors.
Mr Howard Jordan, chief executive of Scottish Engineering, said the Chancellor
had made no attempt to support industry. He had spoken of small businesses
being the seed corn of future prosperity but done nothing to nurture its
growth.
``The tax on fuel will punish the engineering industry in Scotland, which is a
major transporter of goods by road,'' Mr Jordan said.
``As Scottish companies are further from their major European markets, this is
going to be an unwelcome burden.''
TUC general secretary John Monks said that the Budget contained a hidden agenda
of big public sector job cuts. Proposed reductions in the funding of the civil
service would mean a loss of some 26,000 jobs and could hit Customs officers'
attempts to stem drug smuggling and Inland Revenue officers' fight against tax
evasion, and reduce public safety.
Mr John Sheldon, general secretary of the National Union of Civil and Public
Servant, said ``tens of thousands'' of jobs were at risk and there would be a
deterioration in every area from coastguards to social security plus longer
queues for passports and delays for driving tests.
Mr Alan Jinkinson, general secretary of Britain's largest union, Unison, said
the Budget was ``the most short-sighted policy since the Trojans let the horse
in''.
It left people more heavily taxed than they were when the Government took
office - and public services were being devasted to pay for tax cuts. Local
government would be particularly hard hit with a #4bn shortfall.
Health spending needed to increase by 2% a year above inflation just to keep
pace with rising costs and instead the Government planned just a 0.6% increase
next year and 0.1% for the following two. Added to the 17% cut in capital
spending on new hospitials, this was devastating news for the NHS, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Margo Gollogly, Personnel clerk, 42</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mrs Margo Gollogly, 42, a personnel clerk at Asda's Parkhead Forge supermarket
in Glasgow, is married to Alan, 58, a panel beater in Coatbridge who earns
about #14,500. The couple live in Kentallen Road, Barlanark, Glasgow, with two
of their three daughters aged 12 and 10. Margo, who has worked at the store
since it opened in 1988, earns #7500 per annum.
Budget hopes: Margo would have appreciated any reduction in income tax, but
says the Chancellor could have helped families like hers in other, ways, for
example by cutting the cost of road tax and petrol. As a smoker, she firmly
believes that the price of cigarettes has been increased too often and by too
much, and claims the Government already earns enough from taxation on tobacco
without increasing it further.
Budget reaction: Margo dismissed the 1p income tax cut as almost irrelevant and
claimed the Budget would provide no help for most working class people. She was
very disappointed by the increase on cigarettes and said the 15p rise was much
more than those imposed in previous budgets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Colin Hutcheon Teacher, 42</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142935</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colin Hutcheon, 42, Principal Teacher of Music at Broxburn Academy, West
Lothian, earns about #23,500 a year. He lives in a three-bedroom semi-detached
house in Sheriff's Park, Linlithgow, with his wife Rosemary, also 42, and sons
Nick, 16, and Joel, 13. His wife is a social worker and earns about #11,000 per
annum. The family have an outstanding mortgage of about #30,000.
Budget hopes: As a homeowner, Colin would have welcomed a reduction in interest
rates and did not want to see an elimination of taxation relief on mortgages
but, as a teacher, is more concerned about public expenditure. He would welcome
anything which would enhance his son's employment prospects and would like
student grants restored to previous levels.
Budget reaction: Colin said he was very disappointed with the Budget, which he
described as a Budget for people who were in employment and relatively well off
and contained no comfort for the poor or homeless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sharon Robertson Midwife, 32</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mrs Sharon Robertson, 32, a staff midwife in the labour ward at the Southern
General Hospital, Glasgow. She is married to Brian, 35, a psychiatric nurse at
Parkhead Hospital. The couple live at Glenfarg Road, Burnside, and have two
daughters, Fiona, six, and Mairi, four. Sharon earns #16,900 per annum, while
her husband receives #15,000.
Budget hopes: Sharon would have liked to have seen the Chancellor put more
money into health care, because a lot of new equipment is paid for by staff
fund-raising and gifts rather than from the Government or NHS trusts. She would
have liked more investment in education. She said her eldest daughter had to
wait for books because there were not enough to go round the class.
Budget reaction: Sharon was ``quite happy'' with the extra #1bn allocated to
the health service but emphasised it would probably mean a very small amount to
each individual health area. She claimed that, with the tax cut and increases
on petrol and road tax, the Chancellor had given on one hand and taken away
with the other. While she recognised many people would welcome an income tax
reduction she said she would be happy to pay an extra 1p in the #, because it
would have ``no significant effect'' on pay, but could be used to provide more
funds for health and education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Move of great interest to retired</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAVERS are one of the main beneficiaries of the Budget through the lower 20%
rate of tax on savings income, specifically interest from banks and building
societies, purchased life annuities, interest from gilts, corporate bonds, and
authorised unit trusts.
The new rate only applies to basic rate taxpayers and will take effect from the
new tax year next April. Those subject to higher rate tax will still pay 40% on
their interest income.
Savings income will be counted as the ``top slice'' of income. For example,
someone with #5000 of taxable income after allowances of which #500 is interest
income will pay 20% tax on the first #3900, 24% on the next #600, and 20% on
the top slice of #500 interest income.
Basic rate taxpayers will not need to take any action. Tax will continue to be
deducted at source as at present. Non-taxpayers receiving income already taxed
will be able to claim the 20% back.
However, many elderly people dependent on small pensions and interest on
savings will not see any difference because they are already non-taxpayers or
20% taxpayers. But they will no longer have to claim back the present 5% excess
on income taxed at source.
The tax cut will make it even more worthwhile for retiring members of an
occupational scheme to take the maximum lump sum allowed from their pension
benefits because a purchased annuity or interest generated by the lump sum will
be taxed at a lower rate than pension payments.
The Chancellor said the intention of the move was to reduce income tax for
those with modest savings, reward and encourage saving, and make further
progess towards a basic rate of 20%.
The reduction will go some way towards offsetting the decline in income which
savers have suffered with the general decline in interest rates in recent
years. It will also take the edge off the likely reduction in interest rates
which is widely expected shortly and mitigate the effect of lower interest
rates on annuities.
The move will help building societies which derive much of their finance from
savers. The encouragement to savers will help their cash inflow thus enabling
them to be more competitive on mortgages. However, wholesale money markets are
a more important source of finance for many societies, particularly the larger
ones.
Mr Adrian Coles, director general of the Building Societies Association, said:
``This change now makes deposit based savings more attractive. It will assist
those mortgage lenders which raise their funds primarily from retail sources,
so both building society savers and borrowers should benefit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Albert MacKay, Hotelier, 43</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Albert MacKay, 43, and his wife Marian, 49, have run the seven-bedroom Guinach
House hotel near Aberfeldy, Perthshire, for the past six years and live there
with their son, Bert, 12.The hotel has an annual turnover of between #100,000
and #130,000. The couple take very little income from the hotel, ploughing the
profits back into the business.
Budget hopes: A reduction in the 17.5% rate of VAT paid by customers on
accommodation and meals would have lead to an increase in trade. A similar
reduction in VAT paid by hoteliers on all sales would have reduced costs which
would be passed on to customers. Albert said he would welcome a reduction in
duty on alcohol. A drop in interest rates would also improve the profitability
of the business.
Budget reaction: Albert was very disappointed that there was no reduction in
VAT. This, he said, was the biggest outlay he had to make and paying 17.5% to
the taxman every quarter often made him question whether the effort he put into
his business was worth it. He was pleased that duty had been reduced on spirits
by 4% and frozen on beer and wine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Robert Hynd, Director, 40</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Robert Hynd, 40, is company secretary and a director of Magnum Power plc, a
young, growing company which earlier this week moved from Coatbridge to new
#1.1m premises in Livingston, where it employs 45 people. The company designs
and produces Built-In Uninterruptable Power Supplies, which protect computers
and other electronic equipment from electrical failures or surges.
Budget hopes: Robert would have been happy to forgo tax cuts in favour of a
reduction of base rates by at least one point. He would like to have seen the
Chancellor improve the climate for investment. He had hoped the Chancellor
would do little with indirect taxation, claiming a change in the headline VAT
rate would be ``entirely wrong'' because a stable background is vital.
Budget reaction: Bob described the 1p cut in the basic rate of income tax as
politically motivated and said the Chancellor seemed not to have fulfilled any
of his hopes. The Budget was ``mildly reflationary'' and might allow a modest
decrease in base rates, but not of the significance he was looking for.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John Dower Student, 24</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
John Dower,24, is studying journalism on a one year post-graduate diploma
course at Glasgow Caledonian University. Originally from Wimbledon, London, he
graduated in English Literature from Glasgow University last year and lives in
Holyrood Crescent in the West End of Glasgow with his landlady and her
boyfriend.
Budget hopes: John has no taxable income so is unconcerned, from a personal
viewpoint, about income tax changes in the budget, but concedes changes would
affect his family, on whom he relies heavily for financial assistance,
particularly as the Student Awards Agency for Scotland has not yet decided if
he is to receive a #2200 grant and his father was recently made redundant. He
would like to see a reduction in the price of cigarettes but admitted that
smokers.
Budget reaction: John thought the Budget was very dull and said he was
``gutted'' by the 15p increase on cigarettes. He would also have liked to have
seen something done about VAT on domestic fuel. The Budget, he said, was a
clear indication that there would be another before the next General Election
``because there was no major giveaway''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joanne  McAuley Manager, 34</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Joanne McAuley, 34, of Broomhouse Street South in Edinburgh, is Support
Services Manager (head receptionist) with the Forestry Commission at its
headquarters in the city's Corstorphine Road. She earns #14,000 per annum. She
is single, with no children.
Budget hopes: A reduction in income tax rates - ``we would all like to have
more money in our pockets'' - but not short-term cuts at the expense of public
services and not if such cuts would lead to increases in the Council Tax. She
would also have liked to have seen the Chancellor improve the lot of doctors
and nurses ``because I think they are being sold down the river''.
Budget reaction: Joanne claimed the 1p tax cut would do nothing for jobs or the
economy - ``I think the tax cut is just a short term measure in the hope of
winning the next election'' - but was pleased that a significant amount of
money was being invested in health. She also admitted that, as a smoker, the
increase in the price of cigarettes to almost #3 would be enough to make her
try to kick the habit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>David Leslie Architect, 43</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142942</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Leslie, 43, a partner in Wellwood Leslie Architects of Broughty Ferry,
Dundee, and a former Grand Slam-winning Scottish international rugby player.
His architect's practice, which employs 12 people, works for a variety of
housing association, private housing, health care, education, and industrial
customers. Mr Leslie, who lives in Broughty Ferry with his wife, a 13 year-old
son, and two daughters aged 11 and nine, declined to reveal his annual income.
Budget hopes: From a personal point of view, David would have liked to have
seen a significant reduction in the level of VAT on domestic fuel, as opposed
to a cut in income tax, and believes this would be particularly valuable to the
elderly. From a professional point of view, he would have welcomed a reduction
in VAT in the construction industry, but particularly for property owners
building extensions and making alterations. This, he said, would have benefited
charities in particular. VAT is zero-rated on new house builds but, he pointed
out, is levied at 17.5% on extensions and alterations.
Budget reaction: David said his main concern was that the Chancellor had missed
an opportunity ``to make society a bit fairer''. He could have reduced tax on
domestic fuel instead of cutting the basic rate of tax by 1p, which would
benefit people only marginally. ``Perhaps the Chancellor doesn't realise that
the tax on domestic fuel is not popular and not terribly fair,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stewart Whiteford Farmer, 44</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stewart Whiteford, 44, Wester Rarichie Farm, Nigg, is livestock convener with
the National Farmers' Union of Scotland. He has a ``variable'' income between
#20,000 to #40,000. Son and daughter both students at Aberdeen University.
Budget hopes: Lower interest rates, to offset cost of expanding business with
bank loans. Accelerated depreciation on buildings vehicles and machinery.
Reduced duty on fuel. Higher rate of Hill Livestock Compensatory Allow-ances.
As grower of malting quality barley would like to see reduction of rates of
excise duty on Scotch whisky. Opposed to income tax cuts if they are offset by
increases in VAT.
Budget reaction: Stewart was pleased that the duty on whisky had been reduced,
but said this cut was about all there was to welcome. He said he was devastated
by the increase in fuel costs, because he uses his car a lot for business and
estimated that the 3.5p per litre increase meant a 7% increase in his fuel
costs. He was also disappointed that the Chancellor had apparently done nothing
with cattle allowances and said: ``I wasn't enamoured by the 1p tax cut
because, as I expected, there are increases elsewhere.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bob Harvie Pensioner, 75</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95 </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142944</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Retired schoolteacher Bob Harvie, 75, who taught mathematics in Lanarkshire
schools, lives with his wife, Freda, 58, in an old schoolhouse in Coronation
Street, Carstairs Junction, which they previously rented from the local
authority and now own. The couple have two sources of income - Bob's state
pension of #105 per week, which includes a dependence allowance for his wife
who has not worked during their married life, and his superannuation pension of
about #100 a week. Budget hopes: Bob said pensioners have not shared in the
general increase in living standards in Britain and would have welcomed an
increase of about #7 per week for married couples. Bob and Freda heat their
seven-room house with oil central heating and estimate that their annual bills
amount to #700, so would have been delighted to see a reduction in VAT on
domestic fuel. Bob also said that pensioners received a #10 Christmas bonus in
the late 1970s and were still receiving #10 despite the fact that this would be
worth as much as #100 now.
Budget reaction: Bob said that, generally speaking, he did not believe people
in similar circumstances to his would see any change in their standard of
living. ``The Government's policy seems to be every man for himself with a
safety net for the poverty stricken but that should not be needed. That theory
implies people need handouts for bare subsistence and personally I find that
approach distateful.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Highway robbery' on the roads</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE decision to cut a swathe through the Government's major roads programme and
replace it with five privately-financed road schemes worth #500m were widely
condemned as ``highway robbery'' yesterday.
In all, two-fifths of new roads - a total of 77 motorway and trunk road schemes
- have been withdrawn, representing a 33% cut in a programme which will now be
worth #8.2bn.
The RAC described the announcement as ``highway robbery'' and added that the
environmental implications of scrapping bypasses was ``frightening''.
Five new private finance-built road schemes, built under the Private Finance
Initiative, are not expected to start before 1997-98.
Last night, speculation was growing that the proposed M74 extension through
Glasgow, which was recently granted planning permission and is estimated to be
worth #100m, might be one of the five new private schemes an-nounced, but not
detailed by the Chancellor.
Friends of the Earth Scotland pointed out that the A74/M74 scheme through the
South of Scotland, the first to be carried out under the PFI, had shown that
other schemes risked costing the taxpayer more in the end of the day.
The Freight Transport Association also said the road cuts were ``highway
robbery'', as congestion for tax-paying road-users would mean ``standstill and
deliver''.
``He is allowing industry to be choked by congestion. The latest roads cuts are
almost a dead end - bad for the economy and bad for the environment,'' said Mr
Adam Wurf, a spokesman for the FTA.
``The nation has a clear and growing transport problem that wastes time and
money and causes environmental pollution. We need a multi-faceted solution -
investment in public transport, comprehensive utilisation of the existing roads
infrastructure, use of rail where appropriate.''
``But in the absence of anything else we have a clear need for improving the
roads system where it presently pinches together with continuity of by-pass
building,'' he added.
Meanwhile, Mr Richard Diment, Director of the British Road Federation, said:
``Although the Private Finance Initiative is to be welcomed it is clear that it
has been unable to replace more than a small proportion of the money lost to
road investment through public expenditure cutbacks.''
He added: ``The Chancellor has ignored the warnings from industry and business
that without an improved road system Britain's long term economic success is at
risk.''
Mr Neil Greig, the AA's roads and environment officer in Scotland, said: ``The
Chancellor has to realise that the UK economy remains roads-based and trying to
replace a national roads programme with a few privately financed roads is not
going to fill the gap. It simply defers big Treasury bills until after the
General Election.''
Meanwhile, Mr Brian Fitzgerald, vice-chairman of CBI Scotland, said his
organisation was positive about the principle of PFI, but disappointed that the
Chancellor was not pushing it through faster.
He added that it was significant that when originally announced, the PFI was
intended to be ``additional'' to public sector procurement. Yesterday, the
Chancellor had referred to it as being a replacement, he said.
</TEXT>
