<HEADLINE>Shaken, but not stirred, by our Mr Moneypenny</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ruth Wishart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE all would-be conjurers Kenneth Clarke knows that you don't extract the
bunny from the topper before the audience is properly warmed up.
He understands too that there must be a few teasers preceding the big event and
that a judicious amount of sleight of hand is necessary if you don't want
anyone spotting the fact that you've substituted last year's firm and binding
predictions for a completely revised set.
Yet on the evidence of yesterday he shouldn't hold his breath for admittance to
the Magic Circle.
A modest penny off the basic rate was bound to be anti-climactic after the
frenzy of speculation. Not least on the benches behind him, where the
arithmetic currently most of concern to his colleagues is how much of a
majority they need in the bank to have a hope of retaining their current
employment.
In the light of yesterday's modest largesse, they now have to hope that they
have a sizeable number of non-smoking, whisky-loving constituents running
around in gas-powered vintage cars with aged parents about to will them
something worth around the #200,000 mark.
So Mr Moneypenny's finale proved something less than a showstopper. And the
trouble with his build-up was that there are only so many times you can try to
pull off the same tricks without the audience getting the hang of how they're
being swizzed.
Not a good idea, for instance, to keep employing lines like ``efficiency
gains''. Too many people now know that's a pretty long-winded phrase which
freely translates as cuts.
As in: ``Thanks to the efficiency gains made by your local hospital we are
happy to announce that the waiting time for your operation has been slashed to
just three months. You will be entered on this fast track waiting list just as
soon as we can find a consultant to give you an initial appointment.''
In fairness, Mr Clarke has promised another billion of public funds into the
NHS, and investment via this year's sexiest policyspeak, the Private Finance
Initiative.
It was also good to hear that school budgets would get a much needed cash
injection, just strange that this was the only brief mention of the twin
engines of any genuinely modern, competitive economy - education and training.
In fact, young people featured in this Budget largely in terms not of what they
might get to enhance their future prospects, but in how they might be
penalised. Curious, too, to understand why one of the few specific mentions of
cuts in the social security budget, which will total #5000m in all, was that of
restricting housing benefit to the under 25s.
It seems the Government continues to cherish the illusion that there is an army
of young people wilfully and unnecessarily leaving home and thereafter
acquiring ideas above their housing station.
The reality, so far as most people can detect, is that those young people in
caring homes are so reluctant to to out into the ever chillier economic winds
that their parents cannot get shot of them. Those in homes where they are at
risk, or not able to be given adequate care and nourishment, are those who make
up the increasing number of young homeless who do not require any more fiscal
kicks in the teeth.
So far as ambushes by indirect taxation are concerned, it would be nice to have
a bit of frankness. Tobacco costs are not rising because uncle Kenneth is
fretting about our lungs, and fuel duties have very little to do with a
greening of the Major Cabinet.
As for whisky! The Chancellor, casting around for a quick fix a few months
back, stuck a hasty 26p on a bottle, trying to balance a leaky budget.
It backfired spectacularly actually losing the Treasury over #50m in
revenue.Thus yesterday's cut of 27p. Net gain to whisky industry: 1p on the
bottle.
Doubtless they are grateful for mercies, even if they come in distressingly
small measures.
</TEXT>
