<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>PRUDENT BID FOR GROWTH</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142947</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke claimed yesterday that he had produced a Budget that
put Britain on course to be the enterprise centre of Europe, creating more jobs
and generating the greater wealth and prosperity in which all could share.
He told the Commons that business could flourish in a secure climate of low
borrowing, low taxation, deregulation and free trade through a Budget which
controlled overall public spending while shifting more money towards schools,
hospitals and the police.
The Chancellor, who sipped malt whisky and water throughout his 68-minute
speech, said he had achieved what he described as a ``hat trick'' because the
Government had followed a consistent economic policy. ``Only we have clear
objectives and only we know how to achieve them,'' he insisted.
He said that the Budget put the Government on the path to achieving borrowing
falling to zero, public spending falling below 40% of national income,
inflation below 2.5% and a 20% basic rate of income tax.
As a result of his Budget measures, a married couple with only one earner on
average earnings with two children would pay #190 less tax. Overall, their real
take-home pay after tax would rise by around #450 next year and they would be
#700 a year better off than they were at the time of the last election.
The Budget addressed the aspirations of the people of this country in an
economically and socially responsible way, he said.
Economy
Mr Clarke said that in 1994 the economy had grown by about 4%. This was
``fuelled by the success of British exporters overseas.''
Consumer spending was on an upward trend and he predicted it would grow further
in the next two years.
He said manufacturing investment had grown by 12% over the past year and he
forecast a growth rate of 2.75% this year and 3% for 1996.
Inflation remained on course to meet the Government's target of 2.5% or below
by the end of the present Parliament.
He said he expected the Public Sector Borrowing requirement to be #29bn in the
current financial year - #7bn less than last year and #16bn less than two years
ago.
Spending plans
Mr Clarke said: ``The share of national income taken by the state in public
expenditure must be reduced to below 40% if we are to remain competitive in
today's world.''
It was essential to give the private sector more room to generate jobs,
investment and wealth.
The Government was modernising welfare so it underpinned not undermined the
economy.
The Chancellor said ``the priority areas'' where spending would be increased
included the National Health Service which would receive an extra #1bn next
year.
In addition, patients would benefit from efficiency savings - including
reductions in NHS management costs - which would bring in an extra #650m to be
ploughed back into patient care.
Privately-financed projects would bring in a further #700m of extra investment
over the next three years. Mr Clarke emphasised that this would not in any way
undermine the principle of free health care at the point of delivery.
The Chancellor announced a rise in spending on schools of #878m.
``Parents will rightly expect local authorities to carry this funding through
to school budgets and they should ask their local authorities how this extra
money will be spent on their children.''
On crime, he said money was being provided for an extra 5000 police officers
over the next three years - on top of the 32,000 increase since 1979.
Plans also allowed for an extra 10,000 close-circuit television cameras in
towns around the country.
Mr Clarke said spectacular efficiency gains were being made in the running
costs of central government.
``The cash cost of Whitehall will be #860m lower in three years' time than it
is today.
Turning to social security, he said the Government expected growth in planned
spending of around 1% a year for the next three years.
He said this represented a reduction in growth from previous expectations that
social security spending would rise by more than 3% a year.
He said Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley was to announce a futher
intensive campaign against fraud.
He also would announce measures to ensure that asylum-seekers stopped receiving
social security benefit after an unfavourable adjudication.
Other moves included steps to close the gap between single parents benefit and
those paid to other families.
A package of measures to encourage people to go out to work included a further
increase in childcare allowance in family credit from #40 to #60 a week.
He said housing benefit would be restricted for the under-25s. ``It should not
be an inducement for young peple to leave their families before they need to.''
He pledged that the measures announced in his three Budgets so far would reduce
social security expenditure by #5bn a year by the end of the century
The Chancellor said that extra money could be found for the social security
budget ``by trimming back elsewhere''.
He said efficiency savings had been found in defence while the Government
maintained its ``commitment to a strong front line''.
On the Private Finance Initiative, Mr Clarke announced a ``huge'' new package
of privately financed roads - five new projects with a capital value totalling
#500m. Full bids were due on December 5 for the #45m water project in Inverness
and Fort William.
Mr Clarke said #250m had been made available for the third and fourth bidding
rounds for the Single Regeneration Budget Challenge Fund, to help areas
including inner cities.
Over #300m of Challenge Funding would be made available to speed the transfer
of deprived housing estates to housing associations and other private landlords.
Mr Clarke said that he expected total public spending this year to be down to
42% of national income.
Spending plans for 1996-97 will be cut by over #3bn, Mr Clarke said.
Taxation
Mr Clarke said that since 1979, the Government had shifted the tax burden away
from direct taxes on income and employment towards indirect taxes on spending
and consumption.
He announced that the new Landfill tax proposed last year, a charge on the
disposal of waste in tips and old quarries, would come into effect on October
1, 1996.
It would be charged at a standard rate of #7 per tonne and a lower rate of #2
for inactive waste.
He said money raised by this tax would allow for a cut in employers' National
Insurance contributions by a further 0.2% to 10% from April 1997.
This would cut the cost of employment by #500m, making it cheaper for
businesses to create new jobs.
Petrol
Tax on petrol and diesel would rise by 3!sp a litre.
Tax on super unleaded petrol would ill be increased by a further 4p next May.
Mr Clarke said that the Government wanted to encourage further use of gas used
in road vehicles and proposed reducing the duty on them by 15%, amounting to a
5.8p cut in road fuel gases.
He expected pollution from vehicles to fall over the next few years and said
the Government would use vehicle excise duty to encourage lower emissions. This
year, therefore, the cost of the tax disc for cars would rise by #5, although
Mr Clarke said he would freeze the rate for lorries for the sixth year running.
To make sure vintage and classic car enthusiasts were not penalised, the road
tax would be exempt on all cars and motorcycles over 25 years old taking
150,000 historic vehicles out of tax.
Mr Clarke said he would cut general betting duty by 1%. This would benefit the
betting industry as well as horse and greyhound racing.
This would come into force on March 1 next year if agreement could be reached
quickly.
The Chancellor said he would reduce pool betting duty by a further 5% from
December 3.
Tobacco, drinks
A packet of 20 cigarettes would go up by 15p.
There also would be an 8p increase on a 25g packet of pipe tobacco and a packet
of small cigars will cost 6p more.
Mr Clarke said there would be no increase on hand-rolling tobacco.
Of duties on alcohol, the Chancellor said he would freeze duty on beer and wine
adding: ``Tax at a share of the cost of a pint of beer is now the lowest for
over 20 years.''
Very strong cider was under-taxed compared with other drinks and he intended to
raise its duty by 8p a pint from next October but without disturbing the rate
for ordinary ciders.
High rates of duty at home had made it difficult for the Scotch whisky industry
to press ``their excellent case'' for lower duties in other countries, Mr
Clarke said.
Scotch was one of Britain's most important exports and spirits duty would
therefore be reduced by 4%, the equivalent to 27p off a bottle of whisky.
Mr Clarke ruled out a one-off windfall tax on the profits of the privatised
utilities.
``A windfall tax would damage investment and threaten the quality of customer
service,'' he said.
``I do not intend to introduce such a tax.''
He said there also would be no changes to the rules which allow the first
#30,000 of redundancy payments to free of tax.
Increases in insurance premium tax and air passenger duty also were rejected.
Mortgage interest relief would remain unchanged for the lifetime of this
parliament.
Mr Clarke said he agreed with many housing experts that none of the affordable
proposals to revive the housing market would make any difference.
The housing market needed steady growth and low inflation above all: ``That is
what this Budget delivers.''
Mr Clarke announced help for elderly people who need care in residential or
nursing homes.
He said benefits from a range of insurance policies which provide long-term
care benefits would be exempted from tax.
``We should encourage, not penalise, people who decide to take responsibility
for themselves.''
At present, people with assets worth less than #3000 did not have to contribute
towards their care from their capital, while people with assets worth more than
#8000 received no financial support from the Government.
Mr Clarke said from April the lower threshold would be more than trebled from
#3000 to #10,000 and the upper threshold doubled from #8000 to #16,000.
``That means people in residential care who have worked hard and saved will now
keep more of their own money.''
Pensions
He said the Inland Revenue would consult on the possibility of extending the
option to take a variable pension to members of occupational pension schemes.
This could provide a larger pension in later years when people are more likely
to need long term care in exchange for a smaller pension earlier on.
Mr Clarke said Pensioners Bonds had proved a very popular National Savings
product since their introduction two years ago and announced that the
qualifying age for purchasing these bonds would be reduced from 65 to 60.
Mr Clarke said the minimum period for saving under a SAYE scheme was to be
reduced from five years to three and the minimum contribution would be halved
to #5 a month. The holding period under profit sharing schemes will also be
reduced from five to three years.
Mr Clarke introduced a new tax relief enabling companies to grant share options
to their employees up to a limit of #20,000.
``These changes go further than ever before in creating a climate in which
employee share ownership can become the norm.''
Mr Clarke announced that the cap on increases in business rates will be reduced
from 10% to 7!s%. He added: ``Small businesses will get extra help. The maximum
increase for small properties will be 5% instead of 7!s%.''
Capital gains
On Capital Gains Tax, Mr Clarke said: ``We remain committed to abolishing
Capital Gains Tax when resources allow.''
He announced that Capital Gains Tax relief would be extended by reducing the
qualifying age from 55 to 50.
``It is the mark of a Government that backs enterprise,'' he said.
The Chancellor said inheritance was now an issue for Middle Britain, and he
confirmed it was the Government's intention to scrap inheritance tax as soon as
it could be afforded.
It was a myth that only the very rich paid the tax.
The tax-free allowance on inheritance tax would be increased from #154,000 to
#200,000, reducing by one third the number paying the tax.
Income tax
Mr Clarke said on income tax he would be increasing allowances for married
couples and people receiving related allowances by #70.
In order to relieve the burden on as many of the lower paid as possible he
would be increasing the basic personal allowance by #240 - #100 more than
indexation. As a result, more than 200,000 people would be kept out of tax
compared with the indexation of allowances.
On the top rate tax band of 40%, he said that he would be raising the threshold
by #1200 - #200 more than indexation.
He said he also would be increasing the 20% tax band by a further #700 - #500
more than indexation - bringing an extra one million people into that band.
Mr Clarke said about a quarter of all taxpayers, over six million people, will
pay tax on their income at just 20p in the pound.
Now he also proposed to reduce the rate of tax on all savings income for basic
rate taxpayers to just 20%.''
About 14 million savers would gain from this change, receiving an extra #5 from
every #100 invested.
Small companies rate of corporation tax would be cut to 24%.
Mr Clarke said: ``My final proposal in this Budget is therefore to reduce the
basic rate of income tax by one penny to 24p in the pound.
``These three steps - widening the 20p band, a 20p tax rate for savings' income
and 1p off the basic rate - move us much closer to a 20% basic rate of tax for
all income.
``We have a clear commitment ot the 20p basic rate. We believe in it and we can
achieve it.''
As a result of the Budget measures, a married couple with only one earner on
average earnings and with two children would pay #190 less tax.
Overall their real take home pay after tax would rise by around #450 next year,
Mr Clarke said.
Such a family would be #700 a year better off than they were at the time of the
last General Election.
Mr Clarke said: ``My Budgets of the last two years have kept us on the course
we said we would follow.
``We have cut taxes, we are cutting taxes and when we can afford it and when it
is in the interests of the economy we will cut taxes again. Good economics is
good politics.''
</TEXT>
