<DOCNO>GH951129-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CLARKE'S AMENDS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Angus Gawn, Aidan O'Carroll</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95 </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142948</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KENNETH CLARKE caused a furore in July when he withdrew capital gains tax
treatment for approved share option schemes following the Greenbury Report.
Contrary to his intentions, this change hit many employees in the middle and
lower income ranges rather than the ``fat cats'' against which the tax change
was supposedly targeted.
As a result, many employees found that they would pay income tax when they
exercised their share options. Previously they would have been liable to
capital gains tax, but could minimise the liability by claiming their annual
exemption of #6000 when the shares were sold. The exemption could be doubled if
shares were transferred to a spouse before sale.
The Chancellor effectively has reinstated the capital gains tax treatment for
share options granted after July 17, 1995, up to a limit of #20,000.
The new scheme must be approved by the Inland Revenue and there will be no
income tax to pay either when the options are granted or when they are
exercised.
The #20,000 limit applies to the market value of the shares at the time the
options are granted. The exercise price should not be less than the market
value at the date of grant, ie the shares should not be issued at a discount.
Many employees will be holding share options which were granted to them before
July 17, 1995, under the Revenue-approved rules. These options will continue to
be eligible for capital gains tax treatment, but any new options granted after
that date will be aggregated with the previous options to determine the new
#20,000 limit.
Broadly, all other conditions of approved share option schemes under the old
rules will continue to apply. In particular, options must be exercised between
years three and 10 after the date of grant.
The practical effect of this new relief is that the majority of employees who
are in approved share option schemes will continue to obtain capital gains tax
treatment when they sell their shares and they will not be liable to income tax
on the value of the shares when the options are exercised or the shares are
sold.
With the benefit of capital gains inflation relief and the annual exemption,
this will take many employees out of tax on their share options.
This sensible reinstatement of the previous tax advantages is designed to
motivate and reward employees by giving them a stake in the success of their
company without major tax penalty.
Business bonus
THE Chancellor made welcome announcements for owners of small business both on
capital gains tax and inheritance tax.
Currently, when an individual disposes of the whole or part of a business or of
shares in a personal company on retirement, full relief from capital gains tax
is given on the first #250,000 of gains, with an effective 20% tax rate
applying to gains between #250,000 and #1m.
Such relief is currently available to taxpayers who have reached the age of 55
or who retire earlier due to ill health. Under the Chancellor's proposal, the
qualifying age will be reduced to 50.
The reduction in the qualifying age will extend the benefit of the relief to
more entrepreneurs and shareholders in family companies who want to dispose of
their interests before the typical retirement age.
This also could have the effect of releasing capital to be reinvested in new
business projects.
Where the businessman holds only a proportion of the shares in his company,
inheritance tax can be a problem. In general, transfers of unquoted
shareholdings of 25% or less in trading companies will only attract 50%
business property relief.
From April 6, 1996, all unquoted shares in qualifying companies held for at
least two years will qualify for 100% business property relief.
Previously, there was a disincentive for owners of family businesses to reduce
their interest by passing on majority stakes to children and other relations.
These new provisions will now make this more attractive and at the same time,
with the increase of the inheritance tax threshold to #200,000, it should be
possible in the vast majority of cases to avoid inheritance tax altogether.
Special rules apply to transfers of agricultural assets but again, with careful
planning, 100% relief should be available to taxpayers in these circumstances.
Charity boost
CURRENTLY, donations which are given by employees to charities can be made
through a payroll giving scheme. For 1995-96 up to #75 per month or #900 per
annum could be given by employees. This means that the amount paid is treated
as a deduction from their taxable pay so that, in effect, tax relief is given
on the amount paid.
From April 6, 1996, it is proposed that the limits will be increased by
one-third to #100 per month or #1200 anually. The Chancellor says it is his
intention to promote further charitable giving and the increased limit is a
response to representations from a number of charities.
Almost 7500 separate employer schemes exist at present. Last year, #16m was
donated under the payroll giving scheme on which tax relief of #4m was given.
It is hoped that these figures will increase significantly.
The Chancellor also proposes to exempt charities from tax on certain investment
income. Charities already are exempt from tax on most types of income and this
exemption is extended by concession to include bank interest, interest on
dividents payable by building societies and interest on income arising from
property abroad. It is proposed to make this exemption statutory rather than
relying on a concession.
Making it simple
THE Chancellor has responded to widespread criticism that tax law is not only
lengthy and complex but is unnecessarily confusing.
He announced that a start will be made next year on a project to simplify tax
legislation for the benefit of businesses and taxpayers generally.
Key aims of the project are:
q To rewrite tax legislation in plain, user-friendly language.
q To redesign the framework of tax so that it will be easier to understand and
work with.
q To help taxpayers operate the new system of self-assessment
q To reduce compliance costs and improve service from the Inland Revenue.
The plan is to simplify tax legislation. It is not aimed at changing tax
policy. A detailed report is being prepared by the Inland Revenue for
presentation to Parliament next month.
Full consultation will be held with representative bodies and taxpayers to
ensure that taxpayers' concerns are taken fully into account.
While there will be substantial costs involved in rewriting the voluminous tax
legislation, the Government believes that the long-term benefits for business
and self-employed taxpayers, in particular, will substantially exceed those
costs.
Much of the existing legislation is virtually unintelligible even to experts.
Any meaningful progress towards simplification is to be welcomed.
No quick fix
WHILE the Chancellor announced his intention to simplify legislation a good
example of where this won't work concerns the legislation dealing with foreign
exchange.
For most companies, this legislation will come into effect from January 1,
1996, with the intention of bringing a measure of certainty to the tax
treatment of foreign exchange differences which will affect most companies
trading abroad.
However, you just have to look at over 30 pages of legislation which is
mind-bogglingly complex to appreciate that there will be no quick fix.
When dealing with matters financial, in particular all of the complicated
financial instruments and foreign exchange hedges, you cannot be simple. The
simpler you are, the easier it will be to get round the very provisions that
are introduced to try to prevent avoidance of tax.
At least the complex and lengthy legislation should ensure a degree of equity
and certainty to companies affected but finance directors are going to have to
make a number of decisions and elections to protect their company's position.
It is imperative that they understand the legislation - no easy task. Our
advice would be to get professional help as you can't afford to be caught out.
Gilts change
THE Chancellor had already announced changes in respect of gilts and bonds that
will come into effect from April 1996.
While private investors - individuals and trusts - will continue to pay tax on
interest on the present basis, there are new provisions which will affect
taxation on disposal of the investments.
Private investors holding more than #200,000 nominal value of most Government
gilts and company loan stock will be liable to pay income tax from April 6,
1996, on any gains realised. If losses are realised, these can be set against
other income in the year in which the loss arises.
Specific exemptions to these rules will apply in respect of two widely held
gilts - 3.5% 1999-2004 and 5.5% 2008-2012.
The gilts and bonds changes for companies will have a more significant impact.
For companies from April 1, 1996, all holdings of gilts, loan stocks, and
corporate debt will be within the new regime, and revised treatments will apply
to borrowings as well as investments.
Companies borrowing and investing in these forms of debt will be taxable on an
accruals basis, revaluing the capital amount and giving relief over time for
discounts, and taxing gains as they accrue rather than when they are realised.
In addition, there will be significant changes to the tax treatment of
companies' interest receipts and payments as these will be taxed or relieved on
an accruals basis, regardless of the date of payment or receipt.
While some complex provisions already contained in the legislation will
disappear for companies which will lead to a welcome simplification, as usual,
anti-avoidance legislation is likely to appear in some abundance.
There is still a lot of uncertainty left by the Chancellor in connection with
these new rules, but the by-word for companies will be watch out and make sure
that you understand the new rules.
Helping yourself
THE Chancellor announced that help would be given to those who make
arrangements to protect themselves against the financial losses caused by
personal misfortune. Under these proposals, certain insurance benefits paid in
the event of accident, sickness, disability, infirmity or unemployment will no
longer be taxable.
Previously the Inland Revenue did not collect tax where the insurance benefits
were provided in times of sickness, disability or unemployment to meet existing
obligations such as mortgage payments. Under the proposed measures, all such
insurance benefits will no longer be taxable provided the person entitled to
them is sick, disabled or unemployed. This will include top ups to earned
income when it is reduced as a result of sickness.
The exemption will not apply to insurance benefits that are taken into account
in computing trading and similar profits, nor where the premiums have received
tax relief. Sick pay, which is funded by way of a group policy taken out by the
employer, will remain taxable unless the employees have themselves contributed
to the premiums.
It is proposed that the measures will remove the obligation from insurers to
deduct tax from exempted benefits.
VAT relaxed
A POTPOURRI of changes in VAT legislation are included in the press releases
which accompanied the Chancellor's Budget statement. These include increasing
the registration limit for small businesses to #47,000 from midnight tonight
and increasing the deregistration threshold from #44,000 to #45,000.
The Chancellor also announced a package of measures to simplify VAT for
businesses trading with other EC member states. The most important measure is
the introduction of arrangements known as fiscal warehousing. This will allow
various commodities, including metals, foodstuffs and chemicals, to be traded
in a VAT-free regime. This system will be introduced from June 1, 1996.
From November 29 VAT will no longer be charged on business gifts costing #15 or
less. The limit was previously #10 and has been in place since 1973, therefore
the increase seems hardly generous but should cover the cost of a bottle of
whisky.
One area to be welcomed is the relaxation of the rules on what must be shown on
a VAT invoice. This relaxation had been applied previously but was withdrawn
due to faulty legislation. It is good to see that the former position for the
benefit of business is being restored.
</TEXT>
