<HEADLINE>Lilley freezes welfare benefits for lone parents</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAR-reaching changes to welfare aid for lone parents, leading to abolition of
special benefits, emerged in a radical shake-up revealed yesterday.
Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley said the changes - which include the
immediate freezing of one parent benefit and lone parent premium - would end
the system's discrimination in favour of lone parents.
Announcing details of the proposals following the Budget, Mr Lilley disclosed
long-term plans to phase out special benefit help for 1.5m lone parents.
At the same time he announced extra help with child care costs - and revealed
the minimum maintenance payments under the Child Support Act would be doubled.
Campaigners the Child Poverty Action Group warned that the end to special lone
parent benefits would hit the 2.3 million youngsters living in such families,
who often relied on the cash for food.
Mr Lilley revealed that regulations are to be introduced so that one parent
benefit - worth #6.30 a week to all single parents - will be built into Child
Benefit.
Similarly the lone parent premium, worth around #5.20 a week to people on
means-tested benefits, would be merged into the family premium element of
income support.
No-one receiving the benefits will lose out. But a review will be held every
year into the ``appropiate level of special support''.
``While I cannot prejudge what I will do in future years, my intention over
time is to narrow the gap between lone parent benefits and those which go to
couples.''
Other changes announced include:
q Introducing a pilot scheme from April 1997 to provide help with job search
and skills training for up to 25,000 lone parents.
q Increasing the childcare allowance in Family Credit from #40 to #60 - a move
calculated to help up to 10,000 families.
q Increasing the minimum maintenance payment under the Child Support Act from
#2.35 to #4.80.
The National Council for One Parent Families said lone parents faced
``significant extra costs'' to couples.
This would place extra pressure on families and risked driving them into deeper
poverty, added a spokeswoman.
She accused Ministers of failing to recognise that not all lone parents would
be able to go back to work quickly.
Elsewhere, Mr Lilley announced cuts in housing benefit for young people living
away from home. In future this will not cover the full cost of rent, but only
the cost of shared accommodation for under 25's. Parents who get housing
benefit for their children living at home will also be hit under the changes.
Shadow Social Security secretary Chris Smith said young people would be forced
into multi-occupancy housing, with all the potential health and fire hazards.
``The real way to reduce the Social Security budget is not hit young people,
single parents, and families but to get people back to work. This would cut the
benefits bill and increase our tax base.''
</TEXT>
