<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquiry concludes that Scotland requires to build a high growth, high wage economy Companies need more ambition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MAGEE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE successful take-up by Scottish industry of more technology and research
from the country's universities is more important than the much-lauded business
birthrate initiatives, Crawford Beveridge, chief executive of Scottish
Enterprise, conceded yesterday.
He and Professor Tom Johnston, president of the Royal Society of Edinburgh,
reported on findings from a year-long joint inquiry into how the Scottish
science research and development base could be made more commercialised.
Mr Beveridge said: ``Since I returned from the United States to do this job
five years ago, it has struck me that, despite our strong performance compared
to the UK over the last few years, the Scottish economy is still very fragile
and heavily dependent on inward investment.
``We need to expand the base and ambition of Scottish companies,'' he added.
``The first big issue to be tackled then was the business birthrate and the
agreed strategies now being implemented. The second, and in my view even more
important issue, is how we can bring the massive store of intellectual property
in our universities out into the industrial community as a key component of
building a high growth, high wage economy.''
The inquiry team has set itself a deadline of next spring to pull together a
draft long-term R&amp;D strategy for Scotland.
An action plan will be supported by academics and industrialists alike backed
by the financial sector, with the aim to link higher education home-grown
technology more closely to the country's commercial base.
Mr Beveridge said it wanted to create a ``virtuous circle'' to increase the
amount of research commercialised in Scotland whether by new or existing
companies.
``We all know that a high-wage economy must derive much of its competitive
advantage from the application of science and technology.''
Increased commercialisation had the potential, therefore, to improve the
overall economic development of Scotland, and also to benefit the academic
community by helping to ensure continued investment in high-quality research.
He added: ``Scotland already has the key component of commercialisation in
world-class research. However, all too often this research is developed,
manufactured and sold elsewhere.''
Professor Johnston said benefits would not be solely for Scotland as a whole.
It would also offer the potential for graduate recruitment from a strengthened
indigenous corporate base.
He reported on the success of a recent inquiry forum at Glasgow's Clydeport
building when senior decision-makers from across industry, finance and academia
were present.
Several emerging issues became evident. These included a clear need for better
dialogue, the mismatch between the strength of the science base and industrial
take-up, and a serious gap in funding provision.
The inquiry has emphasised no one magic formula for success. Nevertheless, it
was crucial the balance of transfer of research output to industrial take-up in
Scotland was greatly improved.
</TEXT>
