<HEADLINE>Algerian general killed in ambush</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142951</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
GUNMEN have assassinated an Algerian army general, a source close to the
security forces said today, in the first major attack since the presidential
polls 12 days ago.
General Mohamed Bouteghan died last night in the luxurious Hydra suburb of
Algiers by young men who had trailed him, the source added.
His killing came nearly eight hours after President Liamine Zeroual took the
oath of office in a ceremony attended by about 500 dignitaries, including army
leaders.
The general, who is believed to be the commander of Algeria's military coast
guard, was the most senior army officer to be killed in the country's four
years of civil strife.
Up to 50,000 people have been killed in Algeria's violence since early 1992
when authorities scrapped a general election which Islamic militants had been
poised to win.
The 59-year-old Bouteghan was shot dead in an exclusive neighbourhood where
several embassies are located on the heights overlooking the Algerian capital.
The source did not know why the general was in the suburb where many senior
officials and officers once lived before the violence erupted.
Many villas in Hydra are now closed as rich foreigners have left the North
African country and senior officials and officers moved to more secure
locations like the coastal resort of Sidi Fredj, outside Algiers, residents
said.
The killing came as a bitter reminder of the insecurity challenge still facing
Zeroual, himself a general.
Colonel Cherif Djelloul, army commander of Algiers district, was shot dead in
Algiers in last November while leading troops in an operation against
guerrillas.
Zeroual was elected on November 16 with more than 61% of the vote in a massive
turnout by Algerians despite militant threats to shoot voters or cut their
throats.
Diplomats and analysts have been expecting Muslim guerrillas to strike to show
they are still a force to be reckoned with despite the stunning elections
setback.
The Algerian newspaper Liberte said a union official, M'hamed Belabla, was
assassinated on Sunday in the Baraki suburb, south of Algiers. The newspaper
did not give details.
Zeroual yesterday vowed to continue fighting the rebels while offering to hold
a dialogue with political parties and to show leniency to fundamentalist
organisations.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
