<HEADLINE>Sir John's short answer to an important point</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142952</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Newcastle 13, Transvaal 38
THEY were the 12 minutes that probably signalled Gary Armstrong's Tyneside
rugby future. The Jed-Forest, Scotland, and British Lions scrum half came on
after 68 minutes when Newcastle were trailing 31-8. Almost immediately,
Newcastle lock John Dixon had driven over for a try to put the Tynesiders into
double figures.
The seconds that Newcastle's millionaire benefactor took later to answer a
simple question were more important.
Question to coach Rob Andrew: ``Would Newcastle's Scottish recruits be released
to play for district sides in the European championship if Newcastle also were
involved?''
``That's a good question,'' replied Andrew. Step in Sir John Hall. ``That's a
good question and a hypothetical question, and it's much too soon to say. We've
got more important things to worry about.''
Maybe so, but it's a question that the Scottish rugby hierarchy will want
answered before much more water has passed under the bridge over the River
Tyne. Back to the game.
Newcastle, with new signings Dean Ryan and Nick Popplewell on parade, Tony
Underwood and Doddie Weir watching on the sidelines, were no match for the
slick South Africans, but they did just enough to suggest that once Andrew has
completed his recruiting drive, then they may spring from their precarious
perch at the foot of the English second division.
Transvaal, fielding five Springboks, and a huge pack, opened the scoring after
six minutes with a try from fly-half Louis van Rensberg. Hans Pfluger converted.
After 30 minutes, Transvaal went further ahead with a try by the Springbok
hooker, James Dalton, after his own break and a return pass from fly half Louis
van Rensberg. Pfluger failed with the conversion.
Newcastle snatched a try five minutes before the interval when the ball shot
from the front of the lineout and hooker Neil Frankland pounced for the
touchdown. Rob Andrew sent the conversion attempt wide.
In the second half, Transvaal sneaked a try after six minutes when Philip
Schutte snatched a lineout ball and tumbled over unopposed for the touchdown.
Pflugler converted.
Andrew kept Newcastle in the hunt with a penalty after 53 minutes, but two
minutes later, Transvaal retaliated with a sparkling try by Jaco Louw.
The South Africans took a tapped penalty deep inside their own half, Van
Rensberg and Louw galloped upfield and Louw went over. Pflugler was on target
with the conversion.
Louw put Transvaal out of reach after 63 minutes with a try after a searing
break up the left touchline.
With 12 minutes to go Newcastle were awarded a penalty in front of the
Transvaal posts. Armstrong, who had been warming up on the sidelines, made his
Kingston Park debut, and Dixon drove over for the try.
In the final minute, Louw had his hat trick after yet another electrifying
break and again, Pflugler converted.
Newcastle - I McLellan; M Wilson, R Wilkinson, J Fletcher, G Childs; R Andrew,
G Robson; N Popplewell, N Frankland, P Van Zandvliet, F Mitchell, J Dixon, R
Arnold, S Cassidy, D Ryan. Replacements - G Armstrong, D Weir, P Belgian, A
Hetherington, B Adlington, D Holder.
Transvaal - H Pflugler; A Homan, J Mulder, C Scholtz, J Louw; L Van Rensburg, J
Adlam; I Hattingh, J Dalton, P Van Greuning, C Niemand, P Schutte, L Stewart, C
Roussouw, G Gouws.
Referee - J Fleming (Scotland).
SCORERS - Newcastle: Frankland 1t; Dixon 1t; Andrew pg. Transvaal: Louw 3t;
Dalton 1t; Schutte 1t; van Rensberg 1t; Pflugler 4c.
</TEXT>
