<HEADLINE>Betting duty cut may help lottery losses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOTH bookmakers and the pools companies have had to shed jobs because of the
impact of the national lottery.
To help reduce the damage, general betting duty is being cut by 1% to 6.75%
while pool betting duty will fall 6% to 26.5%.
The changes will reduce Exchequer income by about #100m in a full year.
Mr Mike Kershaw, managing director of Stanley Leisure, the largest of the
quoted pure gambling companies, said that the changes were too little and too
late. He had been hoping for a 2% reduction.
Stanley warned earlier this month that there could be a significant drop in
racing division profits.
Even harder hit has been Ladbrokes, which has been forced to make 500 people
redundant in racing activities, and in Vernons Pools, where turnover in the
first nine months was down 27%.
Mr Kershaw said that it would be difficult to split the 1% between the punter
and horse and greyhound racing as a !s% could be a difficult figure to
distribute when it comes into effect in March. The pool duty reduction comes
into effect in two stages.
Ladbrokes shares rose 2p to 151!sp, reversing an earlier loss.
</TEXT>
