<HEADLINE>A blast of air</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975142954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JEFF Green's television-inspired route from light engineering to stand-up
comedy was more straightforward than might first appear. It was also very
tiring, as he explains.
``I came out of university with an engineering degree and loads of debts, and
so to pay them off I took a sales job with British Oxygen, travelling around
the country convincing welders to buy oxygen and acetylene. I very quickly
realised that I'd made a big mistake, career-wise.''
He kept both disparate occupations going, in the process almost dying from
sleep-deprivation. ``For two years from 1988 to 1990, I did stand-up at night
and toured welders' premises by day. I was getting to bed at 2am and then
getting up four hours later. Even in my dinner-hour, I'd be trying to write
jokes.
``Even though I was only 24, I was completely knackered.''
Thankfully, Jeff's winsome brand of laddish confession has never seemed tired,
as his many Scottish fans will be able to discover when he journeys north of
the Border this week. But how did he get from retailing oxygen-cylinders to
creating a happy atmosphere in clubs?
``Friday Night Live on Channel 4. I'd watch it and think: `Here's a bunch of
people who look like me; who haven't had to go through being Butlin's Redcoats;
who are doing comedy that sounds as though it's the kind of comedy I could
write.' ''
Jeff has now been writing and performing his comedy full-time for five years.
Although he's yet to make a major TV breakthrough of his own, he has picked up
sundry Edinburgh Fringe awards. Plus something less tangible, but more
rewarding.
``I have paid my dues, as they say, in Edinburgh. I remember doing a three-week
double bill with Lee Evans in 1991. It was very demoralising at the time,
playing to six people, then nine people. Maybe at the weekend it would rise to
20 people, but then it would be back down again.
``I didn't do a full Edinburgh run this year because I only had 40 new minutes
of material, and it wouldn't have been fair on audiences. So I just did three
nights, but while all my stand-up mates were saying: `You lucky devil,' I was
acutely aware of how much I missed being there for longer. You see, no matter
how few people you might be playing to, a stand-up can't help but come away
from Edinburgh red-hot, honed to perfection.
``I will be doing the whole three weeks next year.''
Other parts of Scotland have been highly important in Jeff's development as a
performer, too.
``I appeared one Burns Night at Glasgow's Old Athenaeum after having been away
on holiday for three weeks. I hadn't looked at my material in all that time,
and as I stood waiting for the curtain to go up, listening to this fearsome
baying noise from the stalls, I knew that I would never be able to remember my
opening line.
``Sheer terror somehow transformed me into a bloke who had never in his life
been so pleased to be standing on that stage that night. I did another Glasgow
show, at Mayfest last year, in a big circus tent. Jo Brand was MC, and I had to
follow a comic who had been most horribly booed off.
``Going on stage in those circumstances can actually make it easier to please
an audience, as they're maybe a little guilty about what they've done, as well
as desperate for light relief. But I'd got a load of new material I hadn't done
before, in preparation for Edinburgh, and I almost bottled it. Thankfully, I
didn't and people liked it.''
Breathe in some of Jeff Green's life-giving comedy and you'll be thankful, too.
n Jeff Green visits Scotland on the Gilded Balloon comedy circuit, calling at
East Kilbride tonight (Arts Centre); Edinburgh tomorrow (Gilded Balloon);
Aberdeen on Friday (Lemon Tree); Dundee on Saturday (Dundee Rep), and Glasgow
on Sunday (Tron).
</TEXT>
