<HEADLINE>Theatre   Every Blessed Thing, Crown Court Church of Scotland, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975142955</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MODERATOR of the General Assembly in 1957; Rector of Glasgow University from
1968-71; founder of the Iona Community in 1938 - George Macleod, to most of us
south of the border, is probably best known for the latter role.
By all accounts, and judging by Tom Fleming and Ronald Ferguson's dynamic
recreation of the man, he was a man who revelled in ruffling feathers. Already
rousingly received at the St Magnus Festival and in Edinburgh, how would this
account go down in London?
In fact, in the austere but almost intimate surroundings of the Church of
Scotland's Crown Court, a place conspicuously apt in George Macleod's centenary
year for being the site of his marriage in 1948, Tom Fleming's two-hour solo,
an undeniable theatrical tour de force, conjures up a very particular kind of
Scottish spirit: that of the fierce, independent freethinker.
With only the help of a lampstand, rug and chair, Fleming leaves it to
Macleod's words and his own inestimable voice to conjure the many-sided images
of this no doubt part-irritating but also inspiringly honest spiritual
traveller - an uncompromisingly uncategorisable and life-long pacifist and
ecumenical, in flight from any form of political or, for that matter, religious
correctness, but also one, paradoxically, deeply involved in religion as a
political force.
Listening to Macleod's blasts against the arms trade and Big Banking, the
rigidities of religious bigotry and sectarianism, you couldn't help thinking
that he and Christ (particularly Dennis Potter's doubting, disputatious one),
would get on like a house on fire, arguing through the night and on into
eternity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
