<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blind penalty secures world title for Ajax. Rangers' new striker fails to hit the target</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142956</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ajax 0, Gremio 0
(After extra time)
Ajax won 4-3 on penalties.
BRAZILIAN striker Jardel, who will join up with Rangers in the new year,
yesterday failed to add to his honours when his current side, Gremio, lost out
on a penalty shoot-out to European champions Ajax in the World Club
Championship before 60,000 fans in Tokyo.
Jardel, who was substituted late in the game, was left to reflect on the two
second-half chances he missed, first shooting wide from good position and then
sending a header past a post.
Yet, in terms of clear-cut chances, Ajax's Patrick Kluivert and Finnish
internationalist Jari Litmanen were as guilty as Jardel of missing a virtually
open target more than once.
When extra time left the match still without a goal, Ajax captain Danny Blind
converted his team's last penalty to give the Amsterdam side a 4-3 victory.
It was the third time since 1985 that the match has been settled by penalties
and the fifth occasion it needed extra time.
Ajax were always in front during the shoot-out after Edwin van der Sar saved
from Dinho and Francsico Arce hit the bar with Gremio's second, even though
Kluivert put the Dutch side's opening spot-kick wide.
The victory rewarded the more enterprising side on a bitterly cold afternoon
that had some Brazilian outfield players wearing gloves.
The Dutch side dominated the match, but were unable to breach the strong Gremio
defence, even though the Brazilian side were down to 10 men after 56 minutes.
Paraguayan central defender Catalino Rivarola was sent off for his second
bookable offence, a second successive foul on teenage striker Kluivert in the
space of three minutes.
Ajax were lucky not to have international winger Marc Overmars sent off minutes
after Rivarola's dismissal. He swung an arm in front of Arilson's face and the
Gremio midfielder went down holding his mouth. But English referee David
Elleray, who had his back to the incident, simply went ahead with a free kick
he had already awarded Gremio after consulting his linesman.
The match could have got out of hand at that point as the Brazilian side
demanded Overmars be sent off, but Elleray's firm hand steered it away from
trouble.
Afterwards, Gremio's coach Luis Felipe said: ``Ajax had too much possession and
it was difficult to fight with only 10 players, but I think we did well to get
to the penalties.
``They are one of the super teams of Europe and today they did not score, so I
think the sides are very even.''
Ajax are unbeaten in 49 successive league games and have run up 55 goals in
their 15 league games so far this season and 11 in five European Champions' Cup
matches.
Coach Louis van Gaal criticised the Tokyo pitch, saying it had prevented his
side from playing their usual passing game.
``We were forced to play another style because of the field. My team were not
so good today, but that was also due to Gremio. They defended in a small area
and played the counter-attack. But we can kill a defence like this on a good
pitch.''
