<DOCNO>GH951129-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music   Blur, SECC, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was very different when Blur last played the SECC, in 1992, at the bottom of
a four-band bill headed by the Jesus and Mary Chain. Then, a tired and
emotional Damon Albarn spent most of the gig laddishly trying to pull down
bassist Alex James' trousers.
The ennui-laden cognoscenti, present for more credible names such as My Bloody
Valentine, looked on askance.
In contrast, most of last night's audience - the massed ranks of 14-year-old
girlies - would have died at the mere thought of pulling down Damon's trousers.
They screamed. They ripped the breast-pocket from Damon's shirt when he
unwisely forayed into the stage-front pit, within reach of their frenzied
grasp. They screamed again.
Damon shrugged resignedly before totting up the votive offerings flung from the
seething mob on to the stage: one leather jacket, a koala bear, a trumpet, a
broken pair of sunglasses...... and a tin of Spam? Lumme, imagine copping a
flying tin of Spam in the chuzzlewits. Oooh. So where's it healthier for Blur
to be in 1995? Sneered at by self-styled hipsters, or the targets of unthinking
adoration? Somewhere in-between, obviously.
But how to get there, now they've outgrown their roots in matey music hall and
nimble power-pop and become stadium-sized teen-fodder? Tunes. They just have to
keep knocking them out. With literate lyrics attached, of course. It's worked
for the past three albums.
Yet overly receptive crowds can cloud your judgment.
So maybe last night's most important sight was Damon smiting himself on the
head with his microphone every so often. Keeping himself in touch with his
knockabout past? Finding strength through suffering? Time alone will tell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saint trains with broken leg</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ST JOHNSTONE defender John McQuillan has spent the last three weeks walking
around on a broken leg. It was only after the 25-year-old full back underwent a
second scan this week in Glasgow that it emerged he had cracked his fibula.
Signed from Dundee during the close season, McQuillan thought he had suffered a
calf strain when he was injured against Dumbarton at Boghead on November 4. Now
he faces a further six weeks out of the game.
Last night he admitted he counted himself lucky. ``I continued to train after
getting the injury and everything was fine as long as I was just running. But
there was a lot of pain when I tried to turn or stretch. I began to worry that
I might have picked up one of those injuries that take ages to clear up. I was
actually relieved to be told by the specialist after the second scan that it
was a cracked bone.
``I thought it was very unusual that the break did not show up the first time,
but I am told that exactly the same thing happened to one of our young players
last season.''
q FORFAR manager Tommy Campbell has told teenager Sean Christie that he does
not want to see him playing in the first team again this season. The
15-year-old became the youngest player ever to appear in a Scottish League
fixture when he came on as a substitute against Berwick last weekend, but
Campbell knows the danger of burning out young talent.
Campbell explained: ``Using Sean against Berwick was done more out necessity
than anything else. We were struggling to field a team and Sean happened to be
at the front of the queue.
``He plays regularly in our reserve team and I knew he would not let us down.
But I really would prefer not to use him in the first team again this season.
He has bags of potential, but I don't want to risk rushing the lad too quickly
and losing him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000046</DOCID>
