<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BATHGATE'S Stephen Gallacher and Longniddry's Raymond Russell will join the
European Tour next season after having graduated from the ardous qualifying
school at San Roque in Spain yesterday.
As a fierce wind blasted the Costa del Sol venue, Atherstone's Steve Webster
triumphed with a remarkable eight-under-par total.
Gallacher slipped to a poor, but understandable, closing 76, yet still finished
in the top five while Russell posted a level-par round of 72.
Starting the day at four-under, Gallacher was virtually assured access to the
lucrative circuit yet failed to fire and finished with a double bogey at the
final hole where his approach found water. It was his first such score in 108
holes.
After his first and, hopefully, last sortie to the school, Gallacher said: ``My
main objective was to gain my card, but it was nice to finish in the top five.''
Having clinched his card at the third attempt, the jubilation of Russell was
tempered as two his countrymen fell at the final hurdle. Both William Guy, of
Buchanan Castle, and Scott Henderson, of King's Links, failed to secure their
cards, slumping to four-over-par rounds of 76.
An exhausted Russell said: ``Thank goodness that tournament is over. It is hard
enough at the best of times without having to endure this wind in the final
round.
``I lost my rhythm completely following the rain shower at the second hole and
was one-over-par after seven holes. But even that included a number of
excellent up and downs.'' Leading British and Irish qualifiers:
