<HEADLINE>No change in HLCA</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOPES of an increase in hill livestock compensatory allowances were dashed
yesterday when the Government confirmed they would remain at present levels for
the third year running, writes ROBERT ROSS.
Scottish Office Agriculture Minister the Earl of Lindsay said even a
stand-still figure represented a significant achievement in the current severe
public expenditure round.
``It is a clear sign of our continued commitment to support hill farming,'' he
said.
HLCA payments are made on breeding ewes and breeding beef suckler cows.
Last year they totalled #40.8m - #17.7m for sheep and #23.1m for cattle.
Scotland has 13,500 hill farmers for whom the payments are regarded as a vital
support.
Lord Lindsay acknowledged the importance of the sector saying: ``If you can
keep the farmers in business you can keep whole communities in business.
Scottish Ministers have fought very hard to protect the HLCAs.''
John Scott, hill farming convener for the National Farmers' Union of Scotland,
said it was disappointing the Government had reacted so negatively to its
request for special consideration for the plight of hill farmers and crofters
in the West and North, where conditions this year had been particularly
difficult.
</TEXT>
