<DOCID>GH951129-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>English clubs win #125m deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142962</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLISH football's breadline clubs were tossed a crumb of comfort with the
announcement yesterday of a #125m, five-year deal for Sky Television to
broadcast Endsleigh League matches. It could mean as much as #1m a year for
first division clubs, with scaled down payments to those in divisions two and
three.
``For some of our clubs this deal will be a lifeline. It will increase their
revenue and raise their viability at a crucial time,'' said League president
Gordon McKeag.
The prospect of a cash share-out from the record deal, allied to extra
advertising from live matches, will almost certainly kill the threat of major
clubs breaking away to form a Premier League division two. There was a sense of
jubilation at the League's Lytham St Anne's headquarters. Their TV income is
set to soar from #8m to #25m per season as a result of this agreement.
A meeting of all Endsleigh clubs will be held in London next month to thrash
out distribution details of the bonanza.
From next August, Sky will broadcast up to 60 Endsleigh matches and the three
end-of-season Wembley promotion play-offs live. Sky will probably broadcast
League matches on Friday nights and Sundays, but head of sport Vic Wakeling
insisted: ``It would be premature to assume a schedule at this stage.''
The deal also includes at least one live tie from each round of the Coca-Cola
Cup and exclusive coverage of the final.
The Football League were involved with the FA and the FA Premier League in
recent discussions about joint television agreements. Their decision to go it
alone has paid dividends.
The FA withdrew their offer after the League stalled on a decision about
whether to accept around #120m of a #250m five-year deal. However, FA spokesman
Steve Double said: ``Any deal which can help secure the financial future of its
member clubs is welcome. The deal is extremely similar to the one we offered.''
</TEXT>
