<HEADLINE>McKinlay and Craik keep well in touch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOMEN'S GOLF
SCOTLAND'S Myra McKinlay overcame a tense start before handing in a
one-under-par opening round of 71 in the 72-hole American Express Tour
qualifying school tournament at La Manga, Spain, yesterday.
It left McKinlay alongside compatriot Tracey Craik and just two strokes adrift
of Australian Joanne Mills, who leads the field after an almost faultless round
of 69.
McKinlay started her round from the tenth tee and thinned her opening drive
into a dry ditch just 40 yards from the tee.
From there the former Curtis Cup player hit a No.4-wood into another hazard but
played out to 15 feet from where she holed for an unlikely par 4. She dropped
shot at the fifteenth but holed from five feet for a birdie at the next hole to
reach the turn in 36.
After the turn, McKinlay found sand to lose a shot at the second hole but then
hit a glorious No.4-wood to 25ft for an eagle 3 at the long third before a run
of regulation figures brought her home in 35.
Craik, who also started her round at the tenth, was out in 36 but despite
losing an early shot to par on the inward half recovered with two birdies to
come home one under 71.
Mills never looked back after starting the day with birdies at the first three
holes.
Another followed at the sixth where she holed from seven feet before dropping
her only shot of the day at the fifteenth, the only green she failed to hit in
regulation. Leading first-round scores (British and Irish unless stated):
69 - J Mills (Australia).
71 - I Tinning (Denmark), T Craik, M McKinlay.
