<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bravura show to silence the critics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975142964</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DURING the run-up to the Budget, the conventional wisdom has held that the
Government faced a choice between tax cuts and investment in public services.
The general advice to the Chancellor of the Exchequer, from leader writers in
the newspapers, from talking heads on the television, and a wide range of other
compassionate folk, was that he should hold off on the cuts and concentrate on
the investment. Anything else, it has been implied, would be sacrificing the
future of the country to the interests of the Conservative Party.
Now Kenneth Clarke, in what seemed to me a bravura performance, has given us
both. There will be higher spending on public services, at least on the more
popular ones, on schools, hospitals, and the police. And there will be tax cuts
for everybody, but most of all, in effect, for the old and for others on the
lowest taxable incomes.
These, far more than the rich, have been the worst example of injustice in our
system of taxation, because of the absurdly high marginal rates they face when
they enter it.
To that extent, the Chancellor ought to silence his critics. Most of them have
indeed been talking rubbish. But once today's headlines, and the special
pleading which produced them, have been consigned to the dustbin of history,
there will be deeper questions about what Clarke has done.
In particular, is this what he claimed it to be, a cautious Budget, steady as
she goes with his own hand firm on the tiller, sailing serenely on to
well-defined long-term goals? Or is it an incautious, an over-optimistic
Budget, a gamble to recoup the fortunes of a desperate Government?
Well, there is plenty of evidence of caution. As Tony Blair remarked during his
efforts to whip up a bit of indignation from his own benches, what the
Chancellor gives with one hand he takes away with the other. Smokers and
drivers, as ever, pay more, while wastrels and fraudsters on social security
get less. The proceeds benefit the rest of us insofar as we do not fall into
those other categories.
The sums balance out and leave the overall fiscal stance unchanged. But then,
Labour does not propose as a general principle to do anything else. And this
general principle is in present conditions just as it should be.
More significant than the details of Clarke's measures were the results that he
expects from them. The most important single item in his speech was the
forecast for growth in 1996. It is estimated to rise to 3% from 2.75% this year.
In other words, the economy will expand faster. Unemployment will shrink
further. A greater number of people will be paying their albeit lower taxes.
Public borrowing will fall. Interest rates will go down with it. The effects of
recession will at last pass away.
Something like the glory days of Thatch-erism may even return, preferably
without the frenetic atmosphere of get-rich-quick. We may hope at least that a
sadder and wiser Government would not for a second time bring the glory days
crashing to a premature close.
Is the Chancellor's forecast plausible? Much hangs on the judgment. The British
economy has grown on a trend rate of between 2% and 3% since 1870 so perhaps it
would be a man bold to the point of foolhardiness who hoped for anything
better. Still, Clarke does not hope for more than 3%.
At the same time, it could just be that the British economy's potential has
improved since 1979. The deregulation of the Thatcherite era ought to have had
some effect beyond inflated wages for chairmen of privatised monopolies. It
ought to have freed capital and labour from the unprofitable activities into
which they were locked before. It ought to have allowed the capacity of a
basically wealthy country to be better used.
Unfortunately, we cannot be quite sure that all this has happened. The benefits
of deregulation were lost in the Lawson boom and the following recession before
their permanent results could be verified. But we can observe some signs at
least that permanent results, and permanent improvements, may indeed be there.
In 1994, the economy grew at 4%, well above the historic trend. That brought
consequences which had to be carefully watched and somewhat curbed, but which
have not got out of hand.
To forecast growth of 3% may therefore err on the optimistic side, but it is
not going over the top. Or at least it would err on the optimistic side if the
Chancellor had done nothing. His bravura performance lies in putting more money
in the taxpayers' pockets without altering the fiscal stance. This may be the
kick-start needed to hit 3%. At any rate, it seems to me a better way of
delivering the kick-start than what Gordon Brown has had to suggest.
Whether this will alter Tory fortunes decisively is, of course, a different
question. I suspect that voters still do not consider that the Government has
taken enough punishment for its past sins. So they will be slow to reward these
small tokens of repentance.
But a day of final reckoning must come in 18 months or so. And on that day, at
the General Election, we know from experience that people tend to act on
different motives from those impelling their expressions of opinion in
mid-term. They have to weigh the record of five years, and ponder the very
serious question of who is best fitted to govern them for the next five years.
This is not to predict that the Tories can yet snatch victory from defeat. But
if Clarke's record is coolly weighed, it will surely be found a creditable one.
</TEXT>
