<HEADLINE>ATV dangers highlighted</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>FARMING DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142965</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATV dangers
highlighted
THE potential dangers of all-terrain vehicles - ATVs - are highlighted by the
Health and Safety Executive in a new video launched yesterday.
Eleven people have been killed and many more injured in accidents over the last
10 years due to lack of proper training, says the executive.
The video shows examples from 100 serious ATV accidents which were investigated
by inspectors. Excessive speed is blamed for overturning incidents especially
when cornering. The use of the wrong gear on sloping ground can also cause the
vehicle to turn over.
Frank Lindsay, chief agricultural inspector, said: ``ATVs are increasingly used
on farms and are popular with young people. It is essential that riders know
the correct techniques for body positioning to improve both stability and
steering. It is also important that loads are correctly distributed on the
front or rear of the machine.''
Profits peak
THE ``golden profits'' period, which has seen farm incomes in some sectors
double over the past four years is reaching its peak, according to Chris
Bouchier, head of agriculture development with the advisory      service ADAS.
Speaking at Smithfield FarmTec, Mr Bouchier said short-term prospects still
looked good but current high profits were largely due to devaluation and the
continuing weakness of sterling - facts beyond the control of the producer.
Compensation
THE maximum compensation payable next month for an animal slaughtered because
it is affected with brucellosis or tuberculosis will be #756.
</TEXT>
