<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deserters reduce the Tory coffers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142966</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRACEABLE company donations to the Conservative Party have fallen to a
five-year low of about #2.5m, according to the latest survey from the Labour
Research Department, which also reveals a further #1.79m from undisclosed
corporate sources.
Meanwhile, Labour has started to attract a few corporate donations, although as
yet these total only #81,000 for the year ended March 1995, during which the
Liberal Democrats attracted just one, worth #2500.
The independent Labour Research Department maintains that its survey fundings
demonstrate the difficulty of getting to the bottom of Tory Party financing and
lend weight to those calling on Lord Nolan's committee on standards in public
life to reverse its decision not to investigate the finances of political
parties until after the General Election.
A company must declare a donation if it produces a directors' report and makes
a donation of #200 or more. With around one million UK companies, about three
quarters of which are required to file such details with Companies House, an
exhaustive survey is not feasible.
Labour Research's latest sift through the accounts of around 5000 key public
and private companies has traced 172 companies giving a total of #2,461,655 to
the Tory Party in the year ending March 1995 - the lowest number of companies
and the smallest amount donated for the last five years.
This compares with 198 companies traced as giving #2,836,600 in the previous
year and substantially down on 1990 - the best non-election year for the
Tories, who attracted #3,815,071 from 309 companies.
Conservative finances have been hit by long-time company supporters deserting
the party. Around 50 have stopped making donations in the last 18 months.
Notable examples are United Biscuits, the Rank Organisation, insurance group
Sedgwick, Whitbread brewers, property giant Great Portland Estates, and cereals
multinational Kellogg.
The collapse of Barings Bank also cost the Tories dear. Other recent deserters
include Glaxo and Lucas. In addition, nearly 30 companies have reduced their
donations over the past two years.
On the plus side, the party has attracted eight new donors, with 28 companies
resuming donations and more than 40 increasing theirs over the past two years.
This fall in corporate donations leaves an increasing proportion coming from
undisclosed sources.
Over the past five years, unaffected by General Election donations, the company
donations traced by Labour Research as a proportion of total donations show in
the Tory Party accounts has plummeted from 52% in the year ending March 1989,
to just over 30% in 1994, and a mere 19.3% in the latest survey.
The Labour Party's financial backers include Dr Swraj Paul's Caparo
conglomerate (#54,000), Pearson Group publishers (#25,000), Currie Motors
(#1000), and Meconic (#1000).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Future in doubt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142967</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN Lara's international future may be in jeopardy after the world's leading
batsman withdrew from West Indies' tour of Australia which starts next week.
Lara, who was fined 10% of his tour fee along with Carl Hooper, Curtly Ambrose,
and Kenneth Benjamin for misconduct on the tour of England this year, withdrew
from the tour party on Monday.
West Indies Cricket Board of Control president Peter Short told the Caribbean
news agency, CANA, that Lara had not signed a tour contract.
``However, I explained to him that I considered that there was a moral
obligation,'' Short said.
Asked about Lara's prospects of playing in next year's World Cup in India,
Pakistan, and Sri Lanka, Short replied: ``What the future holds is very open.
``I don't know what will happen there, I don't know what view the board is
going to take, I don't know what view Brian is going to take about his future
and his immediate post-Australia participation.''
Lara was released from his three-year contract with County champions
Warwickshire last week after pleading fatigue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Special agent Morgan books top Ajax pair Dutch double signing set to be the main attraction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142968</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOP Scottish agent Blair Morgan has pulled off one of the biggest football
coups ever by signing up two of the Ajax players who helped the Dutch champions
to their World Club Cup triumph in Tokyo yesterday.
Nigerian internationalists, Finidu George and Nwanko Kanu, could be available
to the leading Scottish clubs at the end of the season.
The Dunfermline-based lawyer was in Amsterdam at the weekend, and after talks
with the Dutch champions, he signed up both players. And this will give
Scottish clubs the chance to move in.
Last night, Morgan maintained a low profile. The players will not necessarily
be leaving Ajax - though the -recent policy at the Amsterdam club is to sell on
players and continue to produce their own talent through their youth system.
There is little doubt that if suitable offers arrive, then George and Kanu will
move and, equally, with an agent based in Scotland, then the major clubs in the
premier division will have an inside track.
Last night, Morgan said: ``Yes, I was in Holland at the weekend and I have
confirmed that I will be representing the two Nigerian players, Finidi George
and Nwankwo Kanu.
``I cannot say more than that. Both of the players were in action in Tokyo, and
they could be available at the end of the season. I cannot say where they might
go, but if anyone in Scotland is interested, then they can contact me.''
The opportunity is there for our clubs. In the past, the top Dutch players have
moved on to Italy and then, like Ruud Gullitt, have been disenchanted by the
life provided there for footballers.
Now there are two players      who have been hardened by European competition,
gaining winner's medals just last season, and handled by a Scottish-based agent.
The chance is there for our top clubs to move in just as aggressively as Morgan
and sign up the Ajax men.
q.SERIE A could become an even more impressive footballing arena if the Italian
Senate pushes through legislation which will forbid all sports authorities from
restricting the numbers of foreign athletes which is in line with the thinking
of Otto Lenz, the European Court of Justice's advocate general, who has
recommended free movement of European footballers.
If the Italian football federation is forced to end the practice of allowing
only three non-Italians in each club side - Scottish and English clubs can play
as many foreigners as they wish in domestic competitions - people like the
country's former President, Silvio Berlusconi, who is the owner of AC Milan,
will move to import more of world's best players. But he would only do that if,
like Rangers, he was convinced UEFA will be forced to work according to the
Treaty of Rome.
European law regards UEFA's stance on the number of non-nationals per team -
only three foreign players are allowed to play with each club side in any of
the three European club competitions - as illegal, and there will be further
movement on that front before the end of the year, but the Italians probably
believe they are moving into line with what might soon become law.
The Senate voted yesterday to lift restrictions on transfers and use of
football players and other professional athletes from European Union countries.
Under an amendment presented by the Northern League and approved by the Senate
within a broader package of immigration laws, Italian professional clubs would
be able to buy and field an unlimited number of EU players.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Board are likely to ban `casual' fans</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142969</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE British Boxing Board of Control will today almost certainly issue a ban on
all ``casual'' fans from sporting club wine-and-dine shows throughout the
country.
That is the likeliest outcome when the board's stewards, headed by chairman Sir
David Hopkin and including Shadow Minister for Sport Tom Pendry MP, make their
inquiry into the serious disturbance which flared at the end of the tragic Drew
Docherty-James Murray British bantamweight title fight at the Hospitality Inn,
Glasgow, on October 13.
At the end of the bout, which Docherty won by a twelfth-round knockout, fans,
who had been allowed late entry to the event, went on the rampage throwing
bottles and chairs.
The board will consider representations from the promoters, Katherine Morrison
and Frank Warren, Strathclyde Police, the security firm, and the hotel
management before announcing any new measures to be introduced.
Although Docherty-Murray was the main event of a dinner show and not a public
promotion as such, extra stewarding was on hand.
The vulnerable area appeared to be linked to the admission of non-diners to
watch the fight.
Board secretary John Morris said: ``That sort of thing is bound to be discussed
- alcohol is bound to be discussed, plus police presence.
``You are always going to get the flash situation you don't expect. This one
was difficult to deal with in all the circumstances.''
Meantime, Johnny Armour, from Chatham, rated No.2 by the IBF, tonight defends
his European bantamweight title against France's Redha Jean Abbas at York Hall,
Bethnal Green.
Victory would almost certainly lift him into top spot with the IBF, so it is no
time for 19-win Armour to lose his title or unbeaten record.
JIM REYNOLDS
BOXING
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>European ruling supports Spanish fisherman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142970</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government could face a massive compensation claim after the European
Court's advocate-general yesterday backed Spain in a battle over
``flag-of-convenience'' fishing.
If the interim ruling is endorsed by the European Court of Justice, Britain
could be forced to pay out at least #30m to Spanish trawlermen who exploited a
loophole in European law to register at British ports and qualify for limited
UK fishing quotas.
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries, and Food, the ruling could
allow around 100 Spanish boat owners to pursue damages claims for sums of
between #250,000 and #650,000 each in the British High Court.
Around 150 Spanish vessels, some UK-registered and operating out of the west
coast port of Ardrossan, were prevented from fishing in British waters
following the introduction of the Merchant Shipping Act in 1988.
The Act said British-registered boats had to be 75 per cent UK-owned and run by
British bosses.
For 15 months, the Spanish-owned ``British'' boats were forced to tie up.
However, in 1991, the European Court declaed the law contrary to EU rules,
which allow any company to set itself up anywhere in Europe.
Yesterday's statement could rekindle the political fury over interference in
national sovereignty and provoke a backlash from the domestic industry, furious
at the prospect of handsome rewards for Spanish fishermen seen as having
cheated on fish quota rules at the expense of UK fishermen's livelihoods.
Mr Elliot Morley, Labour's fishery spokesman, said the practice of ``quota
hopping'', whereby Spaniards bought up British boats and registered them in the
UK to gain access to Britain's fish quota, had been restricted by amendments to
the Merchant Shipping Act.
He added: ``The Government didn't move swiftly enough to close the loophole.
``This ruling is very bad news for the British fishing industry and the
taxpayer in terms of compensation.
``It is clear that attempts to stop quota-hopping were never implemented
successfully through the Act.
``We need to resolve this situation with the European Commission and try to
minimise the liability to the United Kingdom.''
Earlier this year, Tory MP David Harris, whose St Ives constituents include
fishermen threatened by the Spanish invasion, described the situation as ``an
absolute scandal''.
He has long campaigned on behalf of the Cornish fishermen and condemned
yesterday's decision saying: ``It is absolutely disgraceful if we have now got
to pay #30m on top of having the wretched flag-of-convenience boats in our
waters and fishing against our quotas.
``Cornish fishermen are furious about this further move, which just rubs salt
into sore wounds.''
However, a MAFF spokesman said litigation depended on the actual ruling.
He said: ``We have to wait for the opinion of the European Court of Justice.
Only then will we know whether claims for damages are likely to be pursued
through the UK courts.''
Mr Paul Tyler, the Liberal Democrat MP for North Cornwall, said: ``It is
extraordinary that the Minister is so relaxed about this and yet at the same
time we still have not got the Spanish boat owners to pay up the compensation
for acts of piracy against Cornish fishermen 15 months ago during the tuna
war.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>We do care, honest we do</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975142971</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOOK, I'm getting pretty cheesed off with my generation being labelled as a
bunch of malcontent slackers who are more apathetic than a gang of stoned
sloths. I'm fed up with hearing us described as perpetually fed up. Last year
the Washington Post nicknamed us Generation Hex. Apparently, we're all cursed
with the Don't-Give-A-Damn Disease, disinterested in anything but indulging our
desires and incapable of interest in anything other than the latest indie
import.
Well, hey, sometimes we do give a damn. We're just not very good at expressing
it. Admittedly, we have a slight aversion to the ballot box and would rather
watch The Chart Show than march up and down town on over-demonstrative
demonstrations of a Saturday morning, but that doesn't mean to say that we
don't care about, well, stuff.
We worry about the same things you wrinklies worry about; the nation's
wellbeing, litter on the streets, the future of the family, global peace, and
the price of denture cream. Well, okay, maybe not the latter: our fluoride
situation is sorted, thank you very much. But our chat isn't all about the
sexual shenanigans of Paula Yates, the latest Boddington's advertising
campaign, or the respective merits of Blur and Oasis.
It's not all shallow piffle. Sometimes we get all deep and meaningful. We do
care, honest we do. We even care about the children. Just because we're not
rushing headlong towards the maternity wards doesn't mean we're not interested
in sprogs. Why, just the other week my cronies and I worked ourselves into a
state of deep distress about the nation's youngsters, and their dependency on
the VCR and the computer.
They don't get enough fresh air: that makes us worried. They don't know how to
enjoy themselves: we feel stressed. Their standard of play has been seriously
eroded: we get so anxious we need a drink. See, that shows how much we care.
Last Sunday's Screws of the World got its crotchless knickers in a twist about
the fact that children are about to have access to a CD-Rom showing them how to
make bombs. We concur with the tabloid's concern. This is a very grave
situation. Why should kids today have it so easy? Do they need step-by-step
guides to everything? Do they have no imagination of their own?
I mean, we remember a time when children didn't need to be fed a video or
computer-generated diet of violence and sex. We made our own fun, we created
our own violence and sex. Maybe it's nostalgic, maybe it's rose-tinted crap,
but the conversation quickly settled into an evening of looking back on the
good old days.
``We used to have screaming competitions,'' I remembered fondly, recalling the
occasions when we young teenage girls would gather to vent our hormonal energy
by howling at the moon, testing local residents' commitment to what was going
on in their own backyard. Sort of an antecedent to car alarms, if not very good
on the tonsils.
``Well, we used to have spitting competitions,'' said the current man in my
life who's putting life in my life, waxing lyrical about the time when he and
his compadres would gob across the close in what was surely a psychic limbering
up for future punk concerts. Old ladies would have to show off their twinkle
toes to dodge these phlegmatic bullets. Do young people nowadays show such
concern for the exercise of their elderly neighbours? I think not.
An atheist I may be but I believe that there is something in Jesus's maxim:
``Suffer little children to come unto me.'' My, how we suffered. How we learned
through pain. Our enthusiasm for British Bulldog, a game which was basically
the legitimised beating up of smaller children, was a graphic example of the
rules of Survival of the Fittest. When you are being punched and pummelled and
brought down in the scrum you soon learn to target the kid down the road with
the gammy leg. Unless he had a particularly big brother.
And what's all this fuss about sexual education? Just drag the kids away from
their poncey computers and hurl them into the playground for a quick burst of
Kiss, Cuddle, or Torture. It was good enough for us. In fact, it was a
veritable obsession with us. But surely healthier than being addicted to
heroin, as today's tinies supposedly are, according to the press. No wonder my
generation are such sophisticated practitioners of SM; our school intervals
echoed to the cries of, ``torture, ah, torture please''.
Social order is necessary for the imposition of any form of democracy and we
anticipated boring university lectures on Machiavelli with the strategic
imposition of Bugsy Circles. Chalk circles were drawn around any miscreants -
ie, someone with a faded cardigan - and they weren't allowed to step outside.
Well, you have to be cruel to be kind. The victims should have learned to shape
up. I guess it was an early form of tough love.
And we didn't need video nasties or drugs for our adrenalin rushes. We had
organised vigilante groups instead. And they were truly democratic. Everyone
got their turn. Pah to Freddie Krueger. I remember the heart-thumping
excitement of being chased home by a gang of fellow 10-year-olds, convinced
that they would scalp me if they caught me. And they probably would have.
Virtual Reality just can't replicate that kind of thrill.
Young folks today, saturated on a dull diet of educational Lion King computer
activities, just don't know what they're missing. We despair for them, really
we do. But every now and again you catch a glimpse of a situation which
gladdens the heart, which offers the optimistic suggestion that old traditions
die hard.
The other day I was slumped, I mean slaving, over my Applemac when a din
interrupted my mental gestations. Outside, a gang of eight-year-old girls were
taunting a smaller group across the road. ``Scabies! Scabies!'' they shrieked
with a viciousness and energy which fair caught at my throat. I clasped my
hands together with delight. Perhaps there's some hope for the young 'uns after
all. Suffer, little children. Suffer. Generation Hex cares after all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
