<HEADLINE>Chairman Hunter's quest for success paying off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142972</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HELLO, is that the BBC? Is it a Team of the Year you are after for your Sports
Review of the Year prog? Look no further, my fine fellows, than the glittering,
Jim Leishman-led Livingston, whom you will find in the spanking new stadium at
Almondvale, all lights ablazing.
I was there, and proud to be, when Kilmarnock came for a special challenge
match on Monday night. OK, it was a friendly. But 3000 people turned up.
You see, there has never been a senior football club in the new town until this
year. That's when Meadowbank Thistle took on the mantle of Livingston FC and a
club and an all-seater stadium was born.
Today they are proudly on top of the Scottish third division, leading by four
clear points. If they beat second-placed Ross County this week I bet nobody
catches them in the second half of the season.
Bill Hunter, an East Lothian builder and the club chairman, is the man who made
it happen, backed wholeheartedly by the Livingston Development Corporation.
When he announced his intention to move the club from Edinburgh he and his
family were subjected to a sustained campaign of vilification by a small band
of supporters. He has seen them off.
When I was greeted by him on Monday night he told me they had held a dinner in
the town the previous Friday. ``We had 280 people there, which is more than we
often had attending matches at Meadowbank.''
Thistle, which had developed from the Ferranti works team, had a perfectly
decent record as a senior side - under manager Terry Christie they almost
gained entry into the premier division. But the stadium built for the
Commonwealth Games did not allow room for promotion - even when Meadowbank drew
a plum cup-tie they had to stage it somewhere else.
Hunter bit the bullet, became convinced he could build a new support and now
runs an operation which is the envy of most of the clubs in the country. ``I
was really tickled at that dinner. One guy paid #450 for a shirt signed by Ruud
Gullitt, somebody else coughed up #1300 for a framed Livingston jersey.''
He must be the only club chairman in the land whose office is next door to that
of the cleaner - ``In this game you never know what is going to happen next.''
It was time to have a look at the team. All credit to Kilmarnock, they sent a
full squad and manager Alex Totten, who does not tolerate non-triers, was in
the dug-out.
Totten wasn't over-happy when Robert Connor, late of Aberdeen, slid a cross
past his own keeper. Never mind, Stewart Williamson did the same at the other
end, so the big boys were back on track. Not for long.
A young trialist from Newcastle, named Cona Hislop I was assured, cracked in a
peach of a shot and before half-time Graham Harvey, who has had more clubs than
Arnold Palmer, made it 3-l for the home team before John Henry got one back.
Two unusual features: if the ball goes over the wall at the east end it rarely
comes back; the Labour and SNP parties both have permanent trackside adverts. I
wonder how long a Tory one would last?
Missed Gordon McLeod's fourth goal for Livvy because I was finishing my pie
with Peter Donald, high heid yin of the Scottish League. We remark on the
number of families, mothers as well, who are present.
``If you had to introduce families to football,'' muses Peter, ``can you think
of a better place to do it than here?'' I was back to acclaim goal No.5, from
lively winger Mark Duthie. Livingston had played good football, shown some fine
individual skills and we hadn't had a chant or an F-word from the crowd all
night.
Back in the boardroom Ann Young, the club's marketing manager - her father,
Billy Nimmo, played in goal for Leeds and was Kevin Keegan's hero, so it's in
the blood - was insisting: ``This whole scenario is going to work, the
community is behind us.''
Then in he came, the poet himself. ``You know me,'' said Jolly Jim, with a
wink, ``I have no great tactical awareness. I just like them to pass the ball,
deny the opposition possession, and fire in the odd shot. Simple, really.
``We know fine that was just a friendly, that Kilmarnock let us play, but it
does the boys' confidence a power of good.''
Being around Jim Leishman, an inspired choice, does that for everybody. I want
a Livvy Lions T-shirt in my stocking, please.
And I expect action from the BBC. It's down to you, Dougie.
</TEXT>
