<HEADLINE>UK a haven for Islamic militants, claims Egypt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN was home to Muslim militants fighting the Egyptian government since
1992 and could suffer in the end from militant activities, Egypt's interior
minister Hassan el-Alfi said today.
``There are information centres for the terrorists who roam British soil and
who hold conferences there,'' the minister was quoted as saying in Cairo's
al-Ahram newspaper.
``They also get their instructions (to attack) there and all the attacks that
occur are commissioned from outside Egypt,'' he added.
Last week, the militant Jihad (Holy Struggle) group claimed responsibility for
blasting the Egyptian embassy in Pakistan in which 16 people died and at least
60 were wounded.
Two other militant groups said they were behind the bombing, and one also said
it killed an Egyptian diplomat in Geneva earlier this month.
The minister also warned the United Kingdom that it would be ``burned by the
fire of terrorism'' as long as it gives these groups asylum.
Egypt claims that several Arab and European countries host fugitive militants,
who sometimes claim asylum on human rights grounds.
The government in Cairo charges that some, like Sudan, train militants aiming
to topple President Hosni Mubarak.
About 900 people have been killed in political violence in Egypt since 1992.
Meanwhile, Egypt's parliamentary elections tomorrow have captured the interest
of a larger than expected number of voters, and many said on election eve that
they would cast ballots.-Reuter.
Cairo
</TEXT>
