<HEADLINE>Island's owner in fraud probe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE eccentric German artist who owns Eigg is facing an investigation in
Stuttgart after allegations of fraud.
Marling Eckhard-Maruma bought the island in July, promising millions of pounds
to turn it into a holiday paradise.
A spokesperson for the prosecutor's office in Stuttgart said yesterday: ``We
have opened a formal investigation for investment fraud.''
She said the investigation mainly concerned statements made by Mr Maruma in
brochures promoting the Maruma AG Holding.
She said a person who cannot be identified for legal reasons had supplied
information concerning Mr Maruma's business activities, which had been checked
for several weeks before the prosecutor called for the formal investigation.
Mr Maruma was not available for comment yesterday.
Rumours have circulated about the income allegedly generated by the self-styled
professor's fire-paintings.
A 1993 brochure issued by Maruma AG Holding woos would-be investors by claiming
enormous profits from the spiralling value of the paintings, which would serve
as the holding's main assets.
However, as an investigation by The Herald earlier this year had established,
no German museum, art gallery, or important arts dealer had heard of Mr Maruma.
Even at his home base in Stuttgart, where he runs his so-called Maruma Centre
from a disused factory, he was unknown on the local arts scene.
Mr Maruma insists the Maruma AG Holding never left an embryonic blueprint
status.
Before the launch of the investigation, he told The Herald he had devised a new
art concept years ago.
``But I dropped it without its having been put into practice. The Maruma AG
Holding was never established nor has a single share been sold,'' he said.
He added: ``The blueprints were drafts, plans, concepts, trying to establish
whether such a system would work.''
The prosecutor decided on a full inquiry as press reports are insisting the
material they were shown looked like a brochure designed for a wider
circulation.
</TEXT>
