<HEADLINE>Jaws of age trap eased open</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME, STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor stood accused last night of helping old cars more than old
people.
While politicians and elderly groups in Scotland welcomed parts of the Budget,
they said it did not go far enough to help the vast majority of pensioners and
would not stop the enforced sale of family homes to pay for residential care.
Mr Clarke raised the savings limit below which people qualify for free
residential care from #3000 to #10,000. In addition the higher band beyond
which people have to meet the full cost of care rises from #8000 to #16,000.
Edinburgh District Council's Tory group leader, Daphne Sleigh, who led a
campaign to increase the thresholds, said last night: ``I am pleased he has
responded so quickly but we are only half-way there.
``I was hoping to have the upper threshold raised to #35,000 or #40,000 and I
will be looking for the rest of it next year. He has made a good start and it
will be welcomed by many people.''
However, SNP health spokesman Iain Glen said the Chancellor had helped vintage
vehicles with road tax exemption rather than elderly people.
``Old cars are being looked after better than old people, who will still have
to sell their homes to meet residential care costs. It is a Budget for the
better-off and it doesn't help the elderly except marginally,'' he said.
Ms Hilary Patrick, legal adviser to the Scottish Association for Mental Health,
said raising the higher band would help many people who could not be described
as rich.
``But Mr Clarke has not attacked the main problem: the way the family home is
taken into account. People will still have to sell their homes to pay for
residential care.  They will not be able to pass the house on to their
children. When the NHS was founded we were promised care from the cradle to the
grave. That promise has been broken and the Budget has not altered this.''
Of Scotland's 800,000 people over the age of 65, only 17,000 live in a
residential care homes.
Ms Maureen O'Neill, director of Age Concern Scotland, said the failure to
increase capital limits for other means-tested benefits meant the system was
still penalising older people with savings living at home.
``Tax cuts will not help the vast majority of Scottish pensioners. Only one in
three pay any tax and a couple aged over 75 would have to have an income of
more than #10,000 to benefit from these measures. The Budget contained nothing
to benefit poorer pensioners or to help older people with winter heating
bills,'' she added.
Mr Clarke also increased the inheritance tax threshold from #150,000 to
#200,000 and said the Government would be consulting on new schemes to reward
people who planned for the cost of care in retirement.
Ms Lily Kennedy, chairperson of Strathclyde Elderly Forum, said: ``We are angry
and disappointed. The Chancellor has ignored the problems facing the vast
majority of older people.
``We desperately needed the Budget to address fuel poverty, the frozen savings
limits for means-tested benefits, and the appallingly inadequate pension.''
She said the savings threshold increases affected only 2% of the elderly
population and would not stop pensioners being forced to sell their homes.
``There is also little point in increasing the threshold of inheritance tax if
the family home has been sold to pay nursing home fees,'' she added.
The Labour Party dismissed the Budget announcement on long-term care for the
elderly as inadequate and predicted it would not stop people having to sell
their homes to pay for the care they needed.
Labour's social security spokesman, John Denham, and health spokesman Alan
Milburn said: ``With the average house worth #67,000, the new #16,000 capital
disregard will not safeguard the homes of elderly people who believed they had
been promised care from the cradle to the grave.
``Without clear national guidelines people with assets above the new threshold
will still be paying for care which may be free in other parts of the country.
Under the Conservatives where you live determines the care you get and the
prices you pay. We challenge the Health Secretary to make access to care a
matter of right not a matter of chance.''
Labour also claimed that most members of occupational pension schemes simply
could not afford to buy long-term care insurance. According to the National
Association of Pension Funds a pensioner couple would have to cut their pension
by #3000 a year to allow for higher payments if they need long-term care.
The savings limit has been one of the most contentious aspects of Care in the
Community as old and dependent people were transferred from NHS care into
social services care. A maximum of #3000 in savings were allowed before a
contribution to the cost had to be made, on a scale up to #8000, when the
entire cost had to be met by the client. That scale now begins at #10,000, with
the full charge payable if savings exceed #16,000.
</TEXT>
