<HEADLINE>Too much cricket takes its inevitable toll Lara decides that enough is enough</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BOB CRAMPSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142976</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN Lara will not take part in the forthcoming short tour of Australia by the
West Indies, and that may be the best bit of news first-class cricket has had
in many a long day.
Not that the supreme talent of Lara will not be profoundly missed, but this
withdrawal, at the player's own wish, may be the dawn of sanity in the game.
Lara is unusual, perhaps unique, in that he is capable of playing an innings
which is both long and flamboyant.
Normally, great batsmen divide into two clearly recognisable camps.
There are the Bothams, few in number, ferocious in attack, but by definition
seldom at the crease for two days.
Then there are the Bradmans and Boycotts, prodigiously gifted technically, but
with a cast of mind which makes them willing accumulators.
Lara does not appear to have this obsessive desire to make runs heavily all the
time, especially when all the time means six days a week, 52 weeks a year.
His talent is such that his rare, but inevitable, failures provoke almost a
palpable hostility from those spectators who have paid heavily, but on that day
will see little of the tiny genius.
Genius by definition is variable. It cannot be turned on like a tap. Competence
is steady, genius variable.
Warwickshire members were entitled to hope that Lara would fulfil his contract.
He will not.
The reason? There is far too much international cricket played; far too many
Tests and infinitely far too many dreary, meaningless one-day matches.
The tournament which Lara has opted out of was just such a tedious affair, and
the player himself shows good judgment here.
More significantly, he has just been fined because he went AWOL on part of last
season's English tour. The first-class game the world over is underpinned by
the County championship in England.
It not only produces English players, but cricketers worldwide use it to learn
their trade. There is literally nowhere else to do this.
Now, England supremo Ray Illingworth proposes to take powers to compel the
counties to drop their England players from their sides in the run-up to
England Test matches.
Fred Trueman was a considerably better bowler than anything available to
England at the moment, and he prepared for Tests by bowling fast in County
matches, not by theorising in the nets.
Surrey, or Somerset, or Yorkshire have, at the most, nine home County fixtures
per season and now may well lose their star turns for four or five of these
matches.
This is bound to happen as the counties lose control of the game in the short
term, as the FA have lost it to the Premiership, and the SRU may well do to a
handful of powerful clubs.
It is bound to happen as the new breed of sporting entrepreneurs proclaim
glibly that sport is now a ``managed event'' rather than the glorious
uncertainty we always took it to be.
Fine, if you realise that the price you pay in going after passing trade may
well be the permanent alienation of your former regular customers.
In football terms, ``the good news, Walter, is that Andy Goram is back in the
Scotland side. The bad news is that he misses your next five league matches.''
Great batsmen are not wound up by keys in their backs. They don't become great
by participating in ersatz bunfights.
Seems to me we owe Lara a nod of gratitude.
</TEXT>
