<HEADLINE>`Len' has last laugh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Victoria Freedman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142977</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Leonard Cohen, once branded a boring old drone, is now fted as one of the
greatest and most literate songwriters
HE was called the Godfather of Gloom or Laughing Len if you wanted a touch of
irony; the man whose music you should listen to if contemplating suicide (or as
some would have it, you might contemplate suicide after listening to his
music). He was the man with the lugubrious features who sang dolefully of love
ending, of passion spent, in songs like Suzanne, So Long Marianne, Sister of
Mercy . . . Or as one British music paper summed him up somewhat unkindly -
Leonard Cohen was a boring old drone who should get back to Canada where he
belonged.
But that was a long time ago. In a dramatic revival of his career with the
fabulous 1989 album, I'm Your Man, followed by The Future, critics finally
hailed him as one of the greatest and most literate songwriters of our time,
even recognising the wit and euphonies in his work that had always been
overlooked in favour of the pessimism and pain.
``They've started being quite charitable, even downright complimentary in
Europe and Canada,'' he says in a gloriously deep and sensual voice, as you
would expect from a man who sings, especially about sex, on the same scale as
Barry White.
``But in America I still have to justify the fact that I dare to sing. It's
pretty well accepted that I know how to write a song but the conventional
wisdom is that I should leave it to others to sing them. I can't say my
feelings are hurt. It amuses me.''
The Americans then, will no doubt approve of a newly released tribute album of
his songs, which features an impressive line-up of stars including Elton John,
Bono, Sting, and Peter Gabriel, all paying their respects to the musical poet.
Leonard Cohen, a polite and unassuming man, appears to be genuinely delighted
that people still wish to listen to his music, huge-ly flattered that singers
should wish to record his tunes, and these days impervious to critics.
He began his writing career as a poet, which brought international recognition
while still in his early twenties, then turned to prose with two novels, The
Favourite Game, a portrait of the artist as a young Jew in Montreal, and
Beautiful Losers. ``James Joyce is not dead,'' declared one critic. ``He is
living in Montreal under the name of Cohen.''
``A friend of mine, a great Canadian poet, said the two characteristics
essential to a young poet are arrogance and inexperience. I had plenty of both
so when they compared me with James Joyce I thought, `Yes, that's about right'.
I have a somewhat different view of it now,'' he says with a wry smile.
Cohen left Canada long ago and now lives in California, in a Zen monastery,
6000 feet up a mountain. He rises at three o'clock in the morning and proceeds
to the meditation hall where he sits upright on a cushion for a few hours, his
eyes closed, his knees crossed, his mind open. After breakfast he works -
shovelling paths, cooking, cleaning - then returns to meditate further.
In the evening he often sits in the cabin of the 87-year-old Zen monk who
founded the retreat, the Roshi, where even a discussion of the vodka they are
drinking carries a philosophical flavour. Cohen first became interested in the
practice of Za Zen 25 years ago, and since it required neither theological
discussion about the nature of God nor worship it did not come into conflict
with his family religion of Judaism.
``I was taught to swim by being thrown into a lake. This was the same. Nobody
told me what I'm supposed to think or where I'm to hold my mind. I just knew
that sitting there with myself seemed to have some nourishing capacity. It's
hard to do alone. I often do, but find the companionship of others very
helpful.''
So two years ago he moved from a modest flat in Los Angeles and settled in the
monastery, joining four monks and two students. Now he has near-resident
status, living in a little guest house where he keeps his synthesiser so he can
continue to write.
``It's a very nice way to live. A long time ago my mother said: `Follow your
little heart.' And I guess that's what I'm doing.
``Like anything else that's important or touches you deeply it's hard to
describe but it's the way I keep in touch with my heart, with what's really
true. It also keeps my back straight,'' he adds, his mouth twitching into a
faint ironic smile.
Ensconced in his guest house, Cohen is writing a new collection of songs, and
when finished, perhaps sometime next year, is considering a tour.
``Writing is my lover. I have this intimate feeling, like being in the embrace
of one's beloved. Though it can be infuriating. Someone is whispering to me but
it's often inaudible. You can't always hear what your beloved is saying. I
often beg for the whispers to be louder or clearer.''
The words may not always come easily but he now feels a necessity to write, a
need to hear himself ``speaking from a deep place''. Does it help him get
through life?
``I don't know. I've pretty well made a mess of that. Well, everybody makes a
mess of it in some way,'' he explains. ``You hurt people, structures you tried
to establish fail, you weren't the kind of friend, or father, you meant to be.''
Although he never married the mother of his children, Cohen is, in fact,
gratified by the relationship he shares with them. His daughter, Lorca, 21, has
a coffee shop in Los Angeles, while Adam, 22, has a band and thinks his father
is suitably talented to have all the credentials for a long and agonising life
in art.
``My father died when I was nine and it left me in a kind of ignorance about
how to be a father, so I'm very pleased to have maintained a closeness with my
kids even though we were separated a lot of the time. I didn't take to
domesticity,'' he admits. ``I avoided it at every possible instance.''
Cohen, a small man with cropped grey hair and dressed entirely in black, is now
61.
``I find it a very agreeable age,'' he says. ``Men mature late in our society.
It's very different for women but men really don't start to get a handle on
things until their fifties. And people are kind to you for some reason.
Policemen are nice. Customs officials are polite and women seem to forgive you
for many things which they found unforgivable when you were younger. It's very
agreeable.
``My Zen teacher said: `The older you get the lonelier you become and the
deeper the love you need.' I think it's very true and I'm fortunate that my
closest friends are still those I knew in school and that I still see the very
first woman I ever slept with - I think that's lovely.
``But I do have some young woman friends. As a friend of mine said when he was
well into his seventies, beauty never ceases to wield its tyrannies and its
terrors, and its promises . . .''
Leonard Cohen smiles at the thought. The Godfather of Gloom looks happy enough.
n Tower of Song - the Songs of Leonard Cohen was released on A &amp; M Records last
month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
