<HEADLINE>Scotland ill-served by legislators, claims MP</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142978</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE democratic deficit faced by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth when he
unveils his constititutional reforms tomorrowis highlighted in a report showing
that five in every six pieces of recent legislation applying to Scotland have
been tagged on to English and Welsh legislation.
``The Tory Party has become so pro-English as to subject Scotland to weak
clauses tagged on to essentially English legislation,'' argued Scottish Liberal
Democrat parliamentary spokeswoman Ray Michie yesterday.
She was publishing a report based on figures gathered from the House of Commons
library demonstrating how marginalised Scottish legislation has become in
recent years, with English Tory MPs packing committees and Scottish matters
simply appended to inappropriate English measures.
``Scottish legislation has been bullied through the House of Commons in an
unacceptable manner, with little attention having been paid to the wishes of
the Scottish people,'' said Argyll and Bute MP Mrs Michie.
She said Conservative measures, such as boosting the Scottish Grand Committee,
did not go nearly far enough.
``The Government's rhetoric has so far exceeded its action. A talking shop is
no substitute for a Scottish Parliament.''
Her study found three symptoms of the deficit: too many Bills were tagged on to
inappropriate English legislation; committees considering these Bills had far
too few Scottish members; and those Scottish Bills which were considered
usually had English Tory MP's appointed to ensure a Tory majority at committee
stage.
``Scottish issues are all too easily overlooked in the desire for legislation
to be rushed through Parliament. This year, just as in the past, Scotland has
had to make do with English oversights,'' she said.
</TEXT>
