<HEADLINE>Lively by name . . .</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>road tests</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142979</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay finds the Almera has an identity of its own
NISSAN chose the name Almera for its new car to replace the Sunny, partly on
the grounds that it is pronounced the same way in all European languages. And
yet, I have heard some people call it the Almeera while others automatically
say Almayra. There is just no standardising folk!
Model names are often a problem, partly because so many possibilities are
legally reserved by companies who may never use them. There is a minor industry
in researching and nabbing likely names. That is one reason why so many
companies moved on to model numbers, but customers, especially in Japan, do not
like them. Names are not intercontinental, though. In Japan the Almera is
called the Pulsar.
Anyway, Nissan hopes that Almera is a livelier kind of name than Sunny. The new
model shows that the company wants to branch out and attract more, as well as
different, customers, and not just the ones who would automatically replace one
Sunny with another.
There is no doubt that the Sunny had an image which many younger and perhaps
sportier people did not think of as their own, despite the model's successes in
competition. Alister McRae, after all, won this year's top UK rally
championship in a Sunny GTi.
However, there is a curiosity about Nissan's UK customers which I had not
appreciated until somebody mentioned it at the launch of the Almera. The
motoring press regarded the little 100NX coupe as pretty much of a failure,
dismissing it as what some people sneeringly refer to as a hairdresser's car.
And yet, when it slipped off the market, Nissan had so many outstanding orders
for it here, and more in the pipeline, that the company moved production to
another factory and kept building it in smaller numbers for six more months.
Despite all the statistics about company cars, something like one third of all
new car registrations in this country every year are small family types like
the Almera. Nissan seems to be in a stronger position with the Almera, when you
set it against its class rivals, than it ever was, using the same comparison
year by year with the Sunny.
I am surprised that some critics have given the Almera a fairly lukewarm
reception. The 1.4-litre three-door Si I have been driving, with the Loden
green exterior which shines like a fluorescent beacon in a crowded car park, is
a car with a strong identity of its own, something which was always lacking in
the different generations of Sunny.
The front-end treatment provides a family styling link with the Primera, and I
prefer the three-door's generally simpler appearance to the rear-end of the
five-door. That version follows the trend to rather confused lines which the
Scottish Motor Show demonstrated is ``catching'' throughout many rival model
ranges.
At #10,495 the test car came with the mid-range Almera specification, providing
a good range of interior equipment and lively trim. The 1392cc engine peaks at
88bhp, allowing a 0-60mph time of about 12.5 seconds and a test track maximum
around 105mph. According to the new EC calculations, it is likely to average
about 40mpg in normal use.
Except in its more sporting guises, the Sunny was not a car which enjoyed
itself when you tried to explore its handling limits. The Almera is different,
thanks not only to the whole plan to give it a more youthful feel, but also, in
hardware terms, to the multi-link rear suspension borrowed and scaled-down from
Nissan's flagship QX saloon.
The handling is transformed, on fast corners as well as on the kind of
up-and-down country roads with bends over brows which would unsettle most types
of Sunny. In fact, although this is a judgment I heartily dislike pronouncing,
the Almera could happily cope with more power than the 1.4-litre model offers.
Of course, that is why there is also a 1.6.
</TEXT>
