<HEADLINE>Price is the master</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOWLS
DEFENDING champion John Price and three-times world indoor champion Richard
Corsie both eased through their opening matches in the CIS Insurance Masters at
Coatbridge yesterday and will meet in the semi-finals this afternoon.
Price was the first in action and battled to a 7-3, 7-5 win over East Lothian's
Graham Robertson in a repeat of last year's final.
The Welshman was quickly joined in the last four by Corsie, who needed just
seven ends to defeat Irelands' world outdoor champion, Margaret Johnston, 7-1,
7-1.
Robertson picked up a double on the opening end of his clash with Price, but
immediately dropped behind when the defending champion counted three shots on
the second end.
The players then traded singles to leave Price 4-3 ahead before the Swansea man
stepped in with another count of 3 to take the opening set.
The East Lothian man dropped singles on the first two ends of the second set,
but then a double and a single pushed him 3-2 ahead.
Doubles on the next two ends took Price to within one of victory at 6-3, but
Robertson countered with two singles to be only one down going into the ninth
end.
Price struck with his penultimate delivery and pushed the jack into the ditch.
Robertson drew to within a yard with his last bowl, but Price proved more than
up to the task by drawing shot with his last bowl.
While Price had to work hard for his win Corsie got things all his own way in
the battle of the Commonwealth champions. The Scot started and finished in
style with a maximum 4 on the opening end and the last for the easiest of
victories.
Tweedbank`s Joyce Lindores lost out in the battle of the world champions last
night when Andy Thomson coasted to a 7-3, 7-0 victory in 11 ends.
Thomson led 4-3 after four ends of the opening set and Lindores failed to score
again as the England international wrapped up a comfortable win.
Scottish champion Paul Conlan joined Thomson in the semi-finals with a 0-7,
7-6, 7-5 victory over fellow-Scot Alex Marshall.
GORDON DUNWOODIE
</TEXT>
