<HEADLINE>Mitsubishi boss airs his views on devolution.  Business leaders urged to go public</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, Scottish Political Correspondent  Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE head of a major Japanese electronic plant is going public to urge the rest
of corporate Scotland to be less wary of constitutional change and to join in a
productive debate about the future.
In the run-up to tomorrow's St Andrew's Day unveiling of the rival
constitutional options, there have been claims and counter-claims about the
attitude of the business community to change. These have been based mainly on
anonymous rumblings of concern or optimism.
Now the head of the Mitsubishi video recorder factory at Livingston has put his
head above the parapet of corporate Scotland to add his voice publicly to the
debate.
Mr Alan Gemmell has agreed to appear on the St Andrew's night edition of Words
with Wark on BBC tomorrow to discuss the options and to urge other business
leaders to do the same.
``I can only give a personal view,'' said Mr Gemmell yesterday. ``As a company,
we are very strong on Scotland and we have four manufacturing plants here.
``If people ask whether in the light of political change would we be pulling
out or reducing our investment here, the answer is obviously not - we are
already committed here.''
Mr Gemmell said Scotland was competing for business with the likes of the
Republic of Ireland and Spain and any future Scottish political administration
would have to recognise that. ``If they did anything to damage inward
investment, that would be particularly irresponsible.''
He confirmed that by this he meant that he did not believe such
irresponsibility was likely, which was why he was perhaps less fearful of
change than some in the business community.
``A lot of it is fear of the unknown,'' he said. ``A lot of those who do not
want to take part in the debate just don't know the answers. People are wary of
something that may or may not be coming from a party line.
``A Scottish Assembly would be Labour-orientated and I am not so sure that the
Labour Party has got to grips with what industry wants. The Scottish Office has
the tint of Mr Lang and Mr Forsyth. Labour still has to find its feet.
``There is also the fact that we have had one Government for so long, even
without the devolution issue there is a nervousness about change.''
Mitsubishi opened its television plant at Haddington in East Lothian in 1979
and the video factory at Livingston in 1983, the year Mr Gemmell joined the
company.
The firm also manufactures air-conditioning equipment in the West Lothian new
town, and at Glenrothes in Fife they produce Apricot personal computers. Total
employment in Scotland is 2000.
Words with Wark producer Alan Clements said yesterday: ``I would laud Alan
Gemmell's bravery in putting his head above the parapet.
``It is difficult for the business community and they are sometimes reluctant
to get embroiled in what they see as political controversy but we believe it is
important to get business people to join in the debate.''
</TEXT>
