<HEADLINE>BUILDING MATERIALS Norcros stable</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORCROS shareholders are still waiting for details of the proposed flotation of
its print and packaging division, but chairman Michael Doherty said he was
determined the matter would be settled by the end of this financial year,
writes ANDREW WILSON.
Meanwhile, the interim results show continued pressure in print and packaging
although ceramics enjoyed a marginal improvement, so the combined operating
profit from the continuing businesses was stable at #10.9m.
The impact of the restructuring which will result in Norcros turning into a
ceramics-only business has considerably distorted the pre-tax total. The sale
of the five building products activities brought in #51.4m in cash which threw
up some #12m of surplus with another #1m coming from the release of earlier
provisions to boost stated pre-tax profits by #9.72m to #18.7m.
Although Norcros has ended up with earnings of 2.2p per share from actual
trading and 9.8p including the asset surplus, the lack of distributable
reserves means no dividend can be paid.
The shares eased 3p to 75p with sentiment affected by Monday's warning from
Spring Ram about the continuing difficulties in the building sector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
