<DOCNO>GH951129-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Small no match for O'Sullivan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNOOKER
RONNIE O'Sullivan reached the last eight of the Royal Liver Assurance UK
Championship yesterday and boasted: ``I have got more ability than anyone else
left in the tournament.''
The former champion, who completed a 9-2 demolition of Scotland's Chris Small
in Preston, said: ``If I hit form I can win it again. But I cannot really look
forward any further than my next match. There are no easy games and I've got a
tough quarter-final coming up.''
O'Sullivan began with a 7-1 overnight lead and although Small won the first
frame of the day, it was only delaying the inevitable. Twenty-seven minutes
later he cruised into the last eight, helped by breaks of 42 and 38.
``If I'm playing well, I can say I have won a tournament even before it
started,'' added the 19-year-old from Essex. ``That's how confident I feel.
``When I am flowing, it's a beautiful game. It's something you can't explain.
Only a sportsman knows what its like when their game comes together. It's so
easy and the best feeling in the world.''
Desite the world No.3's insistence that there are no longer any pushovers, he
has enjoyed an easy passage into the quarter-finals - Edinburgh-based Small is
the lowest ranked player he has faced.
The 22-year-old Scot failed to make a game of it during yesterday's first
session and said: ``I'm usually full of nerves before and during the match, but
I felt nothing. Perhaps that's the reason why I couldn't get going.''
Meanwhile, Stephen Hendry yesterday landed a lucrative five-year deal with
snooker equipment manufacturer E J Riley.
The world champion, who faces Irishman Ken Doherty in today's quarter-finals,
has signed a contract which will earn him around #660,000.
Hendry has been associated with the Lancashire-based firm since the early
stages of his career and the present deal will take him to the year 2000.
</TEXT>
