<HEADLINE>450-mile car dash to help patient</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERY breath taken by a critically ill two-year-old girl was being monitored by
doctors and nurses last night after a 106mph dash by a relay of police cars.
The cars delivered a vital piece of fibre-optic tube 450 miles from Kent to the
Royal Hospital for Sick Children at Yorkhill, Glasgow.
The through-the-night journey, completed in four hours and 17 minutes, was made
in response to a plea from the hospital to Abbott Laboratories, in Sheerness.
It came after the girl, who has not been named, had been admitted from
Lanarkshire suffering from meningococcal septicaemia - blood poisoning caused
by the bacterium responsible for meningitis.
The fibre-optic catheter was inserted through a vein in the girl's neck and
passed along to the heart.
Dr Pim Kon, Abbott's senior medical adviser, said last night: ``The tube is
connected at the other end to a machine which the hospital already has. It
operates by shining a light at the heart area and measuring the level of the
reflection.
``The amount of light absorbed by the tissues is computed to measure how the
heart and lungs are performing. This lets the staff know how much oxygen and
fluids to give the patient.''
Two of the #150 tubes were delivered after inquiries at other hospitals in
Scotland and the North of England failed to turn up any of the right size.
The first leg of the journey north, by police traffic car, took the equipment
to Lancashire. A Kent Police spokeswoman said: ``We handed it over to the
Lancashire force and it was relayed from there to Glasgow via police in
Cumbria, Dumfries and Galloway and Strathclyde.''
A special lane and toll booth were opened at the Dartford Tunnel in Kent.
Further north, a closed section of the M6 was reopened to allow the police cars
and their cargo through.
A hospital spokesman said: ``We are tremendously grateful to the police. The
equipment will help us monitor the little girl's heart output over the next 48
hours, which will be critical.''
</TEXT>
