<HEADLINE>Republicans may back plan to send American peacekeepers to Bosnia Clinton wins first round</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
PRESIDENT Clinton has made a ``good start'', according to Senator Bob Dole, in
persuading Congress to support his Bosnia policy.
Mr Clinton addressed the nation last night, and the broadcast was carried on
all the networks, and he justified sending 20,000 troops to Bosnia, but his
chief audience was in Washington.
He does not need immediate Congressional support, but if the US contingent is
to stay in Bosnia for the ``year or more'' that the planners expect, the
president will need Congress to find the money. So his main objective is to
convince members of Congress that the operation is in the national interest.
He appears to have persuaded Mr Dole, uncontested leader of the Republicans,
which means that the Senate will follow him.
The senator said today: ``I want to support the president if I can. We have
only one president at a time in this country.''
He added: ``There comes a time when you have to be responsible and show
leadership,'' and that meant Congressional leaders standing up to support the
president.
A number of other influential senators, on both parties, stated that they were
inclined to support the president, with the same lack of enthusiasm shown by Mr
Dole.
Senator Phil Gramm, who is running for president, seized the opportunity to
distinguish himself by denouncing Mr Clinton's proposals. That will not be
enough to defeat the president.
The House of Representatives will be far more difficult.
The president will probably get the support of most of the Democrats, and will
therefore need 50 or so Republicans.
Several polls published today show that a majority of Americans oppose sending
troops to Bosnia.
Meanwhile, Bosnian Serbs today backtracked on warnings of bloodshed over Nato's
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia. Bosnian Serb ``president'' Radovan Karadzic
said from his base in Pale, near Sarajevo: ``If American troops come here in a
friendly manner, they will find Serbs friendly. If foreign troops behave
completely impartially, they will find friends.''
His statement contrasted with earlier threats of carnage, Nato casualties going
home in body bags and a long struggle which would turn Sarajevo into another
Beirut.
Karadzic said Serbs wanted a peaceful solution to their demand to keep Sarajevo
suburbs where they have always lived, but which are due to be put under Bosnian
government control.
q Nato and Russia tonight reached an historic deal that has paved the way for
the Russians to play a full role in the Alliance-led peace mission to Bosnia.
``This is truly an historic day for Nato,'' said American Defence Secretary
William Perry after talks with Russian defence chief Pavel Grachev.
French Defence Minister Charles Millon said Russia and Nato had agreed a
formula for political control of the Bosnia operation, the last stumbling block
to Russian participation.
The Russian minister said later he was satisfied today's deal answered all
Moscow's concerns and would be approved by his government.
An earlier deal had already been struck allowing Russian forces to take part
without coming under the direct command of Alliance generals.
Today's deal not only clears the way for an unprecedented joint US-Russian
peacekeeping unit but also marks an important step toward closer political and
military co-operation between Moscow and its old Cold War enemy, Nato.
Grachev said about 1500 Russian troops would now join the Nato-led peace force.
They will be part of a multinational unit comprised mainly of members of the US
Army's 1st Armored Division and commanded by American Major General William
Nash.-Reuter/AP
</TEXT>
