<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two-ton Chinese spy satellite may plunge back to Earth, US warns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colorado Springs
A TWO-TON Chinese spy satellite could streak disastrously back to Earth next
April, American air force trackers warned today.
A spokesman for the US Space Command in Colorado Springs said it was too early
to predict where it might land, if it does not burn up on re-entry.
Aviation Week and Space Technology magazine reported that the FSW-1 satellite,
launched in October 1993, was passing over most of the world's heavily
populated areas, including central Europe.
If its parachute works and it has a ``soft'' landing, it could provide valuable
information about Chinese intelligence capabilities. But the US Air Force is
more concerned about it streaking to Earth in a populated area, said the
spokesman.
The Space Command tracks space debris and has a list of items larger than one
yard square that have more than a 5% chance of returning to Earth intact.
``Anything that could cause damage to lives or property goes on that list,''
said the spokesman. ``We expect this item to go on that list.''
Meanwhile Nasa said today it plans to send a spacecraft to within 62 miles of a
comet to capture dust samples and bring them back to Earth for analysis.
``This is the first time since the Apollo programme in the 1970s that a sample
of something interplanetary will be collected and returned to Earth,'' said Ken
Atkins, project manager at Nasa's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
The spacecraft, Stardust, will be launched in February 1999 and will hurtle
through the solar system toward a fly-by of the comet Wild-2 in January 2004.
According to the plan, a return capsule bearing the comet particles will
parachute into a dry Utah lake bed in January 2006.
q China's official Xinhua news agency confirmed that Hong Kong's #150m AsiaSat
2 satellite had been placed successfully into orbit today after its launch from
southwestern Sichuan province atop a Chinese-made rocket. It gave no further
details.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Postal strike flares again at Hamilton</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE postal dispute erupted again yesterday when 70 staff failed to return to
work at Hamilton, despite voting in favour of ending their walk-out.
Royal Mail management said it was bitterly disappointed at the ``pointless
disruption'' which centred on union calls to have a manager switched from the
Hamilton sorting office.
Postal services were disrupted throughout Scotland last week by unoffical
action. A back-to-work deal involving the 5000 strikers was agreed on Sunday.
Hamilton, the only place where the strike was official, recorded a similar vote
on Monday.
However, when the Hamilton night-shift staff arrived for work, they were
infuriated to find Mr Gordon Johnson - who was part of a team drafted into the
office 16 weeks ago to improve working practices, in the office, despite
earlier demands that he be moved.
The night-shift workers mounted a picket and were joined by 70 postmen at
4.30am yesterday.
One of the pickets, Mr John Lynas, a union official for Lanarkshire, said: ``We
were told on Saturday when we met Royal Mail that Mr Johnson would be moved. He
was not. We will not return to work until he goes.''
Mr Steve Cameron, Royal Mail area manager, said: ``We are bitterly disappointed
that customers in Hamilton will suffer further disruption. Staff voted to
return to work on Monday and there were no conditions on that return.''
Mr Cameron said that - despite advice given by the Royal Mail, by the
Communication Workers' Union divisional representatives, the staff vote, and
the wishes of their own customers - the CWU area representative had chosen to
continue the pointless disruption. ``I would urge staff in Hamilton to consider
their customers and return to work,'' he added.
Mr George Robertson, divisional representative of CWU in Scotland and Northern
Ireland, said there was now a danger of the dispute escalating.
He said: ``Many members from other areas are getting upset that Hamilton cannot
get back to normal working. We understood the back-to-work agreement meant the
removal of the so-called policing managers appointed to thrust the new methods
on us.''
There was further controversy when pickets reported to police that a Royal Mail
driver had run down one of their colleagues, who was slightly injured.
More than 5000 Scottish postal workers returned to work on Monday and began
clearing a 12 million-letter backlog which built up during the strike.
Last night, Royal Mail management said staff were pulling out all the stops to
clear the backlog. A spokesman said: ``In the worst affected areas, it will
take one week to clear.''
</TEXT>
