<HEADLINE>Potato processors urged to buy British</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142990</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POTATO processors in Britain should respond to the ending of the quota system
by cutting imports and increasing their use of home-grown potatoes, it was
suggested yesterday.
John Heading, chairman of the Potato Marketing Board, said the clarion call
from Government and processors had been: ``Get rid of quotas and regulation and
you will get investment in facilities to process more British potatoes in
British factories.''
It was now time for the processors to deliver on that call, he told the board's
annual meeting in London.
It is estimated imports of processed potatoes amount to about 700,000 tonnes a
year - mostly frozen chips.
``We know we do not have a divine right to grow these potatoes but we have
delivered the quota-free market which the processors wanted,'' Mr Heading said.
``We do have the expertise. We have a track record of reliable supply. We have
a good disease record. We have invested in the technology, the storage and the
structure to expand potato production to meet real market needs in the late
nineties.
``The sight of boatloads of Dutch and Belgian potatoes coming into our ports -
some from areas with considerable disease risks - is galling.''
Mr Heading called for the utmost vigilance to prevent the spread of brown rot
from Holland to the UK. ``We want to ensure no infected potatoes of any sort -
seed or ware - come into this country,'' he said.
He expressed concern that there were significant quantities of ware grade
potatoes already in the country which might not have been subject to the
rigorous inspection now being demanded. The Ministry of Agriculture had
deployed a team of 200 inspectors to examine all consignments.
Jim Cruickshank of Inverurie, vice-chairman of the board, said all growers
should be alert to the dangers of brown rot. The disease, which is notifiable
in the UK, causes tuber rotting and, therefore, a serious reduction in yields.
If it became established here it would pose a threat to the seed potato
industry, particularly in export markets. Infected land could be taken out of
production for five years.
The Potato Marketing Board chairman said the industry must guard against
falling consumption especially at times of high prices. This could be done only
if consumers were constantly reminded about the quality, nutrition and value
for money of home-grown potatoes.
``Stable prices for quality potatoes leading to steadily increasing demand is
our goal,'' he said. ``We have to put money into achieving that over the long
term.''
He said next year, which had been declared a no-quota year for potato growers,
would be a dry run for deregulation in 1997. In most respects the operation of
the Potato Marketing Board in 1996 would mirror the likely operation of its
successor body the following year.
There was good news on exports, he said with 1994-95 the best year on record
for British ware potatoes. Growers and merchants had been able to take
advantage of poorer yields and quality in continental Europe.
</TEXT>
