<HEADLINE>Real problems ignored, claim elderly</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142991</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE groups representing vulnerable sectors of society found little to
cheer in the Budget. Citizens' Advice Scotland criticised the cutbacks for
single parents, claiming it would cost them up to #300 a year.
Chief executive Martyn Evans said: ``I am also disappointed at the cuts in
housing benefit for young people who are, in increasing numbers, vulnerable,
facing rising housing costs or even the plight of homelessness. However, I
welcome the increases in child-care allowance as a small step in the right
direction.''
His views were shared by One Parent Families Scotland, which speaks for about
140,000 people. Spokesman Ian Maxwell said: ``Lone parents and their families
are overall losers in this Budget. The income tax cuts will do nothing for the
majority of lone parents who live on or below the tax threshold.
``Cutting welfare benefits paid to lone parents won't stop marriages breaking
down or relationships splitting, but it will make it even harder for lone
parents to make ends meet.''
Mr John Findlay, of One Plus, said: ``There can be no excuse for taking away
benefits which so many families need simply to survive.
``Any cut to one-parent benefit penalises parents struggling to rebuild family
life for their children by taking up employment, and is contrary to the
Government's stated aim of helping lone parents to escape benefits.''
The Scottish Low Pay Unit said the Budget had left low paid workers in the slow
lane while those on higher incomes would contribute even less to the
maintenance of public services.
Director Morag Gillespie said: ``This Budget is targeted at savings, financial
provision for old age, and people with personal wealth to pass to descendants.
``Low-paid workers struggle to manage from day to day and they have no scope to
set cash aside in the form of property, assets or other investments.
``The Scottish Low Pay Unit has a question for the Chancellor. How do you
benefit from savings and inheritance when you haven't got a penny to spare?''
Housing groups were also critical of Mr Kenneth Clarke. Shelter said the
decision to cut housing benefit to young people would lead to more homelessness.
Depute director Kate Caskie said: ``The Chancellor claimed that these proposals
will encourage young people to rent within their means. Many young people have
no means and will not be able to rent at all.''
The Scottish Federation of Housing Associations added: ``The Chancellor has
offered tax cuts for short-term political gain. What was needed was investment
for long-term economic and social gain.''
``Cuts in housing benefit are vindictive and counterproductive. The Budget
demonstrates that the Government cares little for those in real need.''
</TEXT>
