<HEADLINE>Bid to reunify railway wins unexpected ally</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON, Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142993</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE campaign to reunite Railtrack and ScotRail has received backing from the
most unexpected of quarters - Swedish Railways, a front-runner in the
European-wide break-up of the industry.
Sweden approved a plan to separate ownership, responsibility for track,
signalling, and other infrastructure from the operation and running of trains
in 1988.
Its experience since then, judged a success, is widely regarded as the model
for the Tories' relentless drive towards rail privatisation in the UK since
1993.
But Swedish Railways' managing director, Mr Stig Larsson, has now concluded
that the decision to separate infrastructure from operations was wrong - and
that Sweden's railways benefited when kept together, according to delegates at
an international conference.
Mr Richard Prosser, general secretary of the Transport Salaried Staffs'
Association, said yesterday that Mr Larsson's comments were ``an
embarrassment'' to the Government, which has repeatedly cited the Swedish
experience when justifying privatisation.
Mr Larsson, at the International Transport Workers' Federation conference in
Budapest, appeared to argue that newly created railway companies were concerned
more with individual balance sheets than the network and services as a whole.
The conference, discussing concerns over changes in structure and ownership in
an increasing number of countries, subsequently called for infrastructure and
operations to be reunited.
Mr Larsson's declaration that those in charge of infrastructure had different
priorities than train operators coincided with the Rail Users' Consultative
Committee for Scotland warning that the split between ScotRail and Railtrack
was not working.
The break-up was damaging - diverting money, time, and effort away from
improving services and infrastructure - and there was no sense in having two
separate organisations ``to do what one did before, and did well''.
Mr Larsson's comments also coincide with increasing fears that Railtrack will
be sold at a give-away price because the Government is so eager to press on
with privatisation.
The conflict in Sweden over railway fragmentation has arisen despite a
restructuring far less radical than that underway in Britain.
For example, the private sector's input has been made easier in Sweden, because
it need not worry about investing in trains. The Government also provides the
infrastructure, with spending now running at three times the level prior to
1988.
Indeed, a trawl of European railway operators reveals that the UK programme is
``exceptional''.
Not only is the infrastructure owner, Railtrack, required to be
self-supporting, but train operators are subsidised to enable them to meet the
access charges.
In Sweden, where the majority of services remain in state hands, only a third
of track maintenance costs are recouped in access charges from train operators.
</TEXT>
