<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tour could spark revival</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142995</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DARREN Gough believes a successful winter in South Africa could be just the
spark England need to start soaring up the world ratings.
Overall, England have looked more like chumps than champs in recent years -
losing five of their last eight series and beating only New Zealand.
But Gough pointed out: ``When we perform well, no-one in the world could beat
us.
``We showed that in Adelaide last winter by defeating Australia and twice
against West Indies during the summer.
``The problem is we are not having enough of those days. We need a good series
here to set it alight.''
England are certainly bubbling with optimism at present - and rightly so - as
they start preparing for tomorrow's second Test at The Wanderers.
The opening match of the series in Pretoria may have been ruined by rain, but
the way Mike Atherton and co. stood up to South Africa's prized pace attack was
highly encouraging.
``If it had been on a points system, we would have won the first Test,'' said
Gough. ``But now we have to start again and treat the game in Johannesburg as
the opening match of the series.''
Meanwhile, England's cricketers have been told not to worry about their safety
in the aftermath of the fatal shooting which took place during a boxing match
in Cape Town earlier this week.
England, who are based in Johannesburg for the second Test, have been assured
that there is no problem with security in a city regarded as one of the world's
most dangerous with muggings and shootings every day events.
</TEXT>
