<HEADLINE>Israelis pound Lebanon after rocket attacks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142996</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tyre, Lebanon
ISRAEL launched three air raids on Muslim guerrilla targets in south Lebanon
today after Katyusha rockets hit northern Israel.
The planes struck at areas used by guerrillas for infiltrating into Israel's
south Lebanon occupation zone.
Hizbollah earlier claimed responsibility for Katyusha rocket barrages that
wounded several people in northern Israel in the terror group's fiercest attack
for months.
Tens of thousands of frightened Israelis were sent scurrying into bomb shelters
across Galilee and Prime Minister Shimon Peres later visited the border area
and inspected one of several heavily damaged blocks of flats.
Waves of rockets slammed into eastern and western Galilee, damaging houses and
cars in a barrage that began when Israeli parents were taking their children to
school.
A first aid official in the northern town of Kiryat Shmona said four people
were slightly wounded by shrapnel and about 30 others were treated for shock.
In the first wave of Israel's response jets fired up to a dozen rockets in
three runs into Wadi al-Qaysiyyeh, a valley used by pro-Iranian Hizbollah
guerrillas for launching attacks.
In a second raid, jets rocketed an abandoned Lebanese army barracks on the edge
of the market town of Nabatiyeh before returning more than an hour later for a
third raid, firing another 12 rockets into Wadi al-Izzieh and other valleys
swarming with guerrillas, security sources said.
Hizbollah guerrillas in Lebanon had earlier mounted their fiercest rocket
attack on northern Israel in months.
Peres visited the border area and inspected one of several heavily damaged
apartment buildings.
Visiting the border town of Kiryat Shmona, Interior Security Minister Moshe
Shahal said: ``The Israeli government . . . response must be effective, strong
and of a scope that will ensure these events do not occur again.''
The waves of Katyusha rockets drew a warning from Israel's army chief that the
last active war front between Israel and its Arab neighbours could heat up.
``Hizbollah is endangering the well-being of many thousands of residents of
south Lebanon . . . I think the Lebanese government also should be very
troubled over what Hizbollah is doing within Lebanese territory,''
Lieutenant-General Amnon Shahak said.
Minutes after Shahak spoke, security sources in Lebanon said Israeli jets
blasted suspected guerrilla hideouts.
Waves of rockets slammed into eastern and western Galilee, damaging houses and
cars in a barrage that began when Israeli parents were taking their children to
school.
A first aid official in the northern town of Kiryat Shmona said four people
were slightly wounded by shrapnel and about 30 others were treated for shock.
Hizbollah, at the forefront of a fight to oust Israeli soldiers from an
occupation zone in south Lebanon, claimed responsibility for the attacks.
q A senior Syrian official said today remarks by Israeli Foreign Minister Ehud
Barak were positive but Damascus needed action, not words, from Israel.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
