<HEADLINE>National Savings bonus for pensioners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>budget 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975142997</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was only one change in National Savings' products in the Budget but it
was an important one for pensioners.
From today, the qualifying age for buying the Pensioners' Bond has been reduced
from 65 to 60 and the maximum holding is increased from #20,000 to #50,000
(#100,000 for joint holdings).
The bond is a highly competitive product, with the current series paying 7.5%
fixed for five years, after which a new fixed rate is offered. Income is paid
monthly and is paid gross with no tax deducted.
After the new 20% rate on interest income takes effect next April, the net rate
will be 6% compared with 5.62% at present.
National Savings is forecast to increase its contribution to the Government's
coffers from #2500m to #3000m for 1995-96 and the new rules for the Pensioners'
Bond are likely to pull in much of this increase, largely at the expense of the
building societies.
Economic Secretary to the Treasury Angela Knight said the changes were what
pensioners had been asking for.
``Many retire earlier and want a good return on their money. The Pensioners'
Guaranteed Income Bond gives more people a good fixed return on their
savings,'' she declared.
q The earnings cap on which the maximum level of pension contributions to an
occupational or personal pension scheme is calculated has been uprated in line
with inflation to #82,200.
</TEXT>
