<HEADLINE>Strathclyde's Pignatelli turns down post with the new Glasgow council Schools director gives up #94,500</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975142998</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE director of Strathclyde's education authority is to quit local government
in April, when he will join the ranks of the unemployed.
Mr Frank Pignatelli, who has run the region's education service since 1988 and
earns #94,500 a year, has told the new Glasgow City Council that he will not
take up the offer of a job with the unitary authority when his post disappears
with local government reform.
He saidyesterday: ``Given the nature of the job and the public reaction to it,
which has been very negative, I have decided that it would not be in my
professional or personal interests, or in the interests of the city council, to
take the post.
``Against that background I will resign and go into open competition for
alternative employment in April.''
Mr Pignatelli declined to elaborate, but it is known that he has been unhappy
about damaging comments which emerged after Glasgow City Council decided in
August that it wanted to use his talents to produce a strategy for the
continued funding of the voluntary sector, which is under severe pressure
because of the break-up of the region.
Like thousands of other local authority employees under 50, he has a statutory
right to be transferred to one of the new councils, with conservation of
salary, for three years. But colleagues believe he would have found it
difficult to adjust to what amounts to a lower-level, less influential post
which would be outside the city council's senior management team.
``It is the kind of task he would normally carry out between meetings,'' one
said last night. As Strathclyde's director of education Mr Pignatelli is
responsible for an annual budget of #1300m, 36,000 staff, and nearly 2100
schools and other educational establishments.
The Herald understands that contracts for the Glasgow job have not been
exchanged, but it would have involved Mr Pignatelli carrying out a strategic
and financial review to safeguard funding in Glasgow for organisations such as
single parent, ethnic minority, and special needs groups, as well as uniformed
organisations such as the Boys' Brigade and the Scouts.
Strathclyde's budget for the voluntary sector is #970,000, and Glasgow's share
would be smaller. There have been damaging comments about Mr Pignatelli taking
responsibility for the BB at a salary of #94,500.
Some Labour councillors have expressed concerns about the post emerging at a
time of cuts in services and jobs being ``disaggregated out of existence''.
It is likely the glare of adverse publicity would have intensified on the post
as Glasgow embarks on a programme of school closures to help cut costs: the
city faces particular funding problems because of its relatively poor tax base
and the comparatively high number of former regional staff assigned to tackle
its huge social problems.
Mr Pignatelli has not applied for any jobs as he has overseen the break-up of
the Strathclyde education service and the transfer of its responsibilities to
the new councils. Neither does he have a job lined up.
It is believed that his decision to turn down the Glasgow post will cost him
dear in financial terms. He did not qualify for redundancy and pension rights
under the staff transfer scheme because he is under 50.
He will not be 50 until December next year and if he had gone to Glasgow until
then, or had exercised his right to stay for the full three years, he would
have qualified on leaving for a lump sum of about #85,000 plus an annual
pension working out at about #47,000 with enhancement, or about #30,000 without
the discretionary element which has applied to other officers going early.
As it is he will qualify for a redundancy payment which will work out at less
than a year's salary, and he will not have access to his pension until he is 60.
A senior education source said last night: ``In a sense he has been caught in a
trap. He is too young to go and, with local government reform, there is no
other job which would allow him to exercise such a range of management
responsibilities.''
It is known that Mr Pignatelli is anxious to continue working for at least the
next 10 years at the same pace which has characterised his time at Strathclyde.
Headhunters invited Mr Pignatelli to apply for the job of running New York's
public education service but it was not a serious option for several reasons.
Mr Pignatelli is a member of several influential bodies including the Secretary
of State's advisory council on education and training targets, and chairs the
group given the key task of shaping the curriculum and assessment procedures
for the forthcoming reform of upper secondary schooling.
</TEXT>
