<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scrooge firms offer no cheer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975142999</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOOVER, Midland Bluebird of Falkirk, and Scottish Pride are top scorers in a
new ``Scrooge index'' of companies which offer their employees no Christmas
cheer.
The Cambuslang Hoover operation, which employs some 780, was even singled out
for special mention in the Labour Research Department publication as this year
it has not only stopped its staff lunch but also scrapped parties for
pensioners and employees' children, thereby ending a 15-year custom.
Some of the 980 employees of Scottish Pride, the Glasgow dairy products
company, used to qualify for a #50 bonus and cartons of cream, but this perk
has disappeared under ``harmonisation''.
Out of 105 workplaces surveyed, 40 (38% of the sample) offered their staff no
Christmas dinner (whereas 32% did), or children's party (25%), a gift (21%),
employees' party (19%), bonus (10%), or time off for shopping (7%).
Forty five per cent of the companies offered two of the six benefits and 17%
offered three or more. Only two companies, Lombard North Central, of Surrey,
and Sericol, of Broadstairs, offered four benefits while the outright winner ,
providing five (dinner, bonus, gifts, shopping, and party) was clothing
manufacturer Dewhirst, of Peterlee, County Durham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
