<DOCNO>GH951129-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>WATER Severn lifts profit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143000</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE water company reporting season got under way yesterday with Severn Trent
reporting a 16% increase in pre-tax profit to #189m, writes NICOLA REEVES.
Profit from the core water services business rose by 12.5% to #206m. This was
largely down to tight cost control, with direct operating costs up by just 1.4%.
The costs included #6.7m of extra expenditure on measures to combat this year's
drought and control leaks from pipes. A further #5.2m of similar extra cost is
expected to be incurred in the second half of the year.
Chief executive Vic Cocker said Severn Trent's decision to spend an extra #130m
on resources and services over the next five years stemmed directly from the
drought conditions which dominated the first half of the year.
The board has retained Arthur Andersen to undertake a comprehensive review of
the main board directors' remuneration packages and, in line with the
recommendations made in the Greenbury report, it will report to shareholders in
the company's annual report to be published next June.
The interim profit and dividend was ahead of City expectations. There is a
second interim dividend of 3.84p payable in August 1996.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sole to sit out meeting with SRU</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143001</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Scotland captain David Sole will not be at Murrayfield tonight for the
planned meeting with the Scottish Rugby Union over his criticism of a referee
after Edinburgh Academicals' premiership clash with Melrose.
Sole, who was unhappy with the performance of referee Colin Henderson following
a series of nine penalties against Academicals which led to an 18-15
injury-time victory for Melrose, said after the game that Henderson's
performance had been ``tantamount to cheating.''
The game was a crucial one for Academicals as they were then in the midst of an
ultimately unsuccessful battle for Division 1 survival.
SRU chief executive Bill Hogg said on Monday that the union had invited club
representatives to Murrayfield for an explanation and Academicals - one of the
union's founder members - had said that Sole, president Charlie Jackson, and
secretary Ken Lauder would attend tonight's face-to-face meeting.
Hogg said that ``all and every'' sanction was open to the union under bye-laws
relating to conduct not in the best interests of the game but only after
discussion would it be apparent whether sanctions were required or not.
Yesterday, Sole said that he could not attend the meeting because he was
baby-sitting.
``My wife has just started a business and she is going to be out. I have to
look after the children, so I can't make it to Murrayfield,'' he said.
The 1990 Grand Slam captain, who managed the Scotland under-19 side at the
Junior World Cup in Bucharest last season, said that he had already written to
Academicals, declaring that his comments about the refereeing had been made in
a personal capacity and had not been intended to embarrass them.
Yesterday, the SRU chief executive, asked if the meeting would still go ahead
in Sole's absence, said: ``This is a surprise. I confirmed no later than last
night with the club that they would all be coming. We shall have to speak to
them again to find out just what is going on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT should take a kind of genius to persuade anyone to feel nostalgic for Soviet
communism. Seven decades of murder, repression, and economic chaos ought to be
quite enough to cure any society of its appetite for state socialism and the
fairytale of history's benign and inevitable tendencies.
Besides, didn't the West always argue that freedom, once tasted, would become
addictive; that the huddled masses of the old Soviet empire would take to
individualism and the free-market like famished men to a feast? Were not
prosperity, liberty, and political stability supposed to be their own best
advertisements? In Russia at least, it hasn't worked out that way.
With fewer than three weeks to go to elections to the lower house of the Duma,
setting the scene for presidential elections next summer, the Communist Party
and its allies are dominating the opinion polls. Ordinary Russians have
concluded that a few vastly expensive hamburger joints are no compensation for
crime, corruption, shambolic politics, and a crippled economy.
Who'd blame them? And who, really, would hold it against them if they despised
those westerners who sold them the dream of freedom while looting their country
four ways from Sunday? If Russia is in a mess that is the responsibility, first
and foremost, of the alliance which won the Cold War.
Now, in place of state repression, Russians suffer under a criminal Mafia that
straddles politics and the economy; in place of Soviet yes-men they are offered
parliamentarians who are either openly crooked or stupidly heroic (four have
been murdered in the past two years).
Strategic industries are being put up for auction - the choice is simple:
privatise or go bust - and the currency is a plaything for speculators.
Small wonder people tell themselves that in the old days they at least had
work, education, housing, welfare, and safe streets, paltry as each of these
may have then seemed compared to VCRs, BMWs, Levis, and Marlboros. In the old
days, they didn't get rich, but at least their salaries and pensions didn't
melt away in the night. Millions may have been murdered, but for the rest,
what? A very human formula; it could have been worse.
Since the party fell from power, or to be more precise, since the party bosses
switched their allegiances, ordinary people have experienced perhaps the most
crushing disillusionment of all. The single alternative to the old life, the
one glittering path that would make things better, has actually made them
worse. After the frying pan, the cruel fire.
This must be hard to comprehend if, all your life, you were seduced by images
of the decadent West. The democracies held out the only hope (keeping their own
people in line, meanwhile, with the fear of Soviet totalitarianism), and with
that hope exposed as a sham, what remains?
A mass return to the CP looks like naivety at best, desperate self-deceit at
worst. Long before it ceased to function as an instrument of control, the party
had lost the ability, never mind the will, to think. By the time it fell,
Soviet communism had not produced a new idea in 50 years.
There is no good reason, therefore, to imagine it has recovered its
intellectual vigour lately. Besides, does anyone really believe the West will
allow wholesale revisionism, even when democratically achieved? If the
Communists were to regain power, eastern Europe would be alive to the sounds of
plugs being pulled. Western companies would bale out and western banks would
haul down the shutters. The American right, meanwhile, would embark joyfully on
another arms binge.
However, the apparent rejection of ``modernisation'' by Russian voters tells us
more about the world than it does about the CP. Most of us grew up with the
myth there were only two political choices in the world. In particular, we were
obliged to believe if state socialism was wrong, free-market capitalism must,
as though true to the principles of the most banal syllogism, be right. It had
to be one or the other, and the world spent half a century on the brink of
immolation trying to decide which.
The message of Russia as the century closes is, perhaps, that both these
systems were intrinsically flawed, inherently cruel, and spectacularly
inefficient.
To the miners of Vorkuta high up in the Arctic, who went out strike on Monday
after receiving no pay for months, there is little to choose between old and
new. But choose, for all that, they must.
</TEXT>
