<HEADLINE>That spice of life</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SALLY KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SALLY KERR views an exhibition which brings together a wealth of ideas covering
a vast range of subjects
THE Royal Overseas League 1995 Open Exhibition, touring for only the second
year in Scotland, is showing 56 works selected from the 500 individual pieces
submitted by artists from 27 Commonwealth countries.
More than #7000 has been awarded in prizes, with Lesley Banks, a graduate of
Glasgow School of Art, winning the ROSL Scottish prize and a travel scholarship
to Singapore.
The standard is consistently high with most overseas artists exhibiting in
Britain for the first time with a vast range of subjects and styles covered.
Joe Amenechi's Balawo, (a metal foil relief), shows the influence of his
Nigerian birth with the simplified features of a native subject.
There is hot emotion and rhythm in Dana Toki's Indoor Jazz, an abstract squash
of a painting, a vision of trumpet, saxophone and swirling music in thick
acrylics, while Karen Macaw's Going Adrift - a figure standing in a stormy
field engulfed by corn - is full of loneliness.
There is humour in John Kelly's Two Men Lifting a Cow (a huge square cornered
monster); and Antonio Argenio's Love - a squirming jelly of a man, all liquid
arms and legs and rubber mouth.
David Wheeler's Pomfret Sisters, a study in photo-realism, is an eerie view of
two women with symbolic chalice and bell, standing in front of a medieval
painting, a landscape of peasants and castle.
Still-life is given a new twist - Jane Williams' Three Studies for Banana in
Red, is stark and large, the primary rich colours lifting the subject, whilst
Robert White's Green Chillies, is a small contemplative piece.
There is no obvious link or theme in this show; and in fact that is its
strength. It is rare to visit such a creative exhibition and see so much talent
and vitality.
n The Royal Overseas League 1995 Open Exhibition at Edinburgh College of Art
ends tomorrow.
</TEXT>
