<HEADLINE>Trained to take the strains</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143006</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
On the eve of its 60th birthday, Hugh MacDonald, head of music    at the BBC,
speaks to Michael Tumelty about his fears, hopes, and plans for the SSO
THERE may be some imaginative reading of the runes required, but it is possible
- just possible - that the outlook for the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra,
which is suffering as much as other Scottish orchestras in the present bleak
climate, might be about to take an optimistic turn as the SSO heads for its
60th birthday next week.
On the downside, as it were, Hugh MacDonald, head of music at BBC Scotland, is
not pulling any punches when he says that the BBC SSO is as much ``in the
doldrums'' as the other Scottish orchestras. He is facing a 5% cut next year in
a budget that he claims is already trimmed as tightly as possible.
``We have great financial worries about how we're going to carry on,
particularly given the financial situation in broadcasting,'' he says. On the
home front, he says, if the entire BBC is having to cut its budget, then Radio
3 will have to cut its overall budget, and those cuts, in turn, will be passed
onto the corporation's orchestras, including the SSO.
And there is little comfort in looking at broader trends in Europe, he says,
citing Italy, which used to have five broadcasting orchestras, and now has one,
or Holland where, similarly, orchestral broadcasting resources are being
slashed.
Radio orchestras, says Hugh MacDonald, are now very vulnerable if they are
totally dependent on broadcasting. ``The whole raison d'etre for them being
formed in the first place has changed, if not disappeared. The BBC is no longer
a monopoly; we're surrounded - in radio terms alone - by hundreds of new
stations.''
The BBC governors have made a commitment to maintaining orchestras in this
country, says MacDonald. ``But they have also said that they expect the
orchestras to generate more of their own income.''
Sponsorship, he says, is very hard to get, is unpredictable, unreliable, and,
in any event: ``if we got any, we'd be taking it away from others''.
More lucrative and promising is the series of commercial recordings the SSO is
now engaged upon, which have evolved from a redefinition of BBC orchestras'
contracts, allowing recordings made for Radio 3 to be licensed on to record
companies. ``It's not a large amount of money, but it is contributing an amount
which is very useful,'' says MacDonald.
The main area of hope he sees for the future, is some sort of collaboration:
``The future for us is definitely some sort of partnership funding so we're not
totally reliant on the BBC.''
Which is exactly where the whole orchestral edifice has crumbled in the last
three years. First the proposed merger of the BBC SSO with Scottish Opera, and
the subsequent Liddell report; then the proposed collaboration with the other
Scottish symphony orchestras to replace Scottish Opera's orchestra, and the
ensuing Robertson report. All have run aground.
MacDonald, along with other orchestral chiefs, doesn't hide his disappointment
over the apparent collapse of the latter plan. ``Make no mistake about it; if
anything happened to the Scottish Opera orchestra, we'd be in there like a
shot.''
If none of these comes to fruition, then it leaves the BBC SSO in a situation,
he says, ``where we have as much stability or instability as the other
orchestras.''
What it has meant, says MacDonald, is that ``we've been in a state of
semi-stasis for three years. We weren't really in a position to plan ahead very
far. Certain things had to be put on hold. The merger discussions and all the
rest of it didn't work out, so now we can make decisions.''
Spearheading a series of important decisions is a determined statement of
intent. Despite all of the financial problems around the corner, says
MacDonald, ``I cannot conceive of the BBC SSO not carrying on. If it wasn't
there, it would be a unmitigated disaster for Scottish musical life. If it
wasn't doing the kind of things it does - especially the contemporary music
side and special projects - it would be an immeasurable loss.''
Up to 12 vacant posts in the orchestra have now all been advertised, and the
orchestra has been snowed under with applications. (Since musicians' contracts
were renegotiated, BBC orchestras' pay now places these posts into the category
of highly desirable.) Collaborations with other Scottish orchestras will be
pursued, as will the expanding commercial recording venture.
With special projects - such as Gavin Bryars's opera Medea, recently performed
at the Tramway, a series of five programmes of excerpts from obscure British
operas, and another four of neglected British symphonies from the fifties -
MacDonald says: ``We are proving our worth, artistically, in our
adventurousness, and I am absolutely determined that the SSO's role will be to
complement the other orchestras; we're not in the business of competing.''
But undoubtedly the main thrust of effort in breaking loose from the
``semi-stasis'' of recent years, will be the announcement, in the new year, of
a newly appointed principal conductor, another post that has lain vacant for
more than two years since the previous encumbent, Jerzy Maksymiuk, was
appointed conductor laureate.
``That,'' says Hugh MacDonald, ``will give us a tremendous shot in the arm.''
But he clearly intends it to be more than just that. ``We intend to build a
team; and with a new chief conductor in place, we've got the core of a good
team.''
As well as the new chief, says MacDonald, the SSO will have associate
conductor, Martyn Brabbins, ``very good with certain repertoire, and liked by
the recording company''.
Then there is the unstoppably energetic Polish conductor laureate, Jerzy
Maksymiuk. ``With his 120% commitment to everything he does, Jerzy is going to
be with us - for life. We will play to his strengths, and obviously they will
include contemporary music.''
And the latest appointment, Chinese composer Tan Dun, MacDonald sees as
``far-reaching''. Tan has an international reputation, and is producing some of
the most imaginative music on the scene. Association with him can only benefit
the orchestra, suggests the head of music.
Even beyond the establishment of an in-house team, MacDonald has plans to
rationalise and focus the range of conductors employed by the orchestra. ``We
want also to cultivate some other people that we know work well with the
orchestra.'' The superb French and Russian conductors, Jean-Yves Ossonce and
Alexander Titov, were named.
``Rather than having a constantly changing variety of guest conductors, we need
to narrow it down, aiming for a more coherent and consistent presentation.
``I want the orchestra to develop its strengths, and concentrate more on
them,'' says Hugh MacDonald. ``We're always going to play Beethoven, Mozart,
and Brahms.
``But this orchestra has got more than just technical competence in
contemporary music. It has a natural affinity. It gives a special kind of
commitment which is quite rare, and we need to capitalise on that.
``We can forge an identity which means that when people hear the name, BBC SSO,
they know that that's the one in demand for exciting projects with new work.
After all, if we're good at contemporary music, why not flaunt it?''
n BBC SSO 60th birthday concert: Glasgow Royal Concert Hall, Thursday December
7, 7.30pm.
</TEXT>
