<HEADLINE>Move to battle stress in dug-out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143007</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE SFA and the Scottish Football Players' Union are to combine in a move to
help managers deal with stress.
Union secretary Tony Higgins said yesterday that he had already held talks with
Scotland manager Craig Brown about the move.
Already this season St Johnstone manager Paul Sturrock and Morton's Allan
McGraw have been rushed to hospital amid fears of a heart attack. Happily, in
both cases this proved wrong.
Higgins said: ``Previously, we ran a management course and part of that dealt
with stress and how to deal with problem situations. I have already had talks
with Craig Brown and    the intention is to hold, at the end of the season,
another course for managers and senior players who may be considering
management.
``It is important to give as much help as possible on the techniques of dealing
with stress. Stress is part of the baggage of the job nowadays.
``In years gone by managers such as Alex Smith and Walter Smith served a long
apprenticeship by being coaches or assistants at clubs. But with players
stepping straight from playing into management there is not the same
opportunity to gain experience.
``There is no management job in industry where the person appointed has not had
some sort of training, but it happens in football.''
</TEXT>
