<HEADLINE>Bedroom scenes to keep you in suspenders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143008</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAGAZINE we try never to miss is the Literary Review, especially the December
issue when they hand out their Annual Bad Sex Prize. This is awarded to the
book which contains the most irrelevant, redundant, perfunctory, embarrassing,
or unconvincing piece of writing describing the old rumpy-pumpy.
First, one of the losers, a section from Involved, a novel by one Kate
O'Riordan, describing a scene between a chap called Eamon and an Irish lady of
the night:
Her blouse lay at her feet, wet with sweat under the armpits. She kicked it
away. Eamon pulled his sweater over his head and stood in his vest and
trousers. He pulled his stomach in and watched her wrestle with the zip of the
tight red skirt.
She wriggled it down along her meaty thighs and kicked it to join the blouse.
She was wearing white suspenders and panties above black stockings over which
white soft flesh spilled generously. Layers of belly, winkled in the middle and
scarred below the navel, quivered beneath the white brassiere.
Enough, enough. We get the picture.
Possibly in second place we have this bit from Blackout, a novel by John
Lawton, set in wartime London:
Troy sat on the edge of the bed with his back to Tosca and unscrewed the top.
``Gorgeous,'' he said, inhaling from the jar. ``Pity we've nothing to eat with
it.''
``We have,'' she said, out of sight.
``Such as?''
``Such as . . . me!''
He turned. She had taken off her blouse and was unhooking her brassiere,
unleashing a bosom of such magnificence as to stagger the beholder. She grasped
the jar and upended it over her torso.
``OK, baby, I'm yours. Sauce me!''
And the winner is . . . Sorry, we've run out of space but we will tell you on
Friday. Sorry to keep you in suspenders, so to speak.
Get in the mood
THE Diary reluctantly acknowledges the advent of Christmas and, indeed, the
advent of advent. To get into the festive mood, we launch a series of
competitions. And what do competitions mean? Prizes.
The first test of the ingenuity of you dear readers is that you have to
nominate a fourth Wise Person who might have visited the stable at Bethlehem
and suggest what gift he or she might bring.
Would Duncan Ferguson, footballer and sometime guest of Her Majesty's prison
service, bring a garden gnome that he made in the workshop at Barlinnie?
Would Gerry Adams give the infant as a token of peace an Armalite rifle or a
daud of Semtex that was now surplus to IRA requirement? The Princess of Wales,
echoing Salome, offering her husband's family jewels (not the ones from the
tower) on a plate.
We are almost certain you get the drift. The prizes? Bottles of Langs Supreme
whisky and the Langs Hogmanay first-footing kit which consists of a stylish
package containing a miniature of whisky, a crystal glass, a bit of shortbread,
a lump of coal, and a pinch of salt.
Entries welcomed by letter, pigeon, fax, or phone, if you can get us in.
Lesson learned
A BOOK called Scotland the Worst (Canongate, #4.99) is already living up to its
name. This list of people and situations which are, literally, awfully Scottish
was serialised, appropriately, in the Sunday Times Scotland. The article was
located adjacent to an expensive advertisement from Dollar Academy, the top
people's school. Who are now refusing to pay because of their proximity in the
paper to a survey of the worst things Scottish.
Toeing the line
AN entirely apocryphal story, we hope, from a Glasgow school. Each wean is
asked to describe father's occupation (the school is obviously in one of those
areas where people have jobs).
``Ma faither's a jiner,'' says one. ``No, your father is a joiner,'' replies
the teacher. ``For tomorrow, I want you to learn to spell the word joiner and
also bring me something relating to your father's employment.''
The next pupil says that his father is ``a bookie''. He is told to learn to
spell bookmaker and bring something relating to his father's business. The
third child is a recent immigrant to Scotland and is struggling with the
language. He says that his father is a ``feet-fixer''. He is given the same
instructions as the previous pupils.
The next day, the first wean duly spells the word joiner and produces a hammer.
The second spells bookmaker and produces, as his evidence of his pater's
profession, a betting line with the words: ``Ten-to-one the wee foreign guy
can't spell chiropodist.''
The last word
WE hope that the Diary's chum Eddie Mair, who left stardom at BBC Scotland to
work on Radio 5 Live in London, has not been introduced to any substances of a
mind-blowing nature.
We ponder this only because Eddie has taken to closing his midday programme on
Radio 5 Undead with comments of a mystical and unexplained nature. So far these
have included:
q Not to be taken internally.
q Made only with pulp from sustainable forests.
q If you can read this, you're driving too close.
q If the red light shows, wait here . . .
Presumably, we can look forward to such statements as: ``My other radio channel
is Classic FM'' or ``I used to live in Dundee but I'm alright now.''
Any suggestions direct to Mr Mair at the BBC in London.
Only an excuse
HOGMANAY is a difficult enough time of year for the average person who might
have taken a dram or two before wending homeward.
The city of Edinburgh is intent on making it even more trying with some of the
events in their five-day Hogmanay festival.
Try, for example, explaining that you were on your way home, honest, but were
held up by an entire half-mile of street theatre.
On no account mention one of the turns in this plethora of street theatre. It
is called Ezili - The Mother of All Monsters.
It is a giant orange, inflatable plastic beastie on the same scale of the Loch
Ness monster which will be laying exploding eggs. Much more frightening than
little pink rats.
Also in attendance and possibly even more disconcerting will be both the
Edinburgh and Cardiff samba schools.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
