<HEADLINE>Former soccer chief Tapie gets prison term for match-rigging</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Douai, France
BANKRUPT former Marseille soccer boss Bernard Tapie today was sentenced to two
years in prison, of which 16 months were suspended, on match-rigging charges.
The appeal court in the northern French town of Douai also declared Tapie
ineligible for public office for three years.
Tapie's lawyer immediately announced that he would appeal to the Supreme Court,
a move that keeps him out of prison while the legal proceedings continue.
The one-time business tycoon, cabinet minister and aspiring politician who
remains a member of the French and European parliaments, had been sentenced by
a lower court last May to one year in jail with another year suspended for
bribing players of rival team - Valenciennes - to lose a 1993 league game to
Marseille and for interfering with witnesses.
The financially troubled tycoon, known for his brash personality and left-wing
views, admitted that while owner of Olympique Marseille he had met the trainer
of the Valenciennes team but denied trying to fix a 1993 match.
Jacques Mellick, the mayor of Bethune who helped construct an unsuccessful
alibi for Tapie, saw his two-year suspended sentence reduced to one year. The
court upheld his two-year ineligibility for office.
The court reduced to 18 months the two-year suspended sentence for Jean-Pierre
Bernes, Marseille's former director general. Bernes told an investigating judge
in June that the Marseille club under Tapie spent up to #750,000 a year buying
off opposing players and international referees.
The court upheld suspended sentences against Jean-Jacques Eydelie, who played
for Marseille, and Valenciennes players Christophe Robert and Jorge Burruchaga.
The defendants were accused of fixing a match on May 20, 1993, in which Tapie's
Olympique Marseille won 1-0 and went on to become European champions.
After the scandal broke, Marseille was stripped of its 1993 French championship
title and relegated to the second division last season, but was allowed to keep
the title of 1993 European club champions.-AP.
</TEXT>
