<DOCNO>GH951129-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Williams' twin target</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143011</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WESTERN Samoa coach Bryan Williams was a two-time Twickenham winner more than
20 years ago and is hoping that his squad can emulate him when they play London
today and return for the Test against England next month.
Williams landed a drop goal in the All Blacks' 9-0 defeat of England in 1973
and scored a second-half hat trick of tries when a World XV crushed England
during the RFU's 1971 Centenary celebrations.
``Being an All Black gave me the attitude that every rugby game was there to be
won.
``But on this tour with Western Samoa we have the twin objective of giving the
new players a taste of international rugby,'' said Williams.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BSE rules tightened</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143012</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AGRICULTURE Minister Douglas Hogg yesterday confirmed plans for further
tightening of the rules designed to protect consumers from any risk of BSE,
writes ROBERT ROSS.
Under new measures the use of an animal's vertebral column in the manufacture
of mechanically recovered meat will be banned.
An advisory committee had expressed grave concern about findings by the State
Veterinary Service that there had been a number of instances where
slaughterhouses had left small pieces of spinal cord attached to carcasses
after dressing.
The cord is a specified bovine offal (SBO) which should be removed from
all carcasses of cattle over six months of age and destroyed.
The Government's chief medical officer, Dr Kenneth Calman, welcomed the new
restrictions and emphasised there was no scientific evidence that BSE could be
transmitted to humans or that eating beef caused Creutzfeld Jacob Disease.
Mr Hogg said that the new measures were a consequence of failings in handling
SBO in slaughterhouses. They did not reflect any concern about the mechanically
recovered meat process itself.
``I look to slaughterhouse operators now to deliver 100% compliance with the
SBO controls,'' he said.
</TEXT>
