<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unions vow showdown as France faces transport chaos</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EDUARDO CUE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Tuesday
RAIL transport was virtually paralysed in France for a fifth day today as
public service unions vowed to step up pressure until the government drops
plans to overhaul the social security system.
Thousands of rail workers, joined by doctors and students, marched in Paris to
protest Prime Minister Alain Juppe's plan to increase the number of years
workers must pay into the social security system before they can retire with
full benefits.
Students are demanding more funding and teachers to relieve crowded classrooms.
Marc Blondel, secretary general of the Worker's Force (FO) union, said
government workers could not accept the proposed changes, which would take away
control of the social security system from the unions and give it to Parliament.
But Juppe dug in his heels today, saying he would not withdraw his
controversial social security plan that seeks to cut next year's deficit of 60
billion francs (#7000m) by half and to eliminate it entirely in 1997.
In what may be the worst piece of news for the conservative government to date,
French unions are discussing the idea of a national strike that would bring out
two million people to the streets next month, the Paris daily Le Monde reported
today.
Juppe admitted in a newspaper interview on November 16 that his government
could not survive such a show of force.
French commuters lived through another difficult day today as trains, subways
and buses were nearly non-existent for the second time in less than a week.
Traffic jams up to 20 miles long were reported on highways leading into the
capital as commuters took to their cars to get to work. Rail, subway and bus
service in and around Paris was seriously crippled.
The strike was called by two of France's three major unions - Worker's Force
and the communist-led General Confederation of Workers (CGT).
A third union, the Democratic Confederation of French Workers (CFDT), which
supports some but not all of the government's proposals, did not participate in
today's strike.
Last night the government said it would exempt the 182,000 railway workers from
its plan to increase the amount of time public sector employees have to pay
into the state retirement fund by 2!s years.
But union leaders immediately rejected the olive branch.-AP.
Nicholas Powell writes: The national rail network and Paris's public transport
system are again expected to be at a virtual standstill tomorrow. According to
unions, 60,000 workers marched through the capital today. Impressed by their
own show of strength, unions promised they were only at the beginning of a
major campaign of industrial action against the highly unpopular right-wing
Government.
The demonstrations and stoppages are due to culminate a week before Christmas
with a massive protest in Paris. Today's strikes also included stoppages in
postal sorting centres.
The government measures entail the overhaul of the nation's chronically
overdrawn welfare system, increases in taxation over the next 12 years to
absorb the overdraft, changes to public sector retirement schemes, and a plan
to mop up the debts of the national railways.
To make matters worse for the government, French students have resurrected the
spectre of the May 1968 Sorbonne riots in recent weeks with protests against a
shortage of teachers, overcrowding, and underfunding in universities.
A major student demonstration, which should bring further chaos to the streets
of Paris, is planned tomorrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Weir joins SGN in new venture</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>BUSINESS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Weir joins SGN
in new venture
WEIR Group hopes to share in contracts worth billions of pounds to decommission
UK nuclear power stations through a new joint venture with a French nuclear
power company.
Strachan &amp; Henshaw of Bristol, a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Glasgow
engineering group, announced yesterday it was joining up with state-owned SGN
of France to form European Nuclear Technologies (Entech).
The new company, which is based in Bristol, will compete for Government
contracts to dismantle and dispose of nuclear power plants throughout the UK.
Merger approval
LLOYDS Bank shareholders have approved the merger with the TSB by a majority of
100-1. Some 566.6 million votes were cast in favour, with 5.7 million against.
A meeting of TSB shareholders at the Scottish Conference and Exhibition Centre
in Glasgow today is also expected to rubberstamp the deal.
Cairn deal
EDINBURGH-based Cairn Energy has signed a deal to conduct its first exploration
in co-operation with a Chinese partner. Cairn and China National Offshore Oil
Corporation will drill in a 2945 square kilometre block in the Beibu Gulf off
southern China. The company did not disclose investment details, but it will
bear all the costs of the operation, including a 1996 seismic analysis which
could lead to drilling in the first quarter of 1997.
Tate changes
TATE &amp; Lyle has made several board changes, including the appointment of Larry
Pillard as chief operating officer and group managing director. Paul Lewis will
step down as finance director to be replaced by Simon Gifford, who will become
an executive director. Mr Lewis stays deputy chairman.
Disney record
THE Walt Disney Co posted record profits and revenues for the fourth quarter
and full year. Net income for the three months to end-September jumped 17% to
$264m from $225.9m, while revenue rose 16% to $3120m. For the full year, net
income leapt 24% to $1380m and revenue advanced 20% to $12.11bn.
Capital flight
EDINBURGH has been selected by Belgian airline Sabena as the first destination
to be served by its new Avro RJ85 jet. The 82-seater aircraft will be put into
service on its Edinburgh-Brussels route on Christmas Eve. The RJ85 will be
introduced on its Glasgow-Brussels route in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Presidency bid by "Mad Vlad"</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143015</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Presidency bid
by `Mad Vlad'
MOSCOW: Ultra-nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky, long seen as the bad boy of
Russian politics, has defied critics who say his time is past by declaring he
will run for president.
Dubbed ``Mad Vlad'' by the Western media, Zhirinovsky's announcement seven
months before the vote appears designed to boost the flagging hopes of his
oddly-named Liberal-Democrat party in parliamentary elections on December 17.
Peace pledge
BARCELONA: European and Mediterranean countries pledged a new era of peace and
prosperity yesterday in an historic Barcelona Declaration adopted after
last-minute wrangles over the Middle East. An unprecedented conference of 27
countries ended nearly three hours late after ministers found a way around
Arab-Israeli issues including terrorism and nuclear weapons.
Afghanistan plea
UNITED NATIONS: Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali expressed grave concern
yesterday at the escalation of fighting in Afghanistan, where government forces
are battling rebel Taleban militia, and urged all parties to exercise restraint
and work for a ceasefire. Taleban, led by Islamic students, has taken control
of more than half of Afghanistan since its emergence last year.
Whitewater move
WASHINGTON: A US Senate panel resumed hearings yesterday into the Whitewater
affair, focusing on what the White House might have been told of government
investigations into two Arkansas firms. The Senate Whitewater Committee is
trying to find out if the White House tried to influence investigations into
the Madison Guaranty saving and loan institution and Capital Management
Services Inc.
Summit opens
CAIRO: Four Central African leaders met in Cairo yesterday with former US
President Jimmy Carter trying to mediate a solution to the havoc which conflict
between Hutus and Tutsis has brought to Rwanda, Burundi and their neighbours.
President Hosni Mubarak of the host country Egypt told the opening session that
peace was vital and he was confident the African presidents, from Burundi,
Rwanda, Uganda and Zaire, could lay the groundwork.
Promise kept
MADRID: Spain yesterday kept a promise made almost 60 years ago to the
International Brigades which fought alongside the Republicans against Franco's
fascist forces in the Civil War. Parliament unanimously approved a motion to
grant Spanish nationality to all surviving members of the 45,000-strong
volunteer force, many of them British.
Graf defended
BONN: Tennis star Steffi Graf's father yesterday insisted she was not involved
in a tax evasion scandal and urged German prosecutors to leave her alone, his
lawyer said. Peter Graf, 57, has been in jail since August on suspicion of
evading tax on millions of pounds she has earned during her high-powered career.
</TEXT>
