<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotch association delighted with 27p drop, the first cost-cutting measure for 100 years Welcomes galore from whisky trade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD, ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>budget 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143016</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scotch Whisky Association last night hailed Mr Kenneth Clarke as the first
Chancellor in 100 years to announce a cut in excise duty on whisky.
His decision to lop 27p off a bottle was widely welcomed by the industry, which
had mounted a powerful campaign to reverse the 4% rise in last year's
mini-Budget.
It will be seen as a particular boost in Scotland, where an estimated 45,000
people are employed, directly or indirectly, by distillers. The last price cut,
in 1895, was of a ha'penny in duty.
The Chancellor's move may also trigger a Christmas whisky war, with companies
vying to woo back drinkers who may have been deterred by soaring prices.
A spokesman for the Scotch Whisky Association said: ``The market is so
competitive at the moment that I think the pressure will be on for retailers to
cut prices. The whisky war is already on in some respects and it is bound to
intensify.''
Mr Hugh Morison, the association's director general, said: ``This cut is
extremely good news. The Chancellor has recognised the commercial damage
inflicted on the industry by successive Governments, which have consistently
discriminated against spirits.
``We hope that this is the first step of a long-term programme of cuts which
will bring the duty on spirits in line with the much lower duties applied to
other drinks.''
Mr Morison said the cut would also strengthen the Chancellor's negotiating
position in the discussions with European Union finance ministers over the
harmonisation of duties.
``By cutting the duty on spirits, the Chancellor has sent a clear signal. He
can tell his fellow ministers, as well as those in Japan and other world
markets, that tax discrimination against Scotch whisky and other spirits is
unacceptable.''
Whisky makers have been fighting a losing battle against the popularity of wine
for the past 15 years. Sales have dropped 30% since 1979, with the average
price of a bottle of Scotch rising #4.70 to #11 during that time. On average,
tax on a bottle of whisky is around 70% compared with 30% on wine.
Mr Clarke's decision was broadly welcomed by individual distillers. Mr Ken
Hitchcock, chairman and chief executive of the Whyte &amp; Mackay group, said: ``We
are delighted. Alongside the industry's recent commitment to TV advertising,
the tax cuts will manifest themselves as a direct benefit to everyone connected
with the industry.''
The managing director of Allied Distillers, Mr Andrew Dewar-Durie, said: ``This
cut deserves two cheers. The announcement shows that Mr Clarke has learned the
lesson that duty increases depress sales, reduce revenue, and cost jobs.
Ultimately, however, we hope to achieve our goal of an 8% cut in duty.''
Highland Distilleries chairman, Mr John Goodwin, said it was as much a
principle than the actual amount that mattered, as the Government was now
actually doing something.
The distiller of Famous Grouse is more exposed to the home market than almost
any other, with 1.2 million case sales compared with one million in export
markets. So it will benefit to a greater extent from any improvement in
domestic sales through the tax stimulus.
That was reflected in Highland shares jumping 20p to 367p, the biggest mover in
the sector.
At Macdonald Martin, the distiller which makes Glenmorangie, finance director
Jim Fyffe expressed concern that no commitment had been given on eventual rates
of duty nor the timescale. He said there remained a complete imbalance between
duty on spirits and that on beer.
While the distillers were happier, there were dismal faces at both the brewers
and the wine importers.
Carlsberg-Tetley pointed out that the British drinker pays seven times as much
duty as a French counterpart. The Chancellor had talked about the legitimate
concerns of the British drinks industry but had done little, said the company.
Tennent Caledonian said the freeze was extremely disappointing and was ``simply
not enough''.
The company added: ``Only the bootleggers will benefit because as long as the
massive gap between British and French beer tax levels remain unchanged, they
will continue to profit from the illegal resale of imported foreign beer.''
Wine and Spirits Association chairman, Mr David Grant, said he had mixed
feelings. He was happy about the move on spirits but quite depressed that there
would be ``another year of carnage'' in the wine trade.
The imbalance in duty between Britain and Europe is now such that 11!s% of wine
is imported quite legally by the consumer. This has meant that there has been a
tax deficit of #453m and a loss of busines to the trade of around #1200m.
Cider shares were hard hit after the decision to raise duty on very strong
ciders - those above 7.5% alcohol - with Matthew Clark, which recently took
over Taunton Cider, dropping 21p to 620p while industry leader HP Bulmer was 9p
down at 484p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Milk yields are up but protein is down</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILK producers attending today's DairyScot event at Ingliston in Edinburgh will
get some good news - and some bad.
According to Scottish Agricultural College experts, milk yields in the last
year have increased despite less expenditure on concentrate feeds, but valuable
milk protein levels have fallen.
Dairy farmers have been told that future milk pricing policy will lead to
reduction in milk fat without lowered protein content.
The latest SAC costings show that milk yields rose by 219 litres to 6008 litres
per cow in the last year. At the same time concentrate usage fell by 135kg a
cow, boosting profits over concentrate usage to a record 20.60p a litre.
This was helped by the availability of high quality silage for last winter and
good grazing conditions this summer. However, SAC's David Scrimgeour pointed
out that milk protein declined by 0.07% to average 3.32% while butterfat levels
rose by 0.04% to 3.98%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Farmer arrested at show</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FARMER was arrested by police at the Smithfield FarmTec show in London
yesterday after an exhibitor claimed his animal had been injured.
A spokesman at Scotland Yard said that officers at Kensington Police Station
were investigating an allegation that a bullock had been hit in the foot by a
pitchfork.
``The incident occurred on Sunday between 9pm and 10pm,'' said the spokesman.
``The animal was seen by a vet and sedated. It had suffered a cut in its left
foot.'' A complaint was made to police on Monday and after investigation the
55-year-old farmer, from Peterhead, was arrested at the show.
The farmer, who has not been named, was released on bail and told to report to
Kensington Police Station on January 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Writers lured by legendary lensman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK McLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143019</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TIP-OFF from a chum and there I was in young Brendan McLaughlin's Clutha
Vaults Bar. Brendan is the landlord of the famed Scotia Bar across the road, a
Glasgow landmark for folk and blues and all sorts of cultural activities.
Indeed The Scotia is a venue for new Scottish writing and even does rather
splendid book prizes. But it was at Brendan's other venue, The Clutha, that
Richard Avedon came to photograph the new Scottish writers.
He booked it early and took hours, my dears, to take one snap: wur ain Harry
Turner, took two minutes to portray Mr Avedon, and Harry didn't have the nine
assistants and 80 cars or whatever which seemed to be a requirement for this
American snapper legend.
As it happens, Harry had taken a large number of photographs in advance for
Avedon just to let him see the lie of the land like. Avedon chose The Clutha,
and also the writers.
The American wizard is travelling around the UK, taking shots of lots of Brits.
``Writers and actors, politicians: I'm doing a lot throughout,'' he said.
``This shot is for our first assignment but a lot of the rest we'll do in wait
for later numbers of the New Yorker.''
Richard Avedon is the man who did the stills for Funny Face with Fred Astaire
and Audrey Hepburn. Later, he was Harper's Bazaar and Vogue.
He did the front cover for The Beatles' A Hard Day's Night album. Jean
Shrimpton posed for him.
For many years, Avedon was the most sought-after photographer in the world and
ad companies turned him into the sort of multi-millionaire which made senior
execs in every multinational company in the world wonder why they stayed on so
long at the Harvard Business School instead of learning how to point a Brownie
125.
Avedon proved to be a small, lean man with a shock of grey hair and not much
time for you, or anybody at all. He has been a star so long, it wouldn't matter
if he took a snap of his dog's turd, they would still run it on the front cover
of Life.
He does take a decent picture all the same and no denying. So would I with all
day and nine assistants, and a level of deference normally due to pontiffs.
But at least the reverence was given, and not asked.
There were a lot of writers about, assembled from all over just to get their
photie took by Avedon, including one of our most august novelists, Alasdair
Gray.
I didn't know who most of the others were actually and they wouldn't speak to
me at that apart from a rather nice fellow called Irving Welsh (he wrote that
trainspotting book), who told me how much he'd enjoyed an article of mine about
Liverpool when he was at Manchester Yooni and feeling homesick for Scotland.
I was touched. I wrote the piece, which I remember, 18 years ago.
And then Harry and me went back to work. Harry's picture's great. Made Richard
Avedon look dead like himself too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scot sells a Botham</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By ALAN HUNTER
SCOTS artist John Bellany's portrait of England cricketer Ian Botham will be
auctioned by Phillips Scotland on Friday.
The National Portrait Gallery commissioned it in 1985.
Lothian based Mr Bellany yesterday recalled: ``Mr Botham said the way I painted
reminded him of bowling.
He would study a batsman with the same intensity . . . and then lull them into
a state of false security before delivering the final ball.''
The painting could make up to #5000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Video of CCTV footage withdrawn from sale</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143022</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONTROVERSIAL video showing ``spy camera'' footage which includes a couple
having sex in a lift is to be withdrawn from sale.
Carlton TV threatened the makers of Caught In The Act! with an injunction when
it emerged that one of the sequences came from its programme Inside Crime.
The clip showed a suspect's car crashing through a shopfront in an unsuccessful
effort to evade police in New Bridge Street, Blackfriars, in the City of London.
However, film maker Barrie Goulding, who confirmed he was withdrawing the
video, said the reason for the withdrawal was political controversy and not
copyright dispute.
Police said they had authorised release of the car crash footage only to the
Inside Crime show and not to Mr Goulding.
Carlton claimed Mr Goulding had infringed their broadcast copyright and its
spokesman said: ``The company concerned will be withdrawing the video from
sale.''
MPs from all parties had demanded immediate Government action on controls on
closed-circuit television (CCTV) footage following the release of Caught In The
Act!
Mr Goulding blamed the political storm over the video for forcing him to
withdraw it yesterday and pointed out Carlton had not taken legal action
against him.
``As a responsible film maker, I have made the necessary research and have the
legitimate and proper paperwork supporting our copyright,'' he claimed.
``However, in the light of the pressure placed on me by politicians, I have
instructed the distributors of this video to cease distribution with immediate
effect.''
No further copies would be manufactured or made available, he pledged.
Mr Goulding said he would seek to re-release the video in the new year.
Amid the political storm, Labour MP Tam Dalyell claimed the video highlighted
the potential for blackmail in closed-circuit television systems.
Mr Roger Gale, Tory member of the media backbench committee, said he wanted all
commercial exploitation of clandestine camera footage to be outlawed.
Mr Goulding argued that Caught In The Act! performed a public service by
prompting debate about CCTV and invasion of privacy.
Ironically, the City of London Police clip which prompted Carlton's legal
threat is relatively uncontroversial.
The film's commentary suggests a hard-up security guard could have been tempted
to sell the voyeuristic footage.
``There is nothing to stop him selling it, us showing it or you watching it,''
the commentary says.
Equally, the private company which apparently shot the footage and owns the
copyright could have supplied it with little hindrance under current law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to challenge will was 10 years too late</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN, Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143023</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SON who waited 10 years to go to court after his mother cut him out of her
will was too late, a judge has ruled.
If Mr James McLure had challenged the will immediately after his mother's
death, his father would have demanded repayment of ``thousands'' of IOUs, Lord
Milligan was told.
Mrs Helene McLure, of Bowling Green Place, Crail, Fife, died in May 1983,
having changed her will the previous month.
She owned a house at Liddle Place in Crail, in which Mr McLure had been living
rent-free. She left him the house in an earlier will but, in 1983, decided to
leave everything to her husband, also James, who died in April this year.
Her son raised an action in 1993 claiming the will was void because of
irregularities in the way it had been witnessed. However, his sister, Mrs
Helene McLeod, of Pickford Crescent, Cellardyke, Fife, argued that the will was
valid and that her brother had raised the action too late.
In a written judgment issued at the Court of Session yesterday, Lord Milligan
said Mr McLure had consulted a solicitor within a week of his mother's death to
see if there were grounds for challenging the will. He was advised to leave
things for the time being to see what his father's attitude would be.
The judge said there was evidence that the mother had given and lent cash to
her son on many occasions.
Mr McLure said in evidence that he had suffered a serious accident in the Army
about 32 years ago when he was about 22, which resulted in epilepsy. After his
discharge, he had made various ventures into coastal fishing which had caused
substantial financial loss and his mother had helped him out.
Lord Milligan said: ``At the time of the mother's death and the making of her
will shortly before, it seems that Mr McLure's financial position was at best
precarious and there was some reason to suppose that any inheritance would
benefit his creditors rather than himself.
``In particular, there was a risk that the house at Liddle Place would be lost
to the family.''
Mr McLure alleged that in 1992, his father took steps to repossess the house at
Liddle Place and evict him. He raised the court action after it became clear a
reconciliation was impossible.
Lord Milligan said Mr McLure had granted IOUs in favour of his mother, now
unknown in number and value. They had been found after the mother's death and
eventually disposed of by the father.
In evidence given in hospital before his death, the father testified that he
tried to get his son to repay the IOUs but that he had refused to do so.
``The father also said that, had there been a challenge of the 1983 will by the
son, he would have taken him to court for repayment of the IOUs.''
Lord Milligan said: ``It is clear that Mr McLure not only had the opportunity
to take expert legal advice as to whether to challenge the will at the time of
his mother's death but that he did so.''
He said the advice not to pursue legal action but wait to see if his father let
him stay at Liddle Place was probably very sound, taking account of his
rent-free occupation and his debt problem.
He added: ``The fact that Mr McLure made a calculated decision not to challenge
the will, taking account of his hopes and expectations with regard to his
father's attitude in the future, would not avail him should his hopes and
expectations prove to be false.''
The judge also rejected Mr McLure's argument that the 1983 will had not been
validly signed and witnessed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jailed dealer must hand over #40,000</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143024</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRUGS dealer who enjoyed a life of luxury while claiming State benefits has
been ordered to hand over profits of nearly #40,000 from his illegal trade.
George Rodden, 32, was jailed for 10 years last month after the biggest drugs
seizure yet in Fife - #40,000 worth of LSD, ecstasy, Temazepam, and diazepam.
His common-law wife, Christina Fisher, 30, who acted as the banker in the drugs
operation, was jailed for five years.
Lord Abernethy was told that Rodden and his wife had lived a luxury lifestyle,
enjoying foreign holidays although both were ``unemployed''.
Police found a cache of drugs during a raid at their home in Dunolly Gardens,
Windygates, in Fife.
Fisher was found to have a ``tick list'' of drugs debts totalling #27,000.
Rodden originally intended to contest yesterday's application by the Crown at
the High Court in Edinburgh for confiscation of the profits of his drugs
operation.
However, his counsel, Mr Jamie Gilchrist, told the court that he had been
instructed to withdraw the defences to the action.
Mr Gerard Moynihan, Advocate-depute, said the Crown was seeking confiscation of
#37,975 of assets which were the personal property of Rodden.
It also wanted him to hand over a further #1000 which had been a gift to his
wife.
Lord Abernethy made an order for Rodden, a father of five, to hand over a
#38,975 within the next six months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Women awarded damages for sex and race discrimination</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143025</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SINGLE mother - forced to leave her job as a London Underground train driver
to look after her baby son because of a new shift system - won her claim for
sex discrimination yesterday. The level of compensation will be set at a later
date.
Ms Susan Edwards, who was one of only 21 female drivers on London Underground,
continued working for five years on day shifts after the birth of her child
until a new rostering system was introduced in 1992. This meant she would have
had to work early and late shifts and so would not be able to look after her
child.
Ms Edwards took voluntary severance but later decided to take London
Underground to an industrial tribunal, claiming loss of earnings and injury to
her feelings.
She was supported by the Equal Opportunities Commission (EOC), which yesterday
welcomed her victory as a warning to employers to consider the impact of
changes to working practices on workers with families.
London Underground argued it introduced the new shift system to reduce costs
and increase efficiency but the tribunal found that the company could
``easily'' have accommodated Ms Edwards. The company is still considering the
tribunal's decision.
In a separate case, a black woman working for the Arts Council of England won
one of the highest ``injury to feelings'' awards - #8000 - at an industrial
tribunal after losing out on a promoted job to a less qualified white woman.
Ms Alex Ankrah applied for the post of combined arts officer at the Arts
Council of England, as an alternative to redundancy, along with two other black
women and one white woman who turned out to be the successful applicant even
though she did not meet the personnel specification and was working at a lower
grade.
The industrial tribunal upheld Ms Ankrah's claims of race and sex
discrimination, the latter because of her treatment while on maternity leave
and awarded her #8000.
Commenting yesterday, Ms Ankrah said hers was an important victory for black
people working in the arts and cultural field who had experienced
discrimination at work, particularly during restructuring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Contract workers were exposed to high levels of contamination at nuclear waste pits Dounreay may face prosecution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143026</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR management at Dounreay may face prosecution after the contamination of
two workers employed by a private company on the first nuclear waste-handling
contract put out to compulsory competitive tendering at the Caithness plant.
Meanwhile, Dounreay yesterday finally published the report of investigations
into an explosion in its controversial intermediate level waste shaft, more
than 18 years after it happened. However, it could be a further 25 years before
it begins to retrieve the nuclear waste in it.
The two men, whose safety could be the subject of a report to the
procurator-fiscal, are reported to have been exposed over the summer to 10mSv,
10 times the level of radioactive contamination that would normally be expected
for a Dounreay worker.
This was made clear by HM Nuclear Installations Inspectorate's principal site
inspector, Mr Malcolm Macphail, at yesterday's meeting of Dounreay Local
Liaison Committee. The NII is responsible for licensing Dounreay's operation.
The two men, a fork-lift driver and another worker, had been working for a firm
called Probabilistic Risk Assessment Ltd, which had been sub-contracted by AEA
Technology, a commercial division of the UK Atomic Energy Authority now being
privatised. They were involved in compacting the drums of low-level waste which
had originally been left rusting in Dounreay's controversial low-level waste
pits until after 1993 when public anger was followed by remedial action.
The work was stopped early in the summer when the contamination was first
discovered, and then restarted, only to be stopped on September 25. It has not
been restarted since.
Yesterday's meeting at Dounreay was first alerted to the problem by Dounreay's
head of safety, Mr Ken Butler, when he reported that there had been ``some
problems with the level of dust, there had been small quantities of
radioactivity breathed by operators . . . . in September we stopped the work
again because there was still evidence of internal contamination and after
investigation it appeared that the workers could have breathed in dosages
towards the upper end of limits''.
Mr Butler did not blame the use of outside contractors but rather an internal
failure to evaluate properly the information and to tell the proper people.
Mr Macphail, meanwhile, reported: ``Two contractors received significant
radioactive doses. Less than the legal limits but still significant. We regard
the incident as very serious. We have been taking formal statements and the
matter will be taken further.''
Afterwards, Mr Macphail said that the level of dose represented one fifth of
the annual legal dose. He said the failure of Dounreay's systems to prevent
this could well constitute a breach of Dounreay's 35 licensing conditions:
``Prosecution is a possibility.''
Mr Macphail had also revealed that the NII had issued the plant with two
improvement notices, which meant that the different areas of radioactive
contamination around the site had to be cleared up by October 1996, apart from
the area around the the controversial waste shaft. The operators had until
January 1997 to clean up there.
Meanwhile, following the publication of the report into the 1977 explosion in
the shaft, Dounreay director John Baxter said the aim was now to remove the
waste from the shaft in an operation that could cost #200m.
``Rather than leave the stuff there, we are seeking to retrieve it, but that
will not be easy and we think it will be the year 2005 at least before we start
taking the waste out, and there are some advantages in leaving it to 2020.''
The report itself records how an explosion was heard about 20 past midnight on
May 10, 1977, in the shaft where nuclear waste, including uranium and
plutonium, had been stored along with other items such as electric motors and
vacuum cleaners, since 1959. The explosion was heard along the coast at the HMS
Vulcan naval establishment but early investigations at Dounreay had failed to
locate anything unusual.
At 1.25am, a general worker reported he had heard an alarm bell ringing. At
1.55am, the site police were informed and road blocks erected to prevent anyone
entering the area of the shaft. One early theory was that it might have been a
bomb but that was discounted.
Mr Baxter pointed to a comparison which showed that levels of radioactivity
around the shaft after the explosion had been less than they had been in 1964
and 1965 and concluded:
``From the perspective of the mid-1990s, neither the use of the shaft as a
disposal site nor the levels of contamination and radiation at the head of the
shaft in the 1960s are acceptable. However, it is important to judge our
predecessors against the standards in force at the time, not the standards we
expect today.''
</TEXT>
