<HEADLINE>Doctor speaks out against euthanasia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING Glasgow doctor last night launched a strong attack on the case for
voluntary euthanasia.
Dr George Chalmers, emeritus consultant geriatrician at Glasgow Royal
Infirmary, said such a move was unnecessary and would be dangerous to society
as a whole.
Dr Chalmers, an elder at Sandyford Henderson Memorial Church in Glasgow, said
he had long-term worries about the effects of any move to make euthanasia
legal, particularly on the most vulnerable members of society.
He cited as an example pensioners in a Dutch nursing home who apparently felt
pressure along the lines of a ``duty to die'' for the sake of those who were
paying the bills.
``Introduce the option to kill and we are in real danger of turning the
exception into the rule, euthanasia being more and more frequent, given even
easier justification,'' said Dr Chalmers.
His comments came during a debate examining euthanasia in the context of
morals, ethics, and law partly organised by the Church of Scotland Board of
Social Responsibility held in Edinburgh last night.
In his speech, Dr Chalmers, who helped prepare a paper on the subject of
euthanasia to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland last year, said:
``Humanism, the philosophy from which much of the pressure towards euthanasia
derives, is Godless by definition and profoundly self-centred. It is
utilitarian, respecting only what is of demonstrable value in material and
human terms.
``If we adopt this way of thinking, we will begin to evaluate our fellow human
beings merely in terms of their contribution to society and we shall bring
pressures upon the most vulnerable members of that society which they are the
least able to resist.
``To legalise euthanasia would be to take a major step towards adopting a
utilitarian philosophy of life for our society and would make a major
concession to the barbarism which would arise from it.''
Dr Chalmers said he believed support for euthanasia and its promotion was
founded so often upon the fear of suffering rather than the fear of death
itself.
``We need to be aware that our actions change us, they make us what we become.
If I lie, I become a liar. If I steal, I become a thief. What do I become, as a
doctor, if I kill?''
q Another meeting on the issue of euthanasia is being held in Renfield St
Stephen's Church, Bath Street, Glasgow, tonight at 7.30.
As well as Dr Chalmers, Mr John Welsh, professor of palliative care at Glasgow
University will be involved in the debate.
</TEXT>
