<HEADLINE>Sharing bed `was not a gamble'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143028</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP David Ashby yesterday denied taking the most terrible gamble and
``putting his head in a noose'' by sharing a double bed on a French holiday
with a male doctor.
Cross-examined by Mr Richard Hartley QC, for the Sunday Times, which Mr Ashby
is suing for libel over an allegation that he was homosexual, the 55-year-old
MP for North West Leicestershire said he thought nothing of the incident at the
Chateau Tilques, St Omer, in January last year.
He was not handing evidence ``on a plate'' to his  estranged wife, Silvana, his
sister, Lynne, and the Sunday Times - who all believed he was having an affair
with Dr Ciaran Kilduff - because there was no evidence, he told Mr Justice
Morland and a jury at the High Court in London.
``For the 28 years of my marriage, my wife had done everything possible to stop
me having friends. She destroyed friendships when I got married, which I
discovered afterwards, with dreadful letters to people. She stopped me from
seeing my family and I didn't see why she should dictate how I lived and who I
saw after I left.''
Mr Ashby, of The Downs, west Wimbledon, and Ravenstone, Leicestershire, is
claiming damages over a January 1994 story that he shared a double bed with a
man friend during a holiday in Goa at the end of 1993.
Times Newspapers Ltd and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel,
although they accept that Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa. They
assert he was and is having an affair with 32-year-old Dr Kilduff.
Mr Ashby said that when his wife told a Government Whip that he had left her
for a man, the Whip roared with laughter. ``He knows me very well indeed and he
thought it was a very funny thing.''
He said someone would have to have a dirty mind to think he was having an
affair with Dr Kilduff, who sat in court only yards away from Italian-born Mrs
Ashby, 52.
Mr Hartley pressed: ``Knowing of your wife's allegations, don't you think you
were taking the most terrible gamble, in effect putting your head in a noose,
by sharing a double bed with Dr Kilduff?''
Mr Ashby: ``I knew I wasn't going to be dictated to by my wife and I was going
to do what I wanted to do in going away that weekend.''
Mr Ashby said he took some responsibility for his marriage breakdown in the
autumn of 1993 but the problem was that his wife had never had any real insight
into what was going wrong.
Mr Ashby broke down, and there was a brief adjournment, when Mr Hartley asked
again why he did not tell his wife he was going to France with Dr Kilduff.
Struggling for composure, he said: ``I had no reason to. I felt very hurt and
bruised and didn't think I could take much more, and I couldn't. I desperately
hoped that my marriage would . . . I hoped that by leaving her and doing all
these things maybe . . . maybe things, pray to God, they would change but they
didn't.''
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
