<HEADLINE>Olympic champion ready to take on the world Gunnell wants record back</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143029</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REALISM - accepting your short-comings, then confronting your fears and
inadequacies - is essential to the make-up of the champion athlete.
Sally Gunnell helped a group of 34 of Scotland's best young female athletes to
understand that truth yesterday as part of a TSB coaching initiative, Gunning
for Gold.
In a day-long course at Meadowbank, she gave the kind of advice and unique
insight which only a world, Olympic, European, and Commonwealth champion can
provide.
Yet, even goddesses are mortal, and can have doubts. If Gunnell succeeds in
making a successful defence of her Olympic 400 metres hurdles title in Atlanta
next year, then she will owe much to her husband, Jon Bigg.
Publicly, it was a minor operation which Gunnell required in August to cure the
foot problem which sidelined her all season and prevented her from defending
her world title in Gothenburg.
But the serious nature of the surgery, and the depths of Gunnell's subsequent
private doubts and fears, emerged as Bigg confessed how he had helped his wife
to train when she was still on crutches, and the pain was so intense that she
could not stand on her own feet.
``We had tried everything, but whenever I hurdled, I broke down,'' Gunnell
said. ``I didn't want to have an operation, but it was no use. A bone had grown
into a point, digging into the bursa of my Achilles tendon.''
A Swiss surgeon filed the bone, removed the bursa, and cleaned it out. He had
promised beforehand that Gunnell should be ready to restart training within a
fortnight, but the damage he found was much worse than had been anticipated.
``The operation was far bigger than we originally envisaged,'' said Bigg. ``In
some ways that was a relief. Finding there was a major problem explained why
Sally had had such a miserable summer.''
But the rehabilitation was almost more than the impatient Gunnell could
tolerate. ``I was a nearly a month on crutches, then a month trying to walk,
let alone run,'' she said.
``The pain I went through was far worse than the injury. I was two weeks just
learning to walk again, then another two before I could jog on the flat of my
feet. It was a further two weeks until I could get on my toes.
``Was I hard to live with? Just ask Jon,'' she added.
``The slow progress was completely disheartening to Sally,'' revealed her
husband, a former international 800m runner. ``Remember, she had never had a
serious injury before.''
Harder, than that, was when, out of the blue, she was locked on to the business
end of a microphone as her world record fell in Gothenburg.
The injured Gunnell had been signed up by BBC, and was in the stand,
commentating.
She did not realise for some moments that her world record had gone, and that
both the winner, Kim Batten, and runner-up Tonja Bufford, just one-hundredth
behind, had broken her time.
``The heats and semis had been nothing special, then, out of the blue, this
happened in what was expected to be a mediocre race.
``All I could think of was what might have been had I been in the race.''
Could things get worse?
Yes. She was ordered to go down and interview Batten.
To her credit, any pardonable uncharitable emotions were kept in check.
Gunnell's enthusiasm for her event, and for a great performance, were what
bubbled through as she spoke to the American.
``I was lucky the right side of me came out,'' said Gunnell.
Coach Bruce Longdon confirmed that, outwardly, Gunnell had never appeared to
let the loss of her world record affect her.
``If anything, it has helped motivate her even more,'' he said. ``If having won
everything in the sport could have been calculated to make you complacent, then
this was all Sally needed.
``But there is no point in minimising what she has been through. You only have
two feet, and if you are a runner, and if you have a great lump of bone carved
out of one of these feet, then that's a major operation.''
Gunnell remains convinced she can come back.
``What this has taught me is that I cannot go out and have it all my own way,
and win as easily as I did before.
``One of my goals now is to regain the record, and set the kind of time which
will stand for 10 or 15 years. That is my dream.''
The pain I went through after my operation was worse than the injury. I was two
weeks just learning to walk again, then another two before I could jog on the
flat of my feet.     It was a further two weeks until I could get on my toes.
</TEXT>
