<HEADLINE>Conran and Mosimann to open restaurants.   New highs for haute cuisine in Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143030</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO high-profile figures whose names have become synonymous with excellent
cuisine are set to open restaurants in Glasgow.
Sir Terence Conran, called the ``emperor of eating out'' for his range of
innovative restaurants in London, is expected to finalise the details soon of
his plans for a brasserie/bar in the new 163-bedroom luxury Hotel
Inter-Continental Glasgow at the former Glasgow Sheriff Court building.
The Herald also understands that the noted chef and broadcaster Anton Mosimann
will soon confirm plans to open a 100-seat restaurant and bar in the hotel.
It will be the first venture outside of London in the restaurant business for
the two men. Sir Terence has seven restaurant-bars while Mr Mosimann owns an
executive dining club.
News that the two exponents of gourmet eating are set to become established in
Glasgow was welcomed yesterday by renowned city hotelier Ken McCulloch.
He said: ``It is great news that Glasgow is able to attract people of this
stature. The more quality we have in the city the better. Their presence will
only make a visit to Glasgow even more memorable.''
It is expected the new restaurants will open in October, 1997, although the
#15m hotel development is not scheduled to open to the public until Christmas
1997.
The Hotel Inter-Continental Glasgow will be one of 141 hotels in 55 countries
operated by the Saison Group of Japan. The group also has interests in the
five-star George Hotel in Edinburgh and the St Andrews Old Course Hotel.
It is perhaps not surprising that Glasgow is the location for Conran's first
major restaurant outside of London, given that Glasgow was the
first-out-of-London location in the seventies for his Habitat stores group.
Sir Terence, who established a high reputation for innovative retailing, is
planning to open a Conran Shop selling highly-individual designer furniture and
household articles within the hotel.
The Glasgow shop will add to his specialist shops in London, Paris, Tokyo, and
one which will open soon in Milan.
Mr Des Gunewardena, chief executive of Conran Holdings, said yesterday: ``We
have chosen to concentrate the restaurants in London in the past because we
believe they needed close management.
``We only considered opening a restaurant in Glasgow because we are opening a
shop there. It is not because we think it is the second-best city in the UK for
restaurants after London.''
The two new restaurants will be sited at either end of the new hotel and will
complement the hotel's own 140-seat restaurant although they will be run as
completely separate business operations.
Conran's range of theme restaurants in London includes Quaglino's, one of
Britain's new period piece restaurants, which has been described by Egon Ronay
as a place of such brilliance in design as well as food for mass pockets that
it is ``epoch-making''.
The stable also includes Mezzo in Soho, Bibendum in South Kensington, the Blue
Print Cafe in the Design Museum at Butler's Wharf, and the nearby Le Pont de la
Tour with its cinematic views of Tower Bridge.
Mr Mosimann's restaurant in Glasgow is likely to be pitched at a slightly
higher level of clientele than Sir Terence's 100-seater, which is expected to
provide ``simple, classy cuisine in simple, classy surroundings'' and be based
on the Le Pont de la Tour.
Mr Mosimann, who developed his culinary skills while working in his family's
restaurant in Switzerland, became the youngest chef to win the prestigious Head
Chef Diploma Award. He was only 28 when he was offered the notable position of
chef de cuisine at London's Dorchester Hotel.
His skills and energy earned the hotel two Michelin stars before he left in
1988 to establish Mosimann's, an executive dining club in London's Belgravia.
The Herald understands that he will confirm his interest in the former Sheriff
Court development early in the new year. He could not be contacted for comment
yesterday.
Mr Patrick Davies, managing director of Sheriffhouse Limited, the Scottish
company created to develop the building, said yesterday: ``For many years, we
have recognised Sir Terence's abilities in retailing and lately in the creation
of landmark restaurants as being without peer on the English scene.
``We are very happy to welcome Sir Terence to join Inter-Continental in the
development of what we believe is the most prestigious building in Glasgow.''
</TEXT>
