<HEADLINE>Italians get rid of foreign lecturers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143032</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ITALIAN universities last night began sacking foreign lecturers as part of a
campaign to give their jobs to local people in defiance of European law.
Professor David Petrie, a languages lecturer from Dumbarton, who works at the
University of Verona, has not yet been sacked but has been demoted and
reclassified as a non-teacher.
Professor Petrie is leader of the Committee for the Defence of Foreign
Lecturers, whose 32 members include a German at the University of Rome. She was
sacked recently but won an injunction allowing her to keep her job meantime.
In Verona yesterday, two employees, a Frenchman and a German, were evicted from
their offices and teaching posts (which they had held for more than 12 years)
and moved to non-teaching jobs. Italians are being hired in their place. The
foreign teachers have been defended by the European Parliament and their plight
has been condemned by the European Commission. The European Court of Justice
has twice found in their favour - but the Italians have simply continued to
ignore the judges.
Professor Petrie has in the past been evicted from his office, demoted, and had
his salary cut. He won compensation and his old job back after taking his case
to the Italian courts.
Last night he said: ``So far they have not sacked me. But I expect to be
reclassified as a non-teacher and after that, who knows? I was recently told
that I could expect to be punished for putting up newspaper cuttings including
some from The Herald and the Times Literary Supplement highlighting our case at
a student meeting.''
The lecturers' case has been taken up by Labour Euro-MP Hugh McMahon, whose
Strathclyde West constituency includes Professor Petrie's home.
</TEXT>
