<HEADLINE>Lottery dodge comes unstuck</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143033</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A KEBAB shopkeeper who tricked his mistress and a policeman into backing a
#150,000 National Lottery swindle was convicted of attempted fraud yesterday.
Ali Hirli, 41, now faces up to seven years in jail. He had hoped to fool
lottery organisers Camelot with parts of two tickets stuck together with sticky
tape last December - within weeks of the lottery's launch.
The court was told Hirli had induced girlfriend Fatima Quasein, who worked for
him as a part-time cleaner, to run up to a policeman in the street pretending
her baby had chewed up a second prize ticket.
Police Constable Vincent Morley told Southwark Crown Court: ``A lady approached
me in a distressed state with this torn ticket. In very poor and broken English
she said: `Winning ticket - please help.'
``She said something about her baby had eaten it.''
He took Ms Quasein and Hirli back to the station to try and sort out the
problem.
``I was just trying to give them some assistance,'' he said.
``The ticket was in five or six pieces. I tried to stick them as best I could.''
Mr Morley then telephoned Camelot to tell them about the ticket.
Two Camelot representatives carried out security checks which showed Hirli had
joined together two tickets, both from a shop in Plaistow, east London, one
purchased on the day of the draw and the other the day after.
One half carried the winning numbers and the other part displayed the correct
date.
Mr Michael Holland prosecuting said: ``This was a crude attempt to obtain money
but nonetheless a serious and determined attempt.''
Had the fraud succeeded, Hirli would have received #149,596, for five winning
numbers plus the bonus ball.
Moroccan born Ms Quasein, of Outram Street, East Ham, east London, was cleared
of attempted fraud after explaining that although she had lied for her
boyfriend, she had not suspected the ticket was anything but genuine.
Hirli, of Brereton Road, Tottenham, north London, who claimed it was her idea,
will be sentenced on January 8.
Meanwhile, a family syndicate have collected a cheque for more than #3.3m.
Prison officer John Lane, 29, his father Brian, 52, and father-in-law Alex
Gunn, 52, plan to share the #3,338,805 with their wives and children.
Mr Lane, who kept the winning ticket in his Bible before notifying Camelot on
Monday, lives in Broadstairs, Kent, with his wife Amanda and three children,
Adam, seven, Holly, four, and Ellie, 13 months. He works at top security
Belmarsh prison in south-east London.
The Lanes plan family trips to Disneyland and a special birthday celebration
for son Adam who is eight next week.
Their syndicate has used the same nine lines of randomly chosen numbers since
the lottery began a year ago. Until now they have won just #30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
