<DOCNO>GH951129-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Critical blast at M8 horn</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143034</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS to spend #154,000 on a giant talking horn beside the M8 motorway came
under fire yesterday.
The floodlit 78ft-high steel horn is to be built at Polkemmet Country Park,
near Whitburn. It will blast out taped messages extolling the virtues of West
Lothian.
West Lothian District Council has been awarded #80,250 from the National
Lottery to help pay for the horn.
Mr Charles Eardley, chairman of Whitburn Community Council, said: ``It will be
nothing but an eyesore. A sheer waste of public money.''
The cost of the structure has risen from an original #50,000.
It has been moved from its planned site because the AA feared it could distract
motorists. Council convener Jimmy McGinley defended the horn as a work of art.
He said it was one of a number of sculptures planned to brighten up the M8.
</TEXT>
