<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Canal plan is put back on millennium agenda</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143035</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Waterways will resubmit its #30m bid for millennium lottery funding
today along with a 30,000-name petition gathered by supporters of a project
designed to create a navigable canal across Central Scotland.
An application earlier this year for funding in support of its #95m Millennium
Link project - which also plans to build a giant wheel based on the technology
of the ancient Greeks at Falkirk to link the Forth and Clyde Canal with the
Union Canal - was not given priority by the Millennium Commission.
The application was one of several projects which lost out on millennium
funding awards earlier this year. They were given B-listed status and invited
to submit more detailed second bids.
Mr Jim Stirling, British Waterways' manager in Scotland, said yesterday that
the board's bid had now been ``refocussed'', with the timescale of the project,
altered although the core project remained intact.
He remained hopeful of securing the commission's support for the project which
had received widespread support from MPs, community groups, and SusTrans, which
was awarded #42.5m of lottery funding earlier this year to create countrywide
cycle links. A decision on the application is expected early next year.
The Millennium Link proposes reopening 70 miles of canal between Bowling and
Grangemouth, creating a unique coast-to-coast Scottish waterway and a corridor
for recreation, environmental improvement, and jobs.
Under the proposal, dependent on receiving multi-million pound funding from the
Millennium Fund, a 75ft-high wheel would be built at the Falkirk Canal
Interchange at Roughcastle, to the west of Falkirk, to transfer boats from one
canal to the other.
Mr Guthrie Hutton, of the Forth and Clyde Canal Society, who helped organise
the petition, said yesterday: ``It was a tragedy when the canal closed. It
would be an even bigger tragedy if the Millennium Commission failed to support
its reopening.''
His comments were supported by Mr Tony Worthington, Labour MP for Clydebank,
who said the project would create much-needed jobs. ``Everyone I have met has
been in favour of it,'' he added.
An independent survey by Coopers and Lybrand forecast that the Millennium Link
would provide between 4200 and 4600 permanent jobs, as well as 1500
construction jobs a year while the canal and its surroundings are revitalised.
The report also predicted an increase of #40m per year in extra spending in
central Scotland.
Mr George Ballinger, British Waterways' principal engineer, urged the
Millennium Commission to recognise the importance of the bid to Scotland's
population.
``We think this is really a people's bid,'' he said, citing the fact that the
canal is within a one-hour drive of seven out of 10 Scots.
Scottish Natural Heritage yesterday also launched a more detailed second bid
for #8m of millennium funding to help create better access to the countryside
by developing a network of paths around towns, cities, and villages. The second
application expands on how the Paths For All project will be taken forward by
securing access and involving local communities in the initiative.
Meanwhile, it has emerged that islanders on Bute are considering a plan to mark
the millennium by reintroducing trams which were withdrawn from service in 1938.
The last tram ran between Rothesay and Ettrick Bay on the west side of the
island on rails which ran from the centre of Rothesay to Ardbeg and Port
Bannatyne before heading inland for two miles across to Ettrick Bay.
Rothesay Rotary Club, which is co-ordinating Bute's campaign for millennium
funds, says trolley-buses, which have been introduced in transport systems on
the Continent, could be an alternative to rail-borne trams.
Club officials are considering the possibility of running the trams or
trolley-buses from the village of Kerrycroy, south of Rothesay, linking two of
the most scenic coastal stretches on Bute.
The construction of a road bridge linking the north of the island at Rhubodach
to Colintraive on the Cowal mainland is among other options also being
considered for millennium funding.
</TEXT>
