<HEADLINE>Miroswaki looks a class apart</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By WHITE and GOLD
SEB Sanders can continue his successful run today courtesy of Miroswaki in the
two-mile Royal St Georges Handicap at Lingfield.
The youngster, who lost his right to claim in the summer, has already clinched
the apprentices' championship.
He is keeping busy by riding on the all-weather through the winter.
And he showed on Monday that he is a rider worth booking even without his
allowance when he completed a treble for three different stables.
He teams up this time with his retaining trainer, Reg Akehurst, who has already
supplied him with ammunition such as Wokingham winner Astrac this year.
Miroswaki is no potential Royal Ascot winner but he has very strong claims
today.
The gelding has proven his effectiveness both at this trip and on Lingfield's
equitrack surface.
He is now very well treated at the weights having failed to find his form this
year and is just the type whose enthusiasm is likely to have been rekindled by
a switch to Akehurst.
The Epsom trainer has time and again landed gambles with runners making their
debut for his yard and Miroswaki looks set to do the same in a race which will
take little winning.
</TEXT>
