<DOCNO>GH951129-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raiders steal festive savings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARMED raiders have stolen a group of pensioners' Christmas savings from an
Edinburgh nursing home.
Two men armed with a knife and wrench forced a male charge nurse to open a safe
containing about #1000.
The thieves appeared to be after drugs but changed their minds when they saw
the safe.
The managing director of the Edinburgh Nursing Home in Duddingston Road, which
has 40 occupants, spoke of the residents' anger.
``They are not thinking about the money at present although that may come, but
are very upset about the invasion of their privacy and the fact their homes
have been broken into,'' said 40-year-old Mrs Liz Miller.
She praised the staff and said: ``They are coping in their own ways. We are
trying to keep things as normal as possible for everyone.''
Around 3.30am yesterday, the raiders, one wearing a crash helmet, the other
sunglasses, confronted three women and one male staff member in the home's
conservatory.
After asking where drugs were kept, the knife-wielding raider forced the male
charge nurse to take him to the cashier's office while the second man guarded
the others.
None of the staff was injured and no resident was aware of the robbery. One
raider is described as aged 25, 5ft 8in and slim. He wore a blue crash helmet,
tartan scarf, and blue checked shirt.
The second is in his mid-20s, stocky, and wore a grey shirt and dark trousers.
A police spokesman said: ``This robbery was well planned. The home is situated
in a quiet area and we would like to hear from anyone such as taxi drivers who
may have passed by during the early hours of the morning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Too little' effort in venue bid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143039</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW has lost out on hosting a significant international conference worth
about #1m to the city because the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre
``did not try hard enough'', the co-organiser of Scotland's successful bid
claimed yesterday.
The 1998 conference on contaminated soil, which is expected to draw more than
1000 delegates from Europe and the US, will be held at Edinburgh International
Conference Centre after Scotland beat off competition from Austria, France, and
England to be hosts.
Edinburgh was chosen as Scottish representative in September, after the city
was invited to compete with Glasgow for the event in June.
Strathclyde University environmental management professor George Fleming, who
fronted Scotland's bid alongside Scottish Enterprise, said Glasgow was rejected
because its venue, the redeveloped SECC, had been ``bureaucratic'' and
unwilling when asked to provide plans, dates, and prices for the conference.
He said: ``Scotland has won a highly prestigious conference, representing a
multi-million-pound industry. That is great and nothing should detract from it.
``However, I am just disappointed that Glasgow could not have smiled better.
Both the Edinburgh and Glasgow convention bureaux responded beautifully but all
we were told by the SECC was that their new conference facilities would be
available from 1997 and could accommodate our numbers.''
Professor Fleming claimed he received no further response before the September
deadline when he pressed for more detail, even though artists' impressions of
the Sir Norman Foster-designed facility were available from July.
``We had to decide to leave Glasgow aside, because of the lack of effort in
providing information. I am a Glaswegian, and that hurts.''
However, the SECC's marketing director, Mr Robert Enyon, rejected the
professor's claims, saying that prices, dates, and rough floor plans had been
made available for the bid.
He said: ``Professor Fleming came to us two months into our new facilities
project at too early a stage to provide exact floor details. There would have
been no point in offering something we weren't definitely going to produce.
``We are simply pleased that Scotland has won this major conference.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
