<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DESIRABLE HABITAT</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143041</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASN'T it Sir Terence Conran who, judging the City of Architecture '99
applications, looked at a rejuvenated Castlemilk and said he would be perfectly
happy to live there? Let the picture tell the story. See what's happened to the
changing townscape of Grange Square, for example, or over at Tormusk Road.
Aspects of council housing are showing great style.
With Glasgow's population below 700,000 and people moving into the suburbs,
what's needed is the kind of working partnership Castlemilk has found. The
existing stock of houses is improved, the local environment upgraded, and every
effort made to have housing that is affordable so that people decide to stay
and, hopefully, work in the area.
The approach is to take a block of flats, reduce the overall height, provide a
new look, include individual front doors for tenants, add in gardens and a more
secure environment.
The bottom line is new flats, with off-street parking, double glazing, central
heating, new kitchens and bathrooms (but unfurnished). And local people are
positively encouraged to particpate in design aspects. Rents range from around
#103 a month for a two-apartment flat to #183 for a five-apartment. Expenditure
ranges from #38,000 to #45,000 a flat in the Grange Square and Tormusk Road
schemes - down to #15,000 per flat in other schemes.
Local authorities are seeking to bring in private sector finance to provide new
homes for sale, in peripheral schemes as well as      in purely greenbelt
areas. In Castlemilk, for instance, there has been a clear rise in demand for
council properties to rent. There is also increased interest by the private
sector. What the district council wants is for people to take pride in living
in Glasgow, in private or rented accommodation. As the population reduces and
demand for council houses falls, the need to remodel housing estates becomes
more urgent.
About 11,000 council houses have been demolished over the past 10 years. By
2000, the total could be 15,000. To give a facelift to all tenements would need
massive sums. But, if Castlemilk is anmything to go by, it could make a world
of difference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fair exchange for home buyers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert MacLeod</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143042</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Robert MacLeod looks at a scheme to help families move up and down the housing
ladder
THE ideal of a new address by Christmas is still a practical reality for some
of the Scottish families who take advantage of one of the many new
part-exchange purchase schemes now available in most parts of the country.
``Most builders have been fine-tuning their part-exchange scheme procedures to
make the whole process smoother and as swift as possible in terms of getting
information about survey valuations back to clients,'' said the director of
sales for one prominent West of Scotland builder.
``Part-exchange is continuing to grow month by month in terms of its importance
in the overall new house purchase scene in Scotland. Most builders will readily
agree that l995 has been a fantastic year for part-exchange growth, easily
surpassing last year's figures. More and more people have experienced
part-exchange schemes as the best option for speedy, frustration-free moves.''
In some new house developments at least 30% of families moving in are able to
do so because they have taken advantage of a builder's part-exchange plan. At
the same time, a growing number of first-time and other buyers are finding
their dream of a new home becoming reality when they buy a competitively priced
``established home'' from builders selling part-exchange houses.
As the part-exchange option keeps growing in popularity, two of Scotland's
largest housebuilders now point out that they are prepared to consider
properties located anywhere in Britain when customers come forward saying that
they want to relocate in Scotland.
In another widening of the market, the same builders now emphasise that they
are extending their part-exchange schemes to include a section of the
house-buying market which may previously have felt excluded.
``Most part-exchange schemes are intended to assist families trading up towards
a larger new house, with a typical upward difference which may be around
#20,000,'' said another sales director. ``But there are people who, for a whole
variety of reasons, may wish to move to a smaller home - then find that their
existing property can't be accepted for part-exchange because they are trading
down.
``The answer has been to introduce a new and supplementary part-exchange
scheme. In our case, we now work in conjunction with a major group of estate
agents and offer these owners of larger properties a special package of help to
assist in the marketing of their existing property.''
A very wide variety of properties have been bought in by builders in recent
months in part-exchange packages. They have covered a spread from modest flats
priced at around #2l,000 to larger, top of the range family properties at
values sometimes exceeding #150,000.
``Part-exchange schemes are taking the hassle and concern out of the process of
selling an existing property and leaving the way clear for more and more
families to achieve the move which is their goal.''
Stage one in any part-exchange scheme is for the builder to arrange two
independent and separate valuations to be carried out on the customer's
existing home. Following that, the builder can make a carefully decided
part-exchange offer, usually guaranteed for a stated period. The usual aim is
to get back to the customer with that proposed offer within seven days.
``There is nothing really new about part-exchange in the house-building
world,'' said the marketing manager for a firm currently building a wide range
of homes in sites throughout the Central Belt. ``We have offered our own scheme
to customers for the past twelve years. It was first introduced to combat the
difficult market conditions of that time. Today, like many other firms, we now
view part-exchange as an established and basic part of the general house
building business and one which is very much here to stay.''
All concerned agree that any home owner considering part-exchange - ``a service
that can unlock the chains on house sales'' would be well advised to examine
the many options now available in the schemes now being offered by various
builders.
It is an indication of how popular part-exchange has become that one builder
now has an office specifically to deal with that demand. But most others have
details of their particular schemes available at their show houses. The size of
the market involved is illustrated by one builder who achieved a #10m turnover
of established homes last year. He has already seen that figure overtaken in
l995.
Different firms offer different fringe benefits and it can be to the
house-hunter's benefit to compare packages and decide which would be best
suited to particular needs and circumstances.
The many options can include packages covering additional financial assistance
or such things as low interest mortgage packages, plus legal costs and survey
fees being partially funded. Some include free mortgage protection assurance
over a period of up to three years, offering payments of up to a maximum of
twelve months.
The experts agree that when part exchange is part of a new house purchase then
customers can relax knowing what price has been achieved by their exisitng
property and also the contractually agreed price on their new home. The
guesswork has thankfully gone, the commercial risk element is being taken on by
the builder.
They are careful to warn that not everyone automatically qualifies for part
exchange and, above all, the rule has to be that both parties are totally
satisfied before an agreement goes ahead.
But more and more the part exchange option is smoothing the path towards a new
home. With everybody happy.
</TEXT>
