<DOCNO>GH951129-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ENDING KITCHEN-SUNK DRAMAS</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143043</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n HAVE got that sinking feeling? Is your cornice cracking, your skirting
sagging? A house that is subsiding can create tremors in your bank balance but,
if you are properly insured, the problem need not lead to total collapse of
your dream home.
Nationwide, the UK's second largest building society, has produced a
leaflet-guide to subsidence. Designed to help customers who think they may need
to make a claim on their insurance, it also aims to put their minds at ease by
offering advice on......
l.How to recognise subsidence, heave and landslip.
l.What to do if movement of the house is suspected.
l.The different steps involved in making an insurance claim for subsidence and
details of what to expect from the insurers.
l.The kind of questions they are likely          to be asked, enabling them to
save time              by getting the information in advance.
The guide is free to Nationwide borrowers who think they may have subsidence
and wish to claim. Peter Richardson, Nationwide's marketing director, says:
``The aim is to help our customers understand more about subsidence and its
causes, and to reassure them that there are solutions. The guide helps them
with claim procedures and provides sources of contact. We hope it will allay
many fears.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Students reap the rewards of education</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143045</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ADULT learners and ambitious students were rewarded for their efforts in
acquiring new skills and qualifications at the annual Scottish Vocational
Education Council awards ceremony in Glasgow yesterday.
Eight students from colleges across Scotland gathered at the Royal Concert Hall
to receive a student of the year award and a cheque for #350 after
demonstrating exceptional skill and commitment.
Scotvec, the Glasgow-based training organisation, also recognised the efforts
of six schools, four further education colleges, two training organisations,
and a hospital for encouraging people to take up courses.
Among those picking up a trophy was Ms Doreen Carnan, 49, who ventured back
into the world of education after her daughter Connie, 20, was seriously
injured in a car accident nearly nine years ago.
Ms Carnan said that while her daughter lay in a coma she took swimming lessons
and noticed a sign for adult education. She then completed a number of care
courses to help her look after Connie.
One course led to another and despite leaving school with no qualifications Ms
Carnan has completed around 30 Scotvec courses including hairdressing, machine
knitting, and a medical receptionist course at the city's Anniesland College.
Accompanied by her daughter, who now works for Marks &amp; Spencer, she said she
was surprised and delighted to receive an award. Studying, she added, had been
a tremendous experience, opened up a new world and given her something to focus
on while helping her daughter to recover from her injuries.
Speaking at the ceremony, the chief executive of Scottish Enterprise, Mr
Crawford Beveridge, stressed the importance of training and said companies
could compete only if they had a skilled workforce. ``The simple question we
all have to ask is whether we are happy to continuously slip down the
international table of wealth or whether we want to do something about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bishop pleads with IRA to give up `missing' victims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143046</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING Roman Catholic bishop yesterday pleaded with the IRA to reveal where
its members buried the bodies of at least a dozen people killed during the
Troubles.
The Bishop of Down and Connor, Dr Patrick Walsh, made his appeal as relatives
of the missing revealed plans to carry empty coffins through Belfast on
Christmas Eve to highlight the issue.
Speaking at a service of remembrance in St Mary's Church, Belfast, the bishop
said: ``In the name of humanity, in the name of Christ, I make a fervent and
heartfelt plea for the return of thebodies.''
He added that respect for the dead had always been regarded as a sign of a
civilised society.
``In Ireland, there has been a long and honoured tradition of having a wake at
home so that in the natural and homely setting of the family the relatives can
take their personal farewell of their loved ones.''
He said it was recognised as a valuable constituent of the grieving process
which the relatives of the disappeared had been denied, making their loss more
intense.
One of the relatives, Mr Seamus McKendry, will be among the guests at a west
Belfast factory to be visited by US President Bill Clinton tomorrow.
The IRA kidnapped, killed, and buried his mother-in-law in 1972.
Mr McKendry told the congregation yesterday that the families did not want
revenge, nor political gain, just the return of the bodies.
``They are buried some place on this island, hidden away and forgotten about by
those who try to monopolise justice.
``Today we ask that those responsible for this suffering and anguish own up to
their responsibilities - no-one has the right to keep our families hanging
around in limbo.
``We do not want these masked men and women unmasked, we do not seek
incarceration . . . a phone call, an anonymous letter, a note slipped under a
door will suffice.''
President Clinton has already called for the bodies of the disappeared to be
returned. However, he could face new demands during his visit to Northern
Ireland to put more pressure on Sinn Fein to help end the relative's distress.
Revealing the plans to carry the coffins through Christmas shoppers to a
candlelight vigil outside City Hall in Belfast, Mr McKendry said it was time
republicans realised that the missing had a right to be buried on consecrated
ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What a pity anti-Catholicism had to spoil it</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143047</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE second, smaller, part of John Macleod's article (November 28) devoted to
the Princess of Wales's Panorama interview was one of the best I have read on
the subject. What a pity he had to spoil it.
The Irish Referendum on divorce is an item which has been the subject of much
debate among commentators. Rightly so; as the result showed, it is seen by many
as another example of the erosion of traditional Christian values and influence
in an increasingly secular world. Indeed some weeks ago John Macleod himself
lamented on this trend.
While not agreeing with their specific case one would have thought that he
would have had a grudging respect for their stand and some sympathy for those
who lost the argument.
Alas no; when John Macleod writes about anything Catholic he seems to lose all
sense of proportion and we are subjected, once again, to historical
half-truths, irrelevances, and embellishments based on his own particular
prejudices.
As a responsible newspaper you surely have a responsibility to discuss matters
involving religion with sensitivity. Do you think think it enhances the debate
by giving free-rein to John Macleod's sectarian outbursts? He is a talented
writer who can be controversial without being offensive to Scottish Catholics,
or any other minority.
J V O'Donnell,
2 Wallace Place,
Falkirk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>To drag us into the eighteenth century</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143048</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM the outset let me make it plain that I am a Scot, born, bred, and educated
in Ayrshire and Glasgow.
I, too, have stood on the terraces at Hampden, roaring on my beloved Scotland
against all ``enemies'', and in particular the ``effete English''.
That having been said, I found The Herald Essay of November 25 to be an utterly
incomprehensible anachronism.
I enjoy The Herald for its appreciation of the exquisite English language and
do not expect it to give credence to the spread of such drivel.
For the same reason I have no time for the ludicrous radio broadcasts of Billy
Kay.
Such people would have us dragged screaming into the eighteenth century.
David S Wilson,
11 Lomond Drive,
Newton Mearns,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
