<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No saviour Dull and devious Budgete</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke insisted that he was not of the slash and burn
tendency when he began his Budget statement yesterday.  He went on to prove it
by demonstrating instead an unsuspected ability to snap and singe.  This was
not an adventurous budget; bunnets remain firmly on heads, although City bowler
hats may oscillate gently with approval; all-in-all it was dull, workmanlike
and possibly devious.  We cannot criticise Mr Clarke for this.  He could have
emulated Chancellor Lawson and thrown caution to the winds with a Budget that
might have allowed Britain to feel good at the expense of much pain afterwards.
We should be glad that he did nothing of the sort.  Britain, as a
medium-to-small nation and economy in not particularly good shape, needs
measured and sensible growth rather than any consumer sprint which would
inevitably lead to inflation and further decline.  To that extent, for his
prudence, common sense, and an endearing tendency to make the best of a weak
hand, he may feel content.
Yet there are large questions which are unanswered by the numbers presented by
Mr Clarke.  Estimates of economic growth are notoriously difficult but they are
also important, both psychologically and as a gauge of how the economy is
performing.  The Treasury has missed the target with past forecasts and this is
unfortunate.  Last year it was estimated that growth ove the succeeding 12
months would be 3.25%.  That figure was reduced to 3% earlier this year and
yesterday the Chancellor confirmed that the actual figure would be 2.75%.  We
are not unique in this as national economies around the globe have dipped over
the same period but the downturn has been more noticeable in Britain.  Stocks
have grown much faster than output, investment is poor and showing little sign
of improvement and even exporters, appear  to have rested on their
achievements.  There is nothing in the Budget, apart from the hope of steady
growth and stability, which will remedy this situation.
Unemployment
Nor is there anything coherent which could be described as a serious attempt to
deal with unemployment.  Those measures aimed at businesses, and particularly
small businesses, are welcome.  They will give this vulnerable end of our
business community a measure of breathing space in the form of reductions in
corporation tax and business rates bills, but welcome as this is it is simply
not capable of making much of a dent in the unemployment figures.  It is all
very well to repeat ad nauseam that growth in the economy will eventually lead
to a reduction in unemployment but, in a situation where many people have been
unemployed for a long time, this is an insufficient answer.  And then there is
the Private Finance Initiative, re-launched repeatedly but no more capable of
floating towards harbour than it has ever been.  The Chancellor's emphasis on
this fig-leaf of a policy was one of the most worrying parts of the speech for
the signs are clear that private business has better things to do with its
money and is likely to be strongly tempted only by concessions which would
amount to state subsidy.  None of the measures proposed will create jobs,
either directly or indirectly, and for the sake of the social fabric of the
country this issue should have been addressed with more urgency and commitment.
It is possible, indeed probable, that there is more to come on the subject of
the wider economy.  By keeping tax cuts to the absolute minimum necessary for
what the Tory Party regards as decency, the Chancellor has opened up a degree
of freedom to cut interest rates in the near future.  A simple 1p reduction in
tax, taken together with apparently energetic cutting of Government expenditure
in certain areas, has ensnared a favourable reaction from the City.  With this
in his pocket Mr Clarke will be able to work on an interest rate cut before the
end of the year.  He has been helped by the slowdown in economic growth but
will need to keep a close eye on the value of the pound which will curtail his
ability to cut interest rates.
This is all very well, the various tweakings, trimmings and twitches to the
economy are interesting but of a somewhat neutral nature.  Surveying it all we
have to pinch ourselves hard to recall that until this week the Budget was
being routinely described as the most important in many years, the Budget which
would make or break the Tory Party.  It was to be a political Budget and
rumoured to contain just the sort of proposals traditionally required  to haul
the Government's rapidly burning electoral coals out of the fire.  It appears
to be nothing of the sort, at least not at first glance.  Tory back benchers
are rallying round gamely and proclaiming that a headline 1p income tax cut is
prudent and therefore likely to enhance their reputation as good managers of
the economy, but in their hearts they are disappointed.
Housing Benefits
The abandonment of the sagging housing market to the mystical benefits of an
improving economy will be particularly galling to many Tory MPs who will have
been under steady and increasing pressures from their constituencies  for
something, anything, to be done.  Perhaps the Chancellor is correct and nothing
can be done in the short term but it will not sell well in the South-east.
There are things to cheer Tory MPs, of course.  The assaults on social security
looks like being serious, although an assessment of just how serious, it is
must wait for the fine detail. The restriction on housing benefits for the
under-25s is mean-minded and unworthy while the Chancellor's enthusiasm for
helping older citizens through savings plans and help with care in older age
suggests that he has paid much more attention to the latest
economic/demographic studies.  The spending figures for education, police, and
the NHS likewise imply that Mr Clarke's eye for political advantage has not
dimmed.
Nevertheless, there is something missing.  Nobody in possession of their senses
could believe that this Budget will save the Tory Party.  At least it provides
a steady hand, a soothing voice and a hope for better times.  It suggests
something else: that is the racing certainty that the Government is determined
to hold out until the spring of 1997, or as near to it as it can get.  This
would allow another Budget a year hence in which all the magic tricks of a
political Chancellor could be produced with a flourish.  True, they would not
have the slightest chance of coming into effect before the General Election but
in Mr Clarke's assessment that does not matter.  They will look good, sound
good, and they will do the Tory Party good.  That, at least, is the
calculation, which has the added benefit of featuring a give-away Budget which
would either win the election for the Tories or leave an incoming Labour
government with an almighty mess.  If that is too cynical, consider the
position of the Ulster Unionists.
Peace Process
If the Government hangs on until 1997 their support will be vital, yet Mr
Trimble and his associates are tough men and it is clear that they have little
confidence in Mr Major's handling of the peace process.  The Budget may have
passed, just, but the peace in Northern Ireland is clearly balanced on a
precipice.  The Chancellor may be determined to play a long game, but the game
may yet be taken from him by events which he cannot control.
It is a strange Budget, more subtle than it looks and not really what was
expected.  It is not populist but is not austere, neither does it raise the
hopes of either the country or of the Tory Party.  We have left the subject of
whisky to the last, admittedly not a Scottish trait.  Duty has been reduced but
only an inebriate would forget that it was increased by much the same amount
last year.  Yet Mr Clarke is the first Chancellor in a hundred years actually
to reduce the duty on whisky.  Given his fondness for it, he might find that
fact an acceptable epitaph, given that his original choice - saviour of the
Tory Party - no longer looks attainable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
