<HEADLINE>Clinton prepared for packed schedule</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143051</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US President Bill Clinton is due to touch down at Heathrow at about 7am before
launching into an action-packed three-day schedule.
He plans talks with all the province's political leaders including Mr Gerry
Adams and fringe loyalists this evening at a reception at Queen's University
and a senior US Government official said: ``We hope that at the reception the
president will have the opportunity for good substantive exchanges with the
party leaders.''
Mr Clinton's day in London includes a visit to the tomb of the unknown soldier
at Westminster Abbey, talks at Downing Street with Mr Major, followed by a
joint news conference, then an address to both Houses of Parliament.
After that, he goes to Buckingham Palace to meet the Queen, holds a meeting
with Labour leader Tony Blair at the US ambassador's residence in Regents Park,
and attends an evening dinner and reception at Downing Street.
Tomorrow, he flies to Belfast, becoming the first American president to visit
Northern Ireland, and travels immediately to a factory in the nationalist
Springfield Road in west Belfast, where he will make a keynote speech before
heading across town to Unionist-dominated east Belfast.
In Londonderry, he will meet representatives of both sides of the community and
will do so again when he meets Belfast City councillors after switching on the
Christmas tree lights outside Belfast City Hall, which is expected to draw huge
crowds. Belfast-born rock star Van Morrison will perform songs there.
A normal lighting-up ceremony attracts crowds of around 15,000 but the RUC
expect that to be exceeded many times over.
Mrs Hillary Clinton will remain at her husband's side for most of the visit but
will break away for a meeting with female activists from both sides of the
community in a restaurant in south Belfast's Ormeau road - scene of clashes
between Orangemen and Republicans during the summer marching season.
Among those meeting the first lady will be Joyce McCartan, from the Ormeau
road, whose 17-year-old son was killed by UVF gunmen in 1987.
On Friday, the focus switches to the republic. There will be meetings with
President Mary Robinson and Mr Bruton, with a press statement to be issued
after the latter.
Mr Clinton will address a public rally at College Green, where the freedom of
Dublin will be conferred on him. He will then make a joint address to the Dail
and Senate. He may also take time out to enjoy a pint of Guinness in a city pub.
In the evening, he will attend a dinner hosted by Mr Bruton at Dublin Castle
and then flies out on Saturday morning.
</TEXT>
