<HEADLINE>Catholic Church gives euthanasia warning as hospital goes to court Family plea to let coma mother die</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Buie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143052</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Today a family will seek permission to withdraw feeding for a woman who has
lain in a coma for more than three years. Elizabeth Buie looks at the questions
raised by Scotland's first `right to die' court case
SCOTLAND'S first ``right to die'' case will be heard in the Court of Session
today. Law Hospital NHS Trust, with the backing of the family of Mrs Janet
Johnston, 50, of Allanton, near Shotts, will ask the court for permission to
withdraw the feeding system of their patient who has lain in a coma for more
than three years since being admitted to hospital after taking an overdose.
Doctors are agreed that she is in a persistent vegetative state (PVS) with no
hope of recovery. Only artificial feeding is keeping her alive. Mrs Johnston's
daughter, Linda, has been seen on television pleading for her mother to be
allowed to find peace.
The Archdiocese of Glasgow, in its magazine, Flourish, has accused the family
of thinking of itself, rather than seeking peace for Mrs Johnston herself. It
has also warned that giving legal sanction to the withdrawal of artificial
feeding will open the way to the legalisation of euthanasia.
However, the hospital's senior staff say they are bringing the case on
humanitarian grounds.
There can be little doubt this case is intended to clarify the law in Scotland
as regards the treatment of PVS patients. For, although the House of Lords
ruled two years ago in the case of Tony Bland, the young Hillsborough Disaster
victim, its decision is only persuasive in Scotland, not binding. Doctors want
to know where they stand, and particularly whether their actions, even if they
are in accordance with good medical practice, could still leave them open to
prosecution.
Earlier this year, the Scottish Law Commission recommended that doctors in
Scotland should be able to switch off life-support machines that are keeping
brain-dead patients alive and withdraw treatment for the terminally ill without
the risk of being prosecuted or sued - in essence that a doctor's duty of care
does not and should not extend to providing futile medical treatment to
incapable patients.
The issue of switching off life-support machines for brain-dead patients is
largely settled in the public mind. However, the treatment of PVS cases is not.
In their situation, the brain-stem is intact, permitting the patient to breathe
independently, but the higher levels of the brain are damaged beyond hope of
recovery.
It was the case of Tony Bland that really opened up to public debate the issue
of whether artificial feeding, which is necessary to keep the patient alive,
constitutes a medical intervention. Doctors maintain it does, and that its
withdrawal comes within the scope of the decisions they have to make daily to
discontinue treatment which is no longer of benefit to the patient.
However, one of the difficulties of PVS cases is it can take some time for the
condition to be safely regarded as irrevocable. The British Medical Association
therefore recommends a minimum of one year of insentience before that decision
is reached. After that point, the BMA believes the persistent vegetative state
can be declared permanent.
The House of Lords' ruling in the Bland case confirmed it is acceptable in some
circumstances for a decision to be made to provide or withdraw treatment in the
patient's best interests, but that until such time as a body of experience and
practice has built up, each case will have to go before a court.
However, no-one has yet satisfactorily explained what the patient's ``best
interests'' are, how they are measured, or whether it can ever be in anyone's
interests to be allowed to die rather than be kept alive.
In Scotland, up until the Bland judgment, it was generally held that if a
doctor acted in accordance with responsible body of medical opinion, he was not
acting negligently if he withdrew artificial feeding. But there was no clear
legal direction and the issue remained: is the removal of tubal feeding an act
or an omission? If a doctor has a straightforward duty of care, then surely he
or she has a duty not to omit in the same way as he or she has an obligation to
act? Or is this issue simply a ``distinction with a difference''?
As the supreme civil court in the UK, the House of Lords' ruling in Bland
should have laid the matter to rest. But while its judgment is highly
persuasive in Scotland, it is not binding, and it will be open to the Court of
Session to reach a different conclusion in the Johnston case.
The other underlying problem with the Bland case is that, while all five House
of Lords judges reached the same conclusion, they arrived at it from different
perspectives and using different arguments. Significantly, two of them
suggested this was not a matter for the courts and they urged the Government to
legislate.
Against this background, the Court of Session's ruling is likely to be very
significant. The court has a number of options before it:
n.To disallow the withdrawal of tubal feeding on the grounds this equates with
passive euthanasia and is therefore a criminal offence.
n.To claim the argument is not backed up sufficiently by medical evidence and
that withdrawal of tubal feeding would be negligent.
n.To authorise removal because it is not in the interests of the individual to
be kept in this condition.
n.To allow withdrawal because such an action is based on current medical
practice.
The Court of Session may then rule on whether each future case must be
considered in court - as the House of Lords did in Bland - or it may lay down
guidelines that hospitals must follow in future, which is what the BMA favours.
Professor Sheila McLean, head of Glasgow University's Institute of Law and
Ethics in Medicine, would like the court to call for Government legislation.
She is concerned that decisions on PVS cases may be considered purely on
clinical grounds, while in her opinion they are a matter that society as a
whole must consider.
She adds that medical teams may inevitably find themselves taking resource
implications into account. They will honestly believe such considerations do
not come into the equation, but subliminally, the question will be there.
``Prognosis and diagnosis are clinical, but as a society we have a role in
saying whether this is a right thing to do with people simply because their
condition is hopeless,'' she says.
Nor have relatives a technical legal right to make decisions about healthcare
in respect of an adult person. They cannot be dispassionate. For some people,
if a member of their family is in a PVS condition, not suffering, the instinct
may be to say they should be allowed to go peacefully. Others may argue for
keeping them alive at all costs as long as possible.
``I actually think that relatives and doctors are very well placed to
understand the grief that is going on because they are experiencing it. But I
do not think they are sufficiently distanced or dispassionate to leave the
decision up to them,'' says Professor McLean.
If we are to follow down the path she suggests and adopt permissive legislation
dealing with difficult cases such as this - in the way the Government did over
the Abortion Act - then as a society we will have to consider many related
issues. How do we feel about voluntary euthanasia, or even non-voluntary
euthanasia? What is our position on assisted suicide?
Can we actually find the courage to state openly what is quietly acknowledged -
that we allow some handicapped infants to die, and accept the decision of
rational adults when they say they do not wish certain treatment?
Professor McLean believes we should start from the point that it is always
wrong to take another person's life - but there are certain conditions which if
met, will not render such an action wrong.
``This would give everybody involved, doctors and families, a set of tests
against which they can measure their judgment. It would relieve them of the
pressures. It would take the moral burden away from them and allow those of us
who are competent at the moment security in the knowledge we will be treated
with respect,'' she says.
Those with religious objections would not be obliged to participate.
She also argues from a pragmatic point of view, saying that such actions are
taking place anyway and it would, therefore, be better if they were carried out
according to guidelines.
She also believes it would be kinder to doctors and families - for doctors,
because at present they have to shoulder an awesome responsibility, a
responsibility particularly hard to bear for people who have been trained to
cure and to restore health.
Some medical experts believe there are between 1000 and 1500 PVS cases in the
UK at present. It is possible the Court of Session's ruling may lead to a long
string of other hospitals coming to court to ask permission to withdraw
artificial feeding; or the responsibility may be thrown back at the doctors and
families, and the public will never know how many decisions have been taken
privately to accord the right to die; or, in the final analysis, the court may
rule it is not in Mrs Johnston's best interests to have her tubal feeding
withdrawn.
</TEXT>
