<HEADLINE>Complete new start on defence spending</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143053</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU report that Britain's Armed Forces no longer have the capacity to launch a
Falklands-style operation (Britain's sinking power on the seas, November 27).
Garrisoning and rehearsing the reinforcement of the Falklands and South
Georgia, the sovereign bases in Cyprus, Gibraltar, Ascension, Diego Garcia,
Hong Kong, and other British dependent territories are legacies of the British
Empire which consume around 15% of the UK's defence budget.
To maintain an illusion of greatness with Trident the Government admits to
spending 8.6% of the defence budget, although the true cost is much higher.
The money invested in Trident might have been better spent equipping the
conventional forces to meet their post-imperial obligations.
The most refreshing aspect of the current defence review in the SNP is that
none of the above obligations, either inherited or chosen by the UK parties,
will be incumbent upon an independent Scotland.
Not only will the people of Scotland, through their parliament, be able to
choose where and when they will deploy Scotland's forces. The reduction in
defence expenditure brought about by being released from the above obligations
will also free resources for defence diversification and investment in the
infrastructure of Scotland.
Colin Campbell,
SNP Defence Spokesperson,
Braeside, Shuttle Street,
Kilbarchan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
