<HEADLINE>Corruption trial told of favours by policeman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143054</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICE officer on trial for corruption advised a man with whom he regularly
drank how to deal with a police investigation into incidents, including one
involving a firearm, in which he had been involved, the High Court in Aberdeen
was told yesterday.
Ian William Smith, 32, who the court has heard was known as ``Fat Billy'' and
was a police informant, said he had been friendly with a number of policemen
through his job as a barman, including the accused, Mr Neil Cooper.
He said as well as being a barman at the time he had sold fake watches,
perfume, and T-shirts, and recalled an incident in which he lost a briefcase
which contained #600 or #700 worth of watches.
He said he phoned Mr Cooper at Grampian Police headquarters and asked him to
let him know if he heard anything about them. He told the court that, a week
later, Mr Cooper contacted him and gave him the name of the man who was
apparently selling them.
He and a friend, Ronald Cormack, who the court has heard is serving 15 years
for drugs and firearms offences, tracked him down to his home.
Smith said the man, Brian Brown, had threatened them, at which point Cormack
had gone to his car and returned with a handgun which he held at Brown's face.
Brown then agreed to return the watches.
Smith said he had been concerned and had phoned Mr Cooper because the incident
had become more serious than he had expected.
He told the court: ``Mr Cooper said it was stupid and he wasn't very happy but
just to leave it with him.''
Smith said that, a few weeks later, he received a call from Mr Cooper who told
him a report had been received about the incident.
He contacted Cormack and they both met Mr Cooper outside a bar before they
later reported to the police station.
Smith claimed Mr Cooper told them to deny having the gun. He said to say they
had been in Brown's house but did not have a gun.
Asked why Mr Cooper had warned him, he said: ``Because he was my pal.''
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fine cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>AILEEN LITTLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143055</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVER heard of a meat boutique? They have in Stonehaven. Shoppers in the
Kincardineshire town have become blase about the flair of their unusual butcher
shop - Charles McHardy's - in the market square. The 88-year-old family
business prides itself on employing a professional to dress the windows: the
Christmas display went up last week. And trade has gone up by 20% since
McHardy's became top butcher's shop in Scotland earlier this year.
Charles McHardy and his brother Kenneth crowned previous owners by winning the
Meat Trade Journal's new Top Shop Award For Scotland. They are also UK
runners-up.
In the past, the Journal has run numerous product competitions, but this is the
first time the focus has been on shops as a whole. The three judges - a meat
and livestock commission inspector, a food economist and a freelance journalist
- declared McHardy's to have ``not only a superb choice of product, but a whole
range of foods to make a complete meal''. And they were very impressed with the
hygiene standards.
Charles McHardy recalls the judges did a very thorough job: ``They were into
our computer programme to see how we do pricing, they were running fingers
across the top of pictures - they were practically under the floorboards.'' In
common with the other 215 participants who entered the first round, McHardy's
was nominated by wholesalers and was required to submit an illustrated CV.
Scotland was one of seven UK areas represented. The 35 shops who were graduated
to the next round had to submit to rigorous inspection.
Of Top Shop Award's 21 finalists, 16 belong to the Q Guild, an exclusive meat
retailers' association which grants membership (50 in Scotland) to those who
meet its high standards. Like many Q Guild members, McHardy's enter products
for the three-yearly meat traders fair at Utrecht; it is through visits to
Holland that the brothers became aware of the gulf between continental and
British butchers. ``The Dutch are clean, methodical and good businessmen,''
says Charles. ``The average UK butcher falls down on presentation.''
To that end, McHardy's has spent #140,000 over the last seven years in
state-of-the-art refurbishment.
Patrons of McHardy, some of whom travel 15 miles from Aberdeen, can choose from
15 ready-made meals including Chicken Catalan (which won a gold medal at
Smithfield) and 14 different stir-frys. Steak and chicken wine marinades are
especially popular, as is the shop's diversification into bakery products,
overseen by the McHardys' niece. For Christmas, the brothers are preparing
their sought-after boned turkey stuffed with ham; and they supply hampers
(smoked gammon, tongue etc) for oil companies in the area.
Charles explains: ``We hope to cure our own bacon, even smoke it and we're
considering a mail shot. Our competitors are the supermarkets, so we want to do
all the things they can't do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Victory for formalde-hype</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143056</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAMIEN Hirst, the man who floats sheep and cows in glass cases, was last night
named this year's winner of the #20,000 Turner prize.
The controversial conceptual artist had been favourite of the four shortlisted
artists to win.
He had the highest public profile, thanks to the notoriety of his work and to
his populist approach.
Jury members said they thought this year's artists had been varied and well
matched.
Hirst, 30, was presented with his prize at an awards dinner at the Tate Gallery
in London by Brian Eno, avant garde musician and former Roxy Music member.
His main exhibit at the shortlist show - a cow and calf each cut in half and
called Mother and Child Divided - was late going on display because preserving
fluid threatened to leak from the display cases.
He also showed two of his ``spot'' paintings called after modern
pharmaceuticals.
However, the judges awarded him the prize for exhibitions in Pittsburgh,
Berlin, and the Serpentine Gallery, London.
Hirst has said: ``I wanted to make art that everybody could believe in.''
The jury, chaired by Tate director Nicholas Serota, praised him ``for having
created an extraordinary series of objects that have caught the public
imagination.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skye protesters say it with ale</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143057</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROTESTERS will be raising a glass to the Skye bridge in the New Year when an
anti-toll real ale is produced to help in the fight to scrap the tolls.
Portree High School teachers Angus MacRuary and Steve Tinney, who run the
newly-opened Leann an Eilein (The Isle of Skye Brewing Company) at Uig, will be
brewing Extortion-Ale to publicise the high tolls on the bridge.
Man shot
POLICE were investigating what was understood to be a shooting incident in the
Niddrie area of Edinburgh late last night. A spokesman said there had been a
serious incident in the vicinity of Greendykes Road. It is understood a
middle-aged man was shot. Early today, eight police vehicles were parked
outside a three-storey block of flats in Greendykes Road as officers
investigated. Police were on patrol around the building.
Church for sale
THE Church of Scotland is selling the Old Parish Church, Alexandria,
Dunbartonshire, which houses the town clock. The building became surplus to
requirements when congregations in the Vale of Leven area merged last year.
Robbery foiled
POLICE in Edinburgh are investigating an attempted robbery at a Pik-N-Save
grocer's shop, in Easter Drylaw Place, Drylaw, where staff, threatened with a
handgun, foiled the two men by locking the till and throwing the keys away. The
men, in their mid-20s, drove off in a stolen blue Ford van.
Fumes scare
TWO young female students were taken to hospital in Edinburgh after being
overcome by ammonia fumes from a leaking refrigerator at their residence in the
city's Warrender Park Road, yesterday. A spokeswoman at Edinburgh Royal
Infirmary said the students were released after treatment.
Hogmanay buses
EXTRA free buses will take revellers home after this year's Edinburgh Hogmanay
street party. Lothian Regional Council said yesterday the number of buses would
be increased from 34 to 53 and would run from St Andrew Square from 15 minutes
after midnight until 3.15am on January 1.
Homely hotel
MS Tricia Fitzsimons, 33, whose father, John, is the senior sheriff at
Dumbarton, has taken over as general manager of the Mews Hilton in Park Lane,
London. She intends to make it the most homely hotel in the capital. One of her
first moves will be to buy a ``big soppy dog to lie in front of the fire''.
Sewage decision
STRATHCLYDE councillors agreed yesterday to seek local planning permission for
structures to house disinfection and screening equipment for sewage outfalls at
Greenan and Cromwell Road, to the south of the river Ayr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
