<TEXT>
There's a new look for the career woman - and it suits her. John Davidson finds
that power dressing is giving way to a more feminine style
WHAT'S happened to power dressing? Forget your preconceptions - that pair of
outsize shoulder pads and a rather assertive lapel line. The new armour of the
executive woman is feminine elegance.
Disarming is exactly the effect of such svelte sophistication - as streamlined
and unadorned as a sixties skyscraper. Like modernist architecture, fuss-free
daytime dressing depends on strong simple lines, spare, minimal detailing and
distinctive fabrications.
Maybe there is something just vaguely reminiscent of the late fifties and early
sixties in these refined clothes, the way an eyebrow is to be drawn, those
carefully defined lips. But this is not another wave of retro-fashion - better
suited to fancy-dress than life in the real world. This is fashion defined by
committed modernists like Gianni Versace.
Some principles of the business world just never change. Which means that city
style is still based on the suit. But the newest suit fits as snugly as the
satin glove which is its unexpected partner. (Yes - even for business.) The
jacket is cut brace-close to the midriff; skirts hug the hips in what could be
termed an intimate caress. Or, most radically, the suit becomes a lean-fitting
sleeveless dress worn under a matching jacket or coat.
Ease is abolished. In its place comes effect. And for effect, think effort. For
there is nothing carefree or careless about the new ideal of elegance.
It takes a deal of time and application to work nails into that perfect short,
French manicure. It takes practice to master really elegant heels. And it
surely requires a computerlike memory to dispense with all the paraphernalia of
information materials in order that hand baggage can be restricted to an
elegant clutch.
No briefcase? Well, there's true minimalism for you. Clearly this new executive
woman is so successful that she has someone else to lug her laptop.
</TEXT>
