<HEADLINE>Fiscal's priorities</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143060</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE ARE constantly advised that there is a lack of both financial and human
resources in the prosecution service in Scotland with little prospect of funds
being made available to correct this.
The press reports that recently a court in Falkirk was closed and offenders set
free all because there was no prosecutor available to deal with the cases.
Against this background how does the procurator-fiscal in Glasgow best utilise
his scarce resources? He sits with a notebook and video recorder watching an
on-field incident at a football match. The fact that such matches are subject
to their disciplinary code seems to escape him.
The justification for all this effort and expense is some nebulous theory that
the public may take a lead from the conduct of those they are watching on the
field. There is no evidence to support this.
Surely in the present climate the fiscal's energies could be better channelled
elsewhere. On the other hand there are those of us who might regard this
interest in football by the authorities as a cynical attempt to draw attention
away from their inadequacies in more routine cases.
James R S Tolmie,
15 Campbell Drive,
Bearsden.
</TEXT>
