<HEADLINE>When it comes to fancy footwork Michael Forsyth has everyone dancing to his own tune Like a man who can't lose</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143061</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Secretary has become adept at confounding his critics. Margaret
Vaughan profiles a politician who is sure of his own standing
WE were all wrong, you know, to conjure up those spine-chilling images on
Michael Forsyth's return to Scotland. All that hairy-scary nonsense, with Drac
is Back, and the Bogeyman's Revenge...... The Nightmare on Cliche Street, as
one observer described the coverage of his appointment in July.
Wrong, because Michael Forsyth II, the Sequel, never lived up to its
flesh-eating publicity. Wrong, anyway, to borrow from the blood-curdling
lexicon of horror films.
From those opening moments, when he sprang like John Travolta into the news
conference at St Andrews House, we should have known. The soft shoe shuffle for
Scottish local authorities, a smouldering tango with the scion of Scotland's
trade union movement, Campbell Christie: yes, we should have been brave enough
to admit it.
This is Michael Forsyth as you have never seen him before. The man has had a
makeover. Ditched his old demonic image as Drac for a nimble new Travolta
routine. He's been doing a vigorous lambada, dancing circles round some of his
opponents, who are left looking like old twits doing a sad, sedate twist.
It has been an astonishing performance in wrong-footing his critics. But then
the man has rewritten the script. And the zealous Thatcherite novice, who as
Scottish Tory Party chairman so alienated huge sections of his own party by
bringing in a chorus of pimply youthful aides with mobile phones and no
political acumen that he almost split the Scottish party asunder, has entirely
recast himself.
If he comes a cropper, it won't be for want of polishing up his political
routine. Hoofing it around Scotland making conciliatory noises, nurses are
nice, teachers are super: sashaying along to the haunts of his old adversaries,
those Scottish Tories who helped his political trajectory take a swift
southernly direction, making soothing noises about the union.
His latest bit of nifty footwork is an attempt to out-perform the carefully
worked out steps of the Scottish Constitutional Convention towards a Scottish
parliament.
Today he will take the wraps off his plans to make the Union dance to a new
tune. He is expected to tell Parliament he wants to revive the old Scottish
Economic Council, give the Scottish Grand Committee greater focus, and devolve
back to local councils many of the freedoms and responsibilities sucked into
the centrist corridors of Tory power. The performance has been well-rehearsed.
It is his speech to local authorities, timed for tomorrow to coincide with the
unveiling of details of the Constitutional Convention's final cut, that will
disclose just how nimble he can be in bolstering the Unionist argument.
A surprise or three is expected: it is hardly in his nature to fail to conjure
up an image grabbing headline.
So far, Mr Forsyth's come-back to the Scottish political stage after three
years banishment has involved a lot of adroit footwork. Can he keep it up?
Let's step back and review the performance so far.
When John Major appointed Forsyth Scottish Secretary in July, it took him by
surprise, according to some political observers. After his enforced move south,
he impressed as a junior minister in two departments, but was said to believe
his star was in decline.
That he was elevated came as no great surprise in Scotland: in the depleted
Tory ranks who else was there to replace the languidly, urbane Ian Lang on his
promotion to Trade and Industry?
Forsyth told Peter Jones, the Economist's Scottish political commentator, it
was a chance he never believed he would get. He intended to make the most of it.
The wounds within Tory ranks had not quite healed. His free-market, Thatcherite
enthusiasms had not diminished: far from it. He remains an unreconstructed
right-winger, as he freely admits. But he had to take the deeply-suspicious
Scottish Conservative Party with him.
When he arrived at the Scottish Office, this time in the driving seat instead
of strapped into the back, he came as a reinvigorated force but with a
remarkably more conciliatory tone.
On one view, he has accepted he exists in a changed political landscape. No
longer the pampered political toy-boy of the Thatcher years, his means must to
be tailored to suit the terrain. By the same view, he learned from his previous
incarnation that in order to reach the end you seek, you have to take people
with you. He has, in other words, polished up his political skills, but with
the same end in view.
Those who have watched his shrewd adoption of a conciliatory tone, instead of
the hectoring, dogmatic voice of the right-wing ideologue, point out he does
indeed appear to be a man rejuvenated. He has thrown his restless intelligence
and dynamism into the role.
In the past, he was held in check because he was simply a minister. A junior
minister can only do what a Secretary of State allows him to do. Now he is the
master, albeit of a small country. His raw energy has shaken up civil servants.
There is resentment that he appears to want 100 impossible tasks performed
before breakfast and that he has brought in his own personal, political aides.
He has, though, shown either cunning or considerable shrewdness, depending on
whom you listen to, in tiptoeing round Scottish political sensibilities. For
instance, he has said he wants to keep increases in water rates down to 6%. But
he can easily recoup the money lost through forcing local authorities to raise
the rates. He knows people will blame the councils not the Government. Nor has
he foisted privatisation in forestry or water.
In one of his first interviews as Scottish Secretary, Mr Forsyth told The
Herald he intended to approach his new job in something of the spirit in which
he operated in his own Stirling constituency, representing the interests of the
whole area, not just those who voted for him.
He said, too, he wanted to find common ground with local councils, be a
listening ear. And indeed his conciliatory tone at the first meeting with the
Convention of Scottish Local Authorities surprised, even confused, many who
were there.
The mutual back-slapping didn't last long. By autumn, Forsyth, along with his
local government minister George Kynoch launched a series of jointly ferocious
attacks on some of the new unitary authorities, accusing them of paying
themselves too many allowances, employing too many staff, and creating ``jobs
for the boys''.
The strain at the seams of the jolly new relationship was beginning to show.
Whether he can mend broken fences by announcing powers to be returned to local
councils on Thursday remains to be seen.
According to one insider, having been given a second chance in Scotland Forsyth
has grabbed it with both hands. He knows he has around 15 months to go until
the General Election, so he has decided to fling everything he has into it. If
the Tories lose, and he with them, he has given it his best shot.
Whatever the outcome, he cannot lose. He is young, just over 40, and looking to
the longer-term, would re-emerge as one of the few right-wingers with Cabinet
experience in some distant Conservative revival, perhaps for an English seat.
Irrespective of whether the Tories win or lose, if he holds up their Scottish
vote, he will have achieved what he set out to do, to secure a Tory base in
Scotland. He has done, as one observer says, what appeared to be impossible in
adapting the tone - if not the ultimate message - of his political ideology.
On his appointment, he said his views, the principles and ideas, remain the
same. The way he planned to go about things had changed: ``I think that I have
probably a greater understanding, having done a number of jobs in Government,
about how to get to your destination. That does not mean that you've forgotten
where you are travelling to.''
So if Michael Forsyth, the consummate politician, is dancing the Last Waltz
towards a General Election, it is to his old tune, played softly. A final
curtain call is some time off yet.
</TEXT>
