<RECORDNO>975143062</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Hodgert tells us that the way forward for Scotland is that we should all
learn to write Scots or Gaelic (Herald Essay, November 25). Aye, and I suppose
national dignity will be fully restored when the White Heather Club returns to
our television screens.
The Saint Andrew's Flag should not remind us, as he suggests, of a crossroads
but of a ford. Athelstane Ford to be precise.
The whole point about a ford is this: you cannae go forward if you're feart to
get your feet wet. The story of our nation's flag and the battle of Athelstane
Ford has a clear, unambiguous message - there is a time when you have to stop
running and turn to fight.
Now if writing in Scots is all the fight Mr Hodgert can muster then fair
enough, contribution gratefully accepted, but I imagine that his essay had
Michael Forsyth sniggering into his breakfast.
Ian Donnelly,
125 Quebec Drive, Westwood,
East Kilbride.
</TEXT>
