<HEADLINE>At a glance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>BUDGET AT A GLANCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143063</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TAX
Basic tax rate cut by 1p to 24p.
20p band extended by #700 to #3900.
Top rate threshold raised by #1200 to #25,500.
Basic personal allowance up #240 to #3765.
Married couples' allowance up by #70 to #1790.
Tax on savings for basic rate taxpayers reduced from 25% to 20%.
Inheritance tax threshold raised from #154,000 to #200,000.
SOCIAL SECURITY
Social security spending to be reduced by #5bn each year by end of century.
Child care allowance in family credit increased from #40 to #60 per week.
Housing benefit restricted for under 25s.
Benefits for asylum-seekers will cease after application rejected.
TOBACCO
Cigarettes up 15p for 20.
Small cigars up 6p.
Pipe tobacco up 8p.
Freeze on rolling tobacco.
DRINKS
Freeze on duty on beer and wine.
Strong cider up 8p a pint from next October.
Spirit duty down 4%, equal to 27p off a bottle of whisky.
MOTORING
Car road tax up #5 to #140.
Petrol and diesel up by 3.5p a litre.
Super unleaded petrol up further 4p a litre from next May.
Exempting all cars and motorcycles over 25 years old from road tax.
Five new privately financed roads to be built with capital value of #500m.
BETTING
Tax on pools betting down 5% from December 3, plus further 1% on May 1.
HEALTH SERVICE
Spending to increase by more than #1bn.
#700m over next three years to come from private sector investment.
#35m deal to modernise two hospitals for South Buckinghamshire NHS Trust.
CRIME
5000 extra police over three years.
10,000 extra close circuit TVs.
BUSINESS
Small firms' rate of corporation tax down to 24% from 25%.
Increase in business rate bills capped at 7.5% for 1996-97.
Increase on small business rates capped to 5%.
Qualifying age for tax relief for business owners selling on retirement reduced
from 55 to 50.
Inheritance tax business property relief 100% for all unquoted shareholdings.
Landfill tax #7 a tonne and #2 a tonne for non-active waste.
SAVINGS
Upper assets limit for those in long term residential care doubled from #8000
to #16,000 and lower assets threshold raised from #3000 to #10,000.
PUBLIC SPENDING
Share of national income taken by state in spending must be reduced to below
40%.
Government running costs to be #860m lower in three years' time.
Total public spending to be 42% of national income this year.
ECONOMY
Growth forecast of 2.75% this year and 3% next year.
Inflation on course to meet 2.5% target.
Public borrowing to be #29bn in 1995-96, #7bn less than 1994-95.
HOUSING
Housing Corporation Loan Board to be         privatised.
Mortgage interest relief unchanged at 15% on #30,000.
SHARES
New tax relief enabling companies to grant share options to employees up to a
limit of #20,000.
SCHOOLS
#878m extra for schools of which #770m channelled through local authorities.
PRISONS
#50m privately funded project to add two new prison building contracts at
Bridgend, South Wales and Fazakerley,     Merseyside.
</TEXT>
