<HEADLINE>Lawyer collapses after sentencing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143067</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LAWYER collapsed in the dock as he was jailed for a year for embezzlement at
Glasgow Sheriff Court yesterday.
William Templeton, 39, crashed to the floor after he was found guilty of
embezzling #11,605.
His wife, who was in court for his sentencing, ran to his aid.
Templeton, of Heath Avenue, Lenzie, near Glasgow, had admitted at an earlier
hearing taking the money from 10 clients' accounts at the city law firm where
he was a partner in 1990.
Defence solicitor-advocate Paul Burns said that Templeton had suffered stress
at the time of the offence.
Mr Burns added that Templeton's daughter had been ill, his wife pregnant, and
that he had money worries.
He said that Templeton had been subject to stress in his legal practice.
Mr Burns told the court: ``A remarkable log was kept by one of the partners of
the obsessive atmosphere in the office, and one wonders if there was any legal
work done at times.
``Templeton was working a 12-hour day and being phoned at home by two partners
who were clearly at war with each other.
``He was like a child in the middle of a divorce.''
Templeton was only paid the ``wages of a typist'' and was forced to carry out
``homers'' doing joinery work and started a toy soldier business which failed,
Mr Burns said.
As he became ill Templeton suffered irrational fears and plan- ned building a
nuclear shelter in the back garden of his home.
The lawyers' guarantee fund had made good the money embezzled from the 10
clients, some of them elderly, but the partners of the law firm, McDowall and
Kerr, of West George Street, Glasgow, were left out of pocket.
Depute-fiscal Ian Bradley told the court that Templeton, who has been struck
off as a practising solicitor, had committed a ``gross breach of trust'' when
the took the money.
As Sheriff Brian Lockhart jailed him Templeton collapsed, vanishing from view
in the dock.
His schoolteacher wife later accompanied him in an ambulance to Glasgow's Royal
Infirmary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
