<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Menem praises princess</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143068</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales would make an ``excellent roving ambassador'', Argentine
president Carlos Menem said yesterday, as he declared that her visit to his
country had helped mend relations with Britain.
The result of the princess's first foreign foray since her declaration in her
Panorama interview that she wanted an ambassadorial role was ``exceptional,
absolutely positive''.
``She managed to make her way to the heart of the people of Argentina,'' he
said, adding that she ``could be an excellent roving ambassador of goodwill,
representing the UK in the rest of the world''.
The president told the BBC Radio 4 programme Today that he sympathised with the
princess over all the media pressure she faced.
The visit passed without any major demonstration over sovereignty of the
Falklands but Mr Menem reiterated Argentina's claim to the islands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leader wants timely debate</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143069</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Council leader Peter Peacock is calling on community groups in the
area to declare their views on the renewed campaign to bring British time into
line with Europe.
Councillor Peacock believes there is a need for widespread debate on the
proposed scrapping of Greenwich Mean Time, which would mean clocks staying at
British Summer Time in winter and moving forward another hour in summer.
Victim named
POLICE yesterday named the victim of a road accident as Mr Walter Beattie, 42,
of Braeside Road, Ballinluig, Perthshire, who had just alighted from a bus in
the village when he was struck by a car. Mr Beattie died from multiple injuries
in hospital.
Hope for jobs
UP to 50 new jobs are expected to be created in Perth, hopefully before
Christmas. The district council is negotiating with an as-yet unnamed company
over land and a building on the town's Inveralmond industrial estate.
Action delayed
INDUSTRIAL action by thousands of workers at car manufacturer Vauxhall has been
postponed for a week because of a ``technicality'', unions announced yesterday.
Production workers at the company's plants in Luton and Ellesmere Port were due
to start an overtime ban and a two-hour a week ``strike'' today in protest at a
3.5% pay offer.
Appeal response
MORE than 150 callers have responded to a police appeal for help concerning
nine girls and young women untraced since visiting 25 Cromwell Street,
Gloucester, the home of Frederick and Rosemary West, where the bodies of nine
young women were discovered. Rosemary West was jailed for life last week after
being found guilty of murder.
Death toll
SHETLAND is Britain's fatal accident blackspot, a survey revealed yesterday. It
had 21.74 deaths per 100,000, compared with the national average of just 6.7.
</TEXT>
