<DOCNO>GH951129-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The best offer made so far</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143070</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN Meek (We can't have our oatcake and eat it, November 23) is clearly a
humorous and warm-hearted man. He is also a good sports journalist and gets
into international rugby matches at Murrayfield for nothing. So he must have
heard, quite a few times by now, the spectators fervently singing that bit
about being ``a nation again''.
They mean it too, as every indicator has shown for years now. So I find it
genuinely sad that Brian Meek should rubbish the best offer so far made to give
the Scottish people their wish - a Scottish parliament.
I speak for no political party and I would accept that there are flaws and
weaknesses in the proposed parliament, but it's a start and the Scottish people
will no doubt improve it with the passage of time.
Can Mr Meek not see that he is playing the role of King Canute? Scottish
political history since the Second World War shows the irresistible rise of the
Scottish people's will to nationhood, despite many setbacks. Had people like Mr
Meek and Allan Massie, for example, understood this we might have had a
parliament ere now.
The deep-lying social magma that has fuelled this long drive to the resumption
of nationhood is the frustrated desire to give again to the world the fruits of
Scotland's innovative genius.
Our ancestors brought civilisation to Europe in the Dark Ages; the Reformation
and the Scottish Enlightenment are great landmarks in European history; the
Industrial Revolution was born in the work of James Watt and Adam Smith; and
the whole modern electronic miracle stems from the work of James Clerk Maxwell,
as Einstein recognised.
To do things like that again Scotland needs, and means, to be free. Brian Meek
should get on board.
Andrew Lockhart Walker,
7 Lovers' Loan, Dollar.
</TEXT>
