<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents' anger at opt-out petition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143071</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARENTS of children at an Ayrshire primary school are to seek legal advice over
an opting-out petition which they claim they were duped into signing.
They say a small group misled them into signing the petition, which has
triggered a ballot on quitting the state system.
The claim came at the meeting in Gateside village hall last night after a
number of speakers had spoken out against the opting-out proposal.
There was anger as several parents declared they had never intended that opting
out should be put to a ballot and that they only wanted information about the
possibilities.
One parent, Mrs Elizabeth Steel, said: ``This has been a waste of time and
completely unnecessary. Why did we have to go through all this ridiculous carry
on just to get some information.''
The controversy began earlier this month when it was disclosed that a
49-signature petition had been received by the school board. It left the board
no choice but to initiate procedures for a ballot to be set up for completion
at the end of January.
However, as word of the ballot spread, parents told the school board it was
never their intention, and that they wanted their signatures withdrawn.
Mr Alistair Wilson, vice-chairman of the school board, warned against opting
out and added: ``If it went ahead, Gateside would wither and die. There is an
avalanche waiting round the corner to sweep this wonderful school away. And it
would be all for a bit of political dogma.
``The whole opting out process is dangerous nonsense and must be rejected.''
Mr David Bates, however, presented a strong argument for opting out. He said it
would save the school from closure and that it would prosper, as many schools
in England have done under grant-aided support.
Mr John Travers, director of education at the new North Ayrshire Council, told
the meeting it had never been the council's intention to close Gateside and he
gave a five-year pledge on the future of the 67-pupil primary school.
He said: ``There appears to have been an attempt to convince parents that
opting out is necessary to safeguard Gateside primary from the threat of
closure.
``Let me assure you that North Ayrshire Council has no intention of proposing
such a closure and is aware of the central role played by the primary school.''
Support for the parents came from Cunninghame North MP Brian Wilson, who is to
ask Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth today to halt the ballot procedure.
Mr Wilson said: ``For whatever reason, political or otherwise, many parents
appear to have been duped into believing that all they were doing was seeking
advice on opting out and protecting their school.
``Instead, a series of events which they did not want was launched and now it
must be stopped. I will be urging Michael Forsyth to end this fiasco before it
causes any further problems for the pupils, teachers or parents of this fine
village school.''
Head teacher Agnes McGuigan said: ``The staff and pupils have been greatly
upset by the events of recent weeks. We are anxious that it can now be brought
to a halt and that we can get on with what we are here to do - teaching the
children of the area.''
The chairperson of the school board, Mrs Helen Smith, will be seeking counsel's
advice on how the petition can be withdrawn and the opting out ballot stopped.
She said: ``We do not want the uncertainty to continue. However, if the ballot
has to go ahead, I am confident the outcome will be an overwhelming rejection
of opting out for Gateside.''
</TEXT>
