<HEADLINE>Deal struck for Irish peace plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Cooney</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143072</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The peace process was rescued last night when John Bruton flew to London to
meet John Major. John Cooney reports on the background
THE launching late last night of a twin-track policy to advance the peace
process in Northern     Ireland was inspired by a manic-like determination by
Taoiseach John Bruton to secure a deal with John Major ahead of President Bill
Clinton's visit to Britain and Ireland.
The 48-year-old Irish Premier's diplomacy centres on the finding of a formula
to circumvent London's demands that the IRA should hand over some of its arms
and ammunition as a precondition for Sinn Fein's admission to all-party
political talks.
The deal involves a tight schedule. It aims to achieve all-party talks by
mid-February, with the commission reporting on ways of decommissioning arms by
mid-January.
After two phone calls the decision was taken by Bruton to travel to London for
a joint presentation of the deal.
An Irish Government spokesman indicated that the breakthrough hinges on the
terms of reference to be given by the two governments to an international
commission that would examine the arms decommissioning issue.
The Irish Government has argued that all the elements involved in
decommissioning of weaponry should come under the remit of the commission,
including the British demand that some weapons must be handed over by the IRA
before Sinn Fein can take part in round-table talks.
Dublin is also trying to persuade Britain to keep an open mind on the
commission's work, especially its efforts to determine other ways in which
British wishes can be met.
However, in view of Major's sensitivities, the Irish are prepared to accept
Britain need not make a prior commitment on this alternative approach. The
Irish expectations are based on Britain making concessions on the arms issue -
on the basis of a fudge.
The latest burst of diplomatic activity came after London and Dublin appeared
to be at loggerheads. Bruton's frantic telephone diplomacy with Major had taken
place as pessimism grew of an IRA return to hostilities in the early New Year
if Dublin and London fail to break the deadlock over the arms issue.
Sources close to Bruton insist he is driven by a mission not to go down in the
history books as the man who failed to consolidate the 15-month IRA ceasefire
which he inherited from his predecessor, Albert Reynolds.
Question marks have hung over Bruton's handling of the peace process following
his pull-out from a scheduled summit with John Major in September after Sinn
Fein leaders warned him the IRA would not give up a single gun.
Suspect in Sinn Fein eyes of being too conciliatory to Ulster Unionists - he is
sneeringly referred to as ``John Unionist'' - Bruton lost the confidence of
Unionists who regarded his summit postponement as capituation to Sinn Fein.
Increasingly, Dublin has looked to Washington in the hope that President
Clinton would put pressure on London to show flexibility.
Reports of progress carried yesterday by Irish newspapers emphasised the
involvement of two senior Clinton aides, Anthony Lake, national security
adviser, and Nancy Soderberg, the President's Northern Ireland adviser.
The overnight optimism came after Britain and Ireland appeared to be engaged in
a war of words about who was to blame for the loss of momentum in the stalled
peace process.
In a widely quoted article in the Irish Independent, the commentator and
author, Tim Pat Coogan, claimed Britain was using the decommissioning argument
to prevent progress in the same way as the Orange Card had been used last
century by the Conservatives to frustrate the introduction of Home Rule in
Ireland.
While the Bruton/Major deal has not been directly brokered by President
Clinton, undoubtedly it will have his imprint on the fine text.
</TEXT>
