<HEADLINE>Petrol policies cause anger</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE, Environment Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143073</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORISTS are the Budget's biggest victims, with 19p extra on a gallon of
petrol and Scotland's rural drivers paying even more, the AA said last night.
Highlands and Islands Enterprise added to the warnings about how rural
communities would be affected, claiming that Budget tax cuts for small
businesses in the North of Scotland could be offset by increases in fuel prices.
While reductions in tax for small businesses, which comprise 90% of companies
in the area, were welcome, increased duties on petrol and diesel were likely to
push up transport costs.
HIE's senior economist, Tracey Slaven, said: ``The decision to cap increases in
business rates, and to reduce corporation tax for small businesses, will
undoubtedly help the majority of companies in the Highlands and Islands area.
We look forward to seeing the details of the Chancellor's plans.
``However, many firms depend on long-distance road transport for importing raw
materials and exporting finished goods, while the area's #500m-a-year tourism
industry relies heavily on car-borne visitors. The increase on diesel and
petrol of 3.5p per litre could do much to strip businesses of the other
benefits announced, as fuel costs are already disproportionately higher in our
area.''
The Scottish Licensed Trade Association said: ``We are appalled at the savage
increase in the cost of petrol and diesel. This really does affect Scotland and
can have a devastating result on tourism, and to residents and visitors in our
more rural areas.''
The Chancellor's increases in motoring costs are likely to cost the motorist
who does about 8000 miles a year an additional #55 per annum. A sales
representative doing 50,000 miles will have to find an extra #265.
Mr Neil Greig, the AA's road and environment officer in Scotland, said: ``We
have seen petrol duty rise by more than a third in the last three years. This
has a huge effect on rural Scotland, because motorists do not benefit from the
competition between petrol retailers in the Central Belt - and with lack of
public transport many have no alternative but to use their cars.''
Environmentalists claimed the Chancellor's measures - car road tax up #5 to
#140; petrol and diesel up 3.5p a litre; super unleaded petrol up a further 4p
a litre from next May; and all cars and motorcycles over 25 years old exempted
from road tax - lacked imagination and would do little if anything to help
transport related environmental problems.
Mr Greig said on behalf of the AA in Scotland: ``These measures will make no
difference to the environment. Our surveys have shown that people will continue
to drive, no matter how much petrol costs. We were looking for incentives to
use smaller cars.''
He added that the higher duty on super unleaded petrol, reflecting concerns
about benzine, would have little effect as most new vehicles used normal
unleaded fuel.
Dr Richard Dixon, head of research for Friends of the Earth Scotland, said:
``We welcome the increased duty on super unleaded petrol, but it is not enough.
It should have been banned straight away. Even motoring organisations say there
is no real benefit in using it.''
He said the increase in duty was giving the right message to the motorist, but
it was not being done in the right way.
``While the cost in motoring has to be increased to reflect the costs to
society, rural populations do not have any buses or trains. Therefore we do not
think this is the right way to change transport policy,'' he said.
He added that, while it was argued that cars and motorcycles over 25 years old
had to be well maintained or they simply would not go, nevertheless such
vehicles were fuel inefficient and heavy polluters.
``We would not be calling for them to be banned from the road, but exempting
them from road tax does encourage people to operate vehicles that may be more
polluting than modern vehicles,'' he said.
Despite the rises, Mr Clarke said petrol prices in the UK ``should remain lower
than in any major European country''.
However, Mr Adam Wurf, speaking on behalf of the Freight Transport Association,
said that Britain had the highest fuel duty and VAT in Europe.
He added that the 3.5p per litre rise in diesel would add #400m to the cost of
UK industry, and would add #1400 per annum to the fuel bill of heavy goods
vehicles. However, he welcomed the Chancellor's decision to freeze the tax disc
rate for lorries for the sixth successive year.
This recognised the direct contribution already being made by the freight
industry to reducing damage to the environment, particularly in the area of
diesel technology. The freight industry was also far closer to using
alternative-powered vehicles than the car industry, he added.
Both Tesco and Sainsbury's said they would freeze their petrol prices until
next Monday. Tesco unleaded is currently 223p a gallon (49.08p a litre) while
Sainsbury's is 226.8p a gallon (49.9p a litre).
The increase in fuel duty was described as ``a typically knee-jerk reaction''
by the Road Haulage Association.
``It seems every time the Government runs out of ideas they tax road
transport,'' said Mr Wylie Cunningham, regional director of the Road Haulage
Association.
``Today's increase will put almost #540m on to the annual costs of the road
haulage industry in the UK. That is a price which every factory, every shop,
and every consumer in the country will have to pay.''
</TEXT>
