<HEADLINE>Clarke dilemma.  A prudent penny may prove too little</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DESPITE Mr Kenneth Clarke's efforts yesterday, the Tories are facing the stark
reality of the need for another Budget next year to enhance their chances in
the coming General Election.
The Chancellor took a cautious step towards political recovery but the dramatic
stride to avoid General Election defeat was missing.
The average family should be #9 a week better off next year: this is only
halfway towards wiping out its losses since Mr Major's 1992 victory.
Labour leader Tony Blair at once spotted this political weakness in the
Chancellor's Budget measures as the Tory Commons majority falls and Mr Major's
reliance on the Ulster Unionists to keep him in power for another year
increases.
Mr Clarke called his Budget ``prudent'' and he expects it to find favour
amongst some wavering Tory voters and the City. He hopes interest rates can be
cut again but Government borrowing is still standing at #22bn. He could do
nothing ``affordable'' to help the crucial housing market.
Mr Blair declared: ``This is not a Budget - it's a wish list. It is long into
the future, long after they've gone of course.'' The Chancellor, he said, was
giving with one hand and taking away with another.
Public spending has been cut by #3250m next year, equivalent to the amount that
is to be cut in taxes. Right-wing Tories wanted much bigger cuts in spending
and taxation but the majority at the Commons believed the Chancellor had found
the correct balance in the circumstances.
All departments have been obliged to make savings to provide impressive
increases in priority spending. The NHS is to get another #1300m. Schools will
benefit by #878m extra. Police forces get another #20m plus 5000 officers and
10,000 closed-circuit TV cameras.
The Chancellor declared: ``We are going to leave our children a welfare state
that works and one that we can afford.''
Social security looks like taking the biggest cuts in housing benefit and
single parent allowances. Mr Clarke predicted that the social security budget
of #97bn would be reduced by #5000m each year to the end of the century.
He is placing great faith in the Government's Private Finance Initiative, which
he hopes will bring #2000m a year of private investment into State ventures
like roads, hospitals, and prisons.
Mr Blair mocked this target because so far the PFI has brought in only around
#500m.
If the scheme works, there will be a bigger switch from state spending and
borrowing into tax reduction.
The Chancellor described what he called three steps towards his target of a 20p
basic rate. Yesterday, he cut it by 1p to 24p, widened the existing 20p band by
#700 to #3700, and cut taxation on savings income to 20p in the #. He also
raised personal allowances and indexed to inflation married couples allowance
and age related income limits.
He reduced the tax rates of 18 million people. A quarter of all taxpayers will
be on the 20% rate and nearly a quarter of a million are taken out of income
tax altogether.
Employers also benefit with a #500m cut in national insurance contributions;
small businesses will pay 1p less (24p) in corporation tax and they are to get
more help on their rates bills.
The Chancellor has also targeted family savings for help with the inheritance
tax threshold increased by #50,000 to #200,000.
The elderly get increased assistance with the cost of long-term care. Mortgage
protection and long-term insurance benefits are to be exempt from tax.
To help pay for all this, customs duties are increased on strong cider,
cigarettes, petrol and diesel, and road tax. Scotch whisky has about 27p cut
from a bottle and he has helped the pools, horse and dog racing by cuts in the
betting levy. Duty on lorries remains the same.
All this made the Tory back benchers feel a little better but they were still
cautious about their General Election chances if the Government does not get
the chance to produce another Budget next autumn.
Some right wingers felt that the Chancellor should have made at least a 2p cut
in the standard rate of tax to have a political effect. Others felt he was
constrained by the Government's borrowing figures, which are still #10bn more
than they were hoping for.
The Budget pleased Essex MP Gerry Hayes, with only a 3000 majority. He said:
``The theme of this Budget is `who cares wins' and I think the Chancellor has
done a lot of good things for my constituents who have been wavering in their
support.''
Ministers believe that the Budget will give them no immediate turn around in
the opinion polls until next spring. One said: ``Public borrowing is on a
downward path to sustain the economic recovery. People are going to keep more
of what they earn and save, and a whole lot more is going to be spent on the
public services that people care about.''
Business leaders welcomed Mr Clarke's decision not to bow to political pressure
for swingeing tax cuts.
Mr Adair Turner, director-general of the CBI, said Mr Clarke had produced a
Budget that stuck to a prudent economic line.
``Overall, caution won the day and we should welcome that,'' Mr Turner told the
annual dinner of the Building Employers' Confederation in London.
However, Mr John Prescott, deputy leader of the Labour Party said: ``The
Government are simply incapable of telling the truth about their own tax plans.
Senior Ministers keep deliberately giving the impression that as a result of
this Budget the typical family will be #9 a week better off.
``That is rubbish and the Tories know it. The tax changes will make a
difference of less than #4 a week. The rest comes from rises in earnings which
have nothing to do with the Budget. And this still means that the typical
family will be #670 a year worse off than they were in 1992, because of Tory
tax increases.
``That is the truth about this Government's tax policies.''
This Budget was a fiscal package for survival but Mr Major could lose his
majority through defections and by-elections. Mr Blair is clearly out to get
him before he can produce an election-winning Budget.
Calum MacDonald writes: The Chancellor's Budget tipple was the Speyside malt,
Glenfarclas.
His choice echoed that of a predecessor, Mr Norman Lamont, who also sipped the
malt while delivering a Budget speech.
Distillery production manager, Mr John Miller, welcomed the tax cut, but added:
``We would like a bit more to be honest. But every little helps.
``I knew that Mr Clarke drank it but I wasn't aware that Mr Lamont did too.''
Mr Miller said the distillery, which lies between Elgin and Grantown-on-Spey,
employs about 20 people.
Mr Clarke visited the distillery last year.
</TEXT>
