<HEADLINE>Recipe for love, just add sauce</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lorn Macintyre</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As a nation of shopkeepers, the British will try to sell anything. Lorn
Macintyre has a lingering dinner with the successful shopkeeper who hopes to
put a bit of naughtiness into the nation's bedrooms
THIS middle-aged interviewer may seem to be on an enviable assignment, dining
with a petite, attractive lady in a hotel on Edinburgh's Princes Street on an
atmospheric evening where the waiters move about like ghosts. Before the entree
arrives she tells me that she would love to open a shop on Princes Street. The
name above the door would be Ann Summers, and beyond the lingerie display sex
aids would be on sale.
I am having a tte-a-tte with Jacqueline Gold. When I agreed to interview her
about her autobiography Good Vibrations (Pavilion, #14.99) I did not know her
name, or that of Ann Summers. It is never too late to learn, and I tell her
that I enjoyed her candid story.
But how am I going to put the questions? I needn't worry: Jacqueline is a good
talker with no inhibitions about the achievements of the dynastic Golds.
After the Second World War her grandparents bought up the books and magazines
used as ballast in container ships from America.
Her father (an East End bricklayer) and uncle created a lucrative publishing
company of top shelf girlie magazines, and acquired Britain's first sex
supermarket in 1971, building up a successful chain of a dozen sex shops based
on the Ann Summers name.
As a teenager Jacqueline started off creating word puzzles for cash, and
selling bric-a-brac on a Kent market stall. ``I went into the family business
in 1979 when I was 19. Initially I had no intention of staying because it was a
very male oriented business. I attended a Tupperware-style party in Essex by
accident.
``Afterwards the women who were there said to me: why doesn't Ann Summers do
parties? Women want to buy sexy underwear and sex aids, but we're too
embarrassed to go into a sex shop. I had also been in a sex shop and could
totally relate to what they were saying.''
Ann Summers Party Plan, Jacqueline's clever scheme for selling to women at
home, started in 1981. ``When women initially come to our parties, they're not
necessarily coming to buy sex aids. They're coming out of curiosity. They'll
buy the underwear and have a good laugh.
``They'll come to another party a few months later, and perhaps get a little
bit more adventurous. They might buy a small vibrator. As time goes on they
seem to become more and more experimental. We now sell 300,000 vibrators a year
to women.''
I take advantage of a rise in conversation level at a nearby table to put a
male-oriented question. Why do women need sex aids? Jacqueline preserves eye
contact. ``A few people may assume that it's because the relationship is
failing. I don't think it's that at all. In the main the majority of women who
buy these aids are already in relationships. Women are much more comfortable
than they used to be about talking to their partners about what they want from
a relationship.
``It's the fact that they are experimenting; it's very much a sharing
experience. They're being more adventurous than perhaps they used to be.''
But surely men get angry if they discover that their wives and partners have
bought such aids? ``In the main men are excited when they learn that their wife
or partner is going to a Party Plan. I hear stories all the time of men saying:
`here darling, here's an open cheque book'. They'll even look through the
catalogue beforehand together and choose what she's going to get.''
I am grateful for the arrival of the starter, but Jacqueline is not embarrassed
by the turn our conversation is taking. ``I know exactly what you're saying
about some men getting angry. When we opened our Southampton shop last year I
heard an argument going on outside. The wife was saying: `Oh, it's Ann Summers;
look after the pram while I go in'. He frog-marched her down the road, saying:
`It's the real thing or nothing at all'.''
Jacqueline recruited more than 1000 sales women in the first year, and, a
decade later, 7500 sales women organise parties for two million women, bringing
a gross annual turnover of around #40 million.
There are also the Ann Summers shops. Do men go into them, perhaps looking for
gifts for loved ones? ``I think a man would feel embarrassed. If you go into a
shop and look at the body language, there are more men who look uncomfortable
than there are women. That's because with women getting together to talk about
sexual issues, it's much more light-hearted.''
The main course has arrived under shining covers, but I have to ask her if
being in the sex industry causes her shame. ``You apply the same business
principles as you would if you were in catering or manufacturing. This is one
reason I wrote my book. I wanted the company to become much more professional
and improve its image. We have our own customer care department, our own
quality care department. It's just like any other business.''
There are now eight Ann Summers shops, including the three opened this year.
But on this November night in Edinburgh, as she toys with her steak after the
long promotional day, she tells me: ``I would love to have a shop up here but
it's finding the right site.''
I am thinking: when I write in The Herald of the possibility of Ann Summers
shops on Princes Street or on Glasgow's Sauchiehall Street, there will be
appalled letters. If the douce citizens of the capital get steamed up over
saunas, how are they going to react to vibrators on the pride and joy of
Princes Street?
Jacqueline is honest but determined: ``We get opposition from time to time. You
might get the odd councillor who isn't happy, but as yet that hasn't stopped us
from opening any shops. The more shops we successfully open, the more people
will get to realise that there is nothing to worry about.
``People have this idea of Ann Summers. I remember getting a taxi to our head
office in Surrey a few years ago. The driver said: `You're not going in there,
are you?' I said: `Why, what's the problem?' He said: `You know what goes on in
there'. I always say to people: please go along to one of the shops; please go
to a party; please look in the catalogue.''
One day Jacqueline Gold will become chairwoman of her family's #150 million
empire. She is divorced, has no children, and, from what I can see in the
discreetly lit dining-room, does not overindulge in either wine or food. What
drives her? ``Throughout my career my motivation has changed. When I was very
young it was very much money. I wanted to be financially independent. Now it's
achievement and success; the success of products I'm involved in, and also
seeing the success of other people around me involved in the business.''
Aren't the mid-thirties too tender an age to write one's autobiography? ``If
I'm honest, the real reason I wrote it was the preconceived ideas and
prejudices. I've been portrayed as a sex queen.
``I laugh a lot of it off now. I don't see myself like that. Also, there are
lots of funny stories in the book, like the talking vibrator.''
Does it speak English, I ask? ``Its vocabulary isn't particularly advanced;
it's lots of oohs and aahs.''
As I savour my main course Jacqueline has more stories. ``I was talking to a
chap who told me he had bought his girlfriend a vibrator. They call it Colin.
He says: `We can talk about Colin in public and nobody knows who we're talking
about. We'll often say: we must tell Colin about that'.''
No, she couldn't retire and live on her fortune because she has too much still
to do for Ann Summers. Is she proving herself to her father? ``I've already
proved myself.'' So what is the next strategy?
``I'm already in Germany, Denmark and Holland, so expanding further into Europe
is on the cards. I suppose what excites me most are the States. I went over
there last year and met with a couple of other direct selling companies. The
potential over there is huge because we won't have the language problem over
there that we have in the other countries. I get a buzz from the business being
successful and trying new things.''
Has Ann Summers in the guise of Jacqueline Gold helped to liberate the British
people sexually, I ask after a superb meal, and an altogether enlightening
evening? ``I don't know if that's quite the right expression. I certainly think
that Ann Summers has contributed greatly to giving women the opportunity to buy
and to take control of what they want, rather than what their partners want. We
all know, don't we, that what men think is sexy, and what women think is sexy,
are different.''
I have no further questions.
</TEXT>
