<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The four weeks of November stalemate that almost ended Northern Ireland peace moves.  A rocky road to all-party talks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE meeting last night between Mr John Major and Irish Premier John Bruton was
a last-ditch effort to restart the stalled Anglo-Irish peace talks before
President Clinton arrives in London for a three-day visit.
The key issue behind the stalemate has been the British Government's insistence
on the IRA beginning to decommission weapons.
November 3: Northern Ireland Minister Michael Ancram rejects demands for
all-party talks from Sinn Fein and says decommissioning must come before the
party can join peace talks.
November 8: Mr John Hume, leader of the SDLP, urges Mr Major to respond to
proposals for a summit by November 30. Unionists say they will not be forced
into talks ahead of IRA disarmament. Mr Gerry Adams of Sinn Fein demands that
preconditions over arms should be dropped.
November 10: Leaders of Republican Sinn Fein, the hard-line breakaway group,
denies it is behind a 1000lb bomb found near the Irish border. They say the
ceasefire is a betrayal which would fail.
November 11: A speech by Mr Bruton to the Meath Association of London causes
``anger and dismay'' when he calls for talks without the IRA giving up its
weapons. Government spokesmen say: ``This is an extraordinary speech, at an
extraordinary time, the eve of Remembrance Sunday and delivered in Britain
through a megaphone.''
November 13: It is announced that Mr Major and Mr Bruton will speak on the
telephone in a bid to heal the rift.
November 14: The White House considers whether to cancel President Clinton's
visit. Mr Clinton says he will not go to Belfast ``just to turn on the
Christmas tree lights''.
November 17: New proposals for talks allowing Sinn Fein to take part are
revealed in London. They include an early target date for discussions to begin
and acknowledgement that Sinn Fein could raise as evidence to a disarmament
commission its views on the British Army and RUC. The need for decommissioning
would not be part of the commission's remit.
November 19: Mr Martin McGuinness of Sinn Fein says on radio there is ``no
possibility'' of any IRA weapons being handed over before Sinn Fein is admitted
to talks.
November 18: Mr Major offers new deal leading to speculation that he and Mr
Bruton will meet to set up an international commission on IRA weapons and a New
Year date for all-party talks.
November 20: Mr David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists, rules out talks
with Sinn Fein, saying Mr McGuinness and Mr Adams ``not fit'' to sit at the
negotiating table.
November 21: Phone call diplomacy between London and Dublin fails to bring a
deal to put the process back on track.
November 24: The IRA tells its members to prepare for a ``return to war'' if
London and Dublin fail to break the deadlock.
November 26: Efforts to arrange a summit are abandoned amid accusations that
Dublin is advocating a ``Sinn Fein prospectus''.
</TEXT>
