<HEADLINE>Royal Mail test for Tony Blair</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143078</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE spontaneous strike action taken by postal workers across Scotland last week
was an outburst of underlying anger at the manner in which management has
undertaken the task of rationalisation over the last five years.
In Royal Mail's rationalisation programme we can see in microcosm the vast
changes in working practices our society has undergone since the early eighties.
These changes and the underlying tensions they have created are one of the
major challenges facing Tony Blair's industrial policy makers, if he wins the
next election.
The tiny Edinburgh office at Portobello, the strike's epicentre from where the
shockwaves spread out across the country, is representative of the situation
throughout Royal Mail. The trend has been towards casualisation, increased use
of part-time staff, and heavier workloads, changes implemented with glee by
over-zealous and in many cases over-young management.
At Portobello out of 28 full-time positions four second deliveries have been
rationalised, to use Royal Mail terminology, or to speak more plainly four
full-time jobs have been cut.
Hamilton is currently undertaking official strike action against similar cuts.
Every delivery office across the land has been visited by this attack on
full-time jobs which explains the swiftness of the secondary action and the
deep anger of the strikers.
Alex Gibb has justified Royal Mail management's attack on full-time jobs by
stating: ``Almost 90% of the mail is now available to go in the first delivery
whereas previously it was 60%. The impact on second delivery is that we have
less mail. We have no intention of getting rid of the second delivery but it is
the number of people available to make that second delivery.''
Increased automation and more efficient utilisation of transport have made this
possible. Yet Alex Gibb is speaking the cold, calculating language of the
private sector of the mid-1990s.
Royal Mail as a business made a profit of #1500m last year and from its own
figures 98% of first-class items make it for delivery the following day. Just
how much more efficient can Royal Mail become?
Once again the arguments used during the campaign against privatisation must be
reiterated. The Post Office is not and should not be simply a machine for
making money: it is a public utility set up to provide a service to and jobs
for people in the wider community.
An uneasy peace has broken out with many postal workers returning to work in
order to maintain this high-quality service to the public over the Christmas
period. However, the day of reckoning may only be postponed until the new year.
The Post Office is determined to cut staffing levels on the second delivery
which must logically lead to redundancies.
If Royal Mail persists with this policy it is difficult to imagine how a
protracted industrial dispute can be avoided. Such a dispute has far wider
implications and will be seen by many as an acid test for Tony Blair and New
Labour's commitment to those on a low income.
Support for a wholly legal campaign against job cuts in Royal Mail at a future
date by Tony Blair would go a long way to reassure that other electorate out
there who do not hail from middle England, and whose overriding concern is not
tax cuts.
John McGroarty
(Postman, Gorbals area),
22 Strathclyde Drive,
Rutherglen.
T
</TEXT>
