<HEADLINE>Boy, 12, found guilty of #4600 theft from safe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143079</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 12-YEAR-OLD boy was found guilty yesterday of stealing more than #4600 from a
filling station.
The boy, who was 11 at the time of the offence, has already been referred to
the Reporter to the Children's Panel in Dundee 120 times, Aberdeen Sheriff
Court was told.
The boy, who cannot be named for legal reasons, fidgeted with a packet of
sweets as the sheriff found him guilty.
He had denied stealing #4657 from the Cocket Hat (South) filling station,
Aberdeen, on Friday, January 13, this year. The money was not recovered.
Workers at the garage noticed the cash missing from an office safe shortly
after a member of staff found the boy trying to leave via a fire escape, the
court had heard.
When one of the staff went to the forecourt and asked his mother to go back
inside because of a problem, the boy ran away.
He was being taken to a Children's Panel hearing in Dundee and had tried to run
away earlier that day, the court was told.
The boy told the court yesterday that he was trying to escape from his mother
to avoid going to the hearing, and took his chance when they stopped at the
garage so she could buy cigarettes.
He denied going into the office and taking the cash, or telling staff that he
was looking for a toilet.
The boy added: ``It was Black Friday that day and I thought I was going to get
put away by the panel. That's why I wanted to escape.''
After running from the filling station, he went to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary,
where he took a taxi to the railway station and, he said, boarded a train to
Dundee, avoiding buying a ticket by hiding in a toilet.
In Dundee, the boy said, he had met friends and played on a moped - ridden by a
12-year-old friend - before police caught him later that night.
Sheriff Alexander Pollock found that the boy stole the money and adjourned the
hearing until December 12 so that reports could be prepared.
</TEXT>
