<DOCNO>GH951129-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In danger of drowning before boat gets down slipway</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alex Salmond</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``IT is not difficult,'' remarked P G Wodehouse, ``to tell the difference
between a ray of sunshine and a Scot with a grievance.'' Michael Forsyth may be
reflecting on these wise, if somewhat condescending, words as he prepares for
the constitutional shootout on St Andrew's Day.
One big problem is the extent of Tory pre-match hype, particularly from the
Prime Minister in his interview of last week. Scotland, on the basis of the
words from No 10, should be fastening its seatbelts and preparing for lift off.
If then all oor Michael has to offer is a sooped-up Grand Committee and a
bigger quango to ``advise'' him on matters of state then a lot of people are
going to be more than a little disappointed. His reported remark at a lobby
briefing last week, ``it is the best I can do'', sounds almost plaintive as if
he already expects Scotland to greet his proposals as a damp squib rather than
constitutional fireworks - not so much ``taking stock'' as ``laughing stock''.
This is the difficulty of course with being dragged on to the ground of your
political opponents. Over the past six months Michael has been enjoying himself
poking fun at Labour's devolution scheme, particularly the Aunt Sally 3p
variation in the basic rate of income tax.
This, incidentally, is a proposal so foolish that conspiracy theorists might
believe that the less enthusiastic in the Convention deliberately planted it
there with the precise purpose of giving the Scottish Secretary a target to hit.
Michael has also been relishing the opportunity to raise one bloodcurdling
piece of scaremongering after another. To listen to the Scottish Office team,
constitutional change in Scotland would lead to the end of civilisation as we
know it. What they actually are concerned about is that it would lead to the
end of the Scottish Office team as we know them.
That is the luxury of negative campaigning. It also has limitations.
Scaremongering is the easiest card to play in politics, however it seldom takes
a trick on its own.
Despite saturation coverage for his anti-devolution and independence views,
Tory support remains stubbornly anchored in the depths of Scottish politics.
People may see a lot of Michael. A few might even believe him but next to
nobody is going to like him.
The solution, therefore, is to have something positive to say and that brings
us to the big St Andrew's Day announcement. The difficulty is that as soon as
something is put forward it can be dissected by the other parties. From
negative campaigning on the front foot the Scottish Secretary might soon find
himself campaigning positively on the back foot.
Certainly if he launches the good ship ``real devolution'' on Thursday with the
proposals that have been ventilated thus far it will soon be renamed ``no real
change''. His first problem then is on how to spring a surprise to avoid being
sunk by general public derision before he even gets the boat down the slipway.
Given the extent of the leaks and the weakness of his proposals he is in a
pretty tight corner.
One possibility which presents itself is to offer a constitutional referendum
on the various proposals which are being put forward.
It would certainly be a gambler's move but it is not as unlikely as it first
might seem. It would wrongfoot Labour who adopted a policy of favouring a
multi-option referendum after the last election but do not propose to have one
on their own devolution proposals.
It would bring the Scottish position broadly into line with Northern Ireland
where, since the Downing Street declaration, the Prime Minister has accepted
that any constitutional settlement must be tested by referendum. There is a
downside, however, as there is with most pieces of political chicanery. It
would make an explicit recognition of Scottish sovereignty and the problem with
expressions of the popular will is that it might come up with an inconvenient
answer. It would also immediately revive memories of how the last referendum
was rigged by the 40% rule.
Worst of all, however, is that if a vote was offered only after the next
election it would be vulnerable to the immediate and obvious question, ``Why
not test opinion right now?''
And to that question there is only one real answer. The Scottish Secretary is
engaged in an exercise of trying both to survive politically and to protect
Westminster control of Scotland for as long as it is possible.
Prolonged pressure has brought him to the top of the slippery slope to change.
He is likely to delay his trip down it to the last possible minute even if that
procrastination makes the journey all the more certain.
</TEXT>
