<DOCNO>GH951129-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Single-tier councils face new cash rules</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH , Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth has redrawn the rules covering capital
spending and council debt for the new single-tier councils.
He made it clear yesterday when giving details of the local government
settlement for next year that they would be expected to rely much more on
involving the private sector to meet local needs.
Mr Forsyth spelled out the thinking behind the changes. ``The outgoing councils
have in general been able to pursue the outdated philosophy that, where the
needs exist, they must be met by direct public investment,'' he said
``The Government's approach, reflected in the Private Finance Initiative, is
that the public sector should increasingly focus on specifying the services its
customers need and look to others to incur the necessary investment.''
Mr Forsyth also announced that he would retain his powers to cap local
authority spending, despite his general desire to reduce controls on local
government.
Effectively, he blamed the behaviour of Scottish councils for his decision to
keep the capping controls. It had been made, he said, against a background of
increased council spending, growing council manpower, and rising council tax
bills.
He repeatedly contrasted the higher levels of spending by Scottish councils
with those of their counterparts in England.
On council grant, the Scottish Secretary said he had improved on last year's
plans by #106m. Government support for council spending would total #5400m and
he had allocated Scottish councils the full formula consequences of the English
settlement.
Scottish councils, he claimed, were being treated ``very favourably'' and there
was no need for cuts in front-line services or excessive council tax increases,
especially if the new councils took the chance to streamline their management
structures and took a fresh approach to the way services were delivered.
However, Convention of Scottish Local Authority leaders disagreed totally, and
warned of council tax rises and the need for ``savage'' cuts in services to
stay within the new capping limits.
The Scottish Secretary said it was necessary to take steps to control the
escalating level of Scottish local authority debt which, on general services,
had risen by 65% since 1987. Housing debt had risen by 57% over the same period
and he said that paying the loan charges meant using up more and more money
which should be available for spending on services.
Under the new rules next year, councils will have to use 25% of their capital
receipts from house and land sales to repay their capital debt. That figure
will rise to 50% for 1997-98.
Mr Forsyth said he recognised that his decision would curtail councils' ability
to incur capital expenditure at their own hand but he said that, by engaging in
joint ventures with the private sector under the PFI, the councils should be
able to attract private investment on a scale ``which would more than offset
the effects of his decision''.
The unitary councils will also face severe new restrictions on the amount of
current revenue they can spend on capital projects.
Mr Forsyth said this action would protect council taxpayers. Capital funded
from revenue involved the use of council tax money and the new curbs would
reduce the average council tax bill by #41 as compared with this year.
Councils had planned to spend #132m on Capital Funded from Current Revenue this
year. This had added #79 to the average council tax, claimed Mr Forsyth. Next
year, such spending will be limited to just #62m.
Cosla's Labour president Councillor Rosemary McKenna said the settlement meant
greater control of local government finances by central Government at a time
when we had a Scottish Secretary who claimed to want to devolve more powers to
local authorities.
More control was being exerted by the requirement on councils to use a quarter
of their capital receipts from the sale of assets to pay off loan debt rather
than invest in much-needed community facilities.
Scottish Liberal Democrat local government spokeswoman Ray Michie MP said the
new regulations on capital receipts would mean that the #500m backlog in school
building repairs in Scotland would only get worse.
Announcing the settlement in a series of Parliamentary written answers, Mr
Forsyth said Grant Aided Expenditure - the amount the Government thinks
councils need to spend on services and debt charges - was 1.75% higher than in
the current year after adjusting for transfers of responsibility. Aggregate
External Finance - councils' total income from grant and business rates - would
rise by 2.62%.
Cosla said the settlement went nowhere near meeting the 3.2% rate of inflation
nor the fact that councils would have to find more than #200m of additional
spending for Government initiatives.
Labour's Scottish Local Government spokesman John McAllion MP said the new
capping regime would force deep cuts in council services as well as impose
council tax increases.
He said the settlement confirmed the continuing centralisation of decision
making away from local government. Michael Forsyth had effectively decided the
level of local services and taxes across Scotland.
</TEXT>
