<HEADLINE>Awakened to the problem by the big sleep</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUGAL PERMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOUGAL PERMAN talks to the volunteers preparing for a cold night on the
Edinburgh streets
Former Housing Minister Lord James Douglas Hamilton maintains: ``There isn't a
housing problem in Scotland.'' If not, why are 100 people bedding down outside
St Andrew's and St George's church in Edinburgh on Friday.
Homeless charity the Rock Trust recognised that there is a problem and is
encouraging as many people as possible to abandon their beds in favour of cold
concrete as part of the seventh national sleep out for the 110,000 Shelter
estimates are homeless in Scotland.
This is the third sleep out organised for the ecumenical Christian charity, the
Rock Trust by Communications worker Ruth Innes who sees it as a ``great
opportunity for us to raise not only the Rock Trust's profile but the public's
awareness of the homelessness problem''.
Innes got in touch with the National Trust for the Homeless three years ago and
90 people slept out to raise #7000. Last year 70 people raised #4000. This year
the target is #10,000 to be shared between the Homeless Outreach project, the
Grassmarket Advice Centre, and the Rock Trust's Stepping Stones.
Apart from funds raised through sponsorship from the sleep out or the light
option of paying #15 to sleep in your own bed, Innes contacts previous
supporters and urges them to give help and money.
The Trust divides its cash between three ventures. Bedrock takes young people
from emergency hostels like Edinburgh's Stopover hostel and houses them with
three or four others and a supportive flatmate who helps them shop, budget and
pay the rent.
From there the young people move on the Stepping Stones project which also
takes young homeless people from other organisations like Barnardo's and
Bethany. ``One girl was a Big Issue seller who felt she couldn't quite manage
on her own and wanted to go to college,'' says Innes. Stepping Stones pays her
bills and allowance so she can go to college.
Edinburgh District Council gave the trust three Stepping Stones houses, and
they have bought two themselves. Each house and a flat has to be renovated and
decorated by volunteers. Stepping Stones has four flats providing six spaces
and the trust are about to buy two more flats.
The third stage is the Keystone project, befriending young people on their own
for the first time.
Part of helping these people is raising awareness. Many people do not know what
it is like to be 16 or 17 and out in the cold. They can't get benefits or help
with housing without disclosing very personal information; 70% are abused.
Even when all their housing spaces are full, the trust continues interviewing
applicants so that when spaces are available they can help. Each applicant has
to be assessed by the Community Care department. The homeless have to prove
they are vulnerable.
Lothian Regional Council is good at recognising the problem. Perhaps because of
the scale of the problem in Edinburgh or perhaps because of the awareness
raised by homeless charities. Officially Edinburgh's housing applications stand
at 3500. Shelter estimates it at three or four times that because of family and
group applications and many single people do not apply.
Lord Douglas Hamilton, who was contacted by the Rock Trust to ask for his
support last year, may not see the problem evident on every High Street in the
country but the same is not true for all.
Ruth Innes calls on everyone to volunteer their support. ``I'm not very popular
at this time of year,'' she laughs. This year, however, all eight of the
Edinburgh office staff are sleeping out.
Last year while fund-raisers bedded down outside, the minister of St Andrew's
and St George's church allowed several homeless people who turned up to see
what was going on to sleep in the church's undercroft. The Carlton Highland
Hotel sent down a huge spread of sandwiches for the sleepers.
The Rock Trust operates on care and compassion which is why 100 people will be
on George Street on Friday doing more than just losing sleep over the
homelessness problem.
</TEXT>
