<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Office spending curbed. Forsyth has his allowance cut over three years</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143084</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office faces a sharp reduction in its annual budget over the next
three years as its share of an overall cut in Government spending, according to
expenditure plans announced yesterday.
Mr Forsyth chose to stress a #173m cash-terms increase in next year's total
allocation as ``the highest ever'', and claimed it was a far better settlement
than pre-Budget rumours had indicated.
``I am delighted with the outcome of this year's public expenditure
negotiations in what was rightly billed as the toughest expenditure round for
years,'' he said.
However, figures show Mr Forsyth has had to accept a #329m cut in real terms to
his budget next year and faces cuts rising to 5% in the financial year
1998-1999.
Scottish Office spending will fall by #329m in real terms next year from
#14,048m (in last year's prices) to #13,719m. The cuts will continue, bringing
the department's predicted spending in 1998-99 to #13,318m - #730m less than
this year.
Despite claiming to have done better than his critics had predicted, Mr Forsyth
denied suggestions that Scotland's Budget settlement was politically motivated.
``I don't set out to bail out the Tories' fortunes when dealing with the
nation's finances,'' he said.
He had successfully defended the Barnett formula, which guarantees Scotland an
enhanced, fixed share of spending in England and Wales. Scotland had come out
``around the middle'' in the list of Government departments facing cuts.
The Budget was ``prudent and sensible'' and went ``far beyond what had been
expected in Scotland'', he said, adding: ``The Chancellor has done what's right
for the country. We'll give him credit not to succumb to any politically driven
pressures.''
Announcement of the cuts was offset by the Scottish Office coming third among
Government departments taking on the Private Finance Initiative to transfer
capital spending to the private sector.
Mr Forsyth said Scottish Office spending will be supplemented by investment,
under the PFI, of #930m over the next three years.
</TEXT>
