<HEADLINE>A test to show whether there is more say</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143085</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Secretary of State for Scotland is reported as saying that he has set
himself the test ``to find ways of improving the accountability of the
Government and give Scots more say in their own affairs and decision-making''.
The test I will use in assessing his proposals is whether he has removed the
situation in which he can block a piece of legislation which exists for England
and Wales from being introduced in Scotland even though the vast majority of
the Scottish people have been shown by opinion polls to want it.
The particular piece of legislation I have in mind is that enabling National
Parks in England and Wales and they have been described in Government papers on
the environment as ``jewels in the crown''.
Although in 1949 five Scottish areas were designated ``National Park Direction
Areas'' no progress has been made, despite the recommendations in 1990 of the
Countryside Commission for Scotland (then the Government's advisory body in
such matters) that four areas in Scotland be designated National Parks.
When 1000 people were interviewed by System Three Scotland in 1991, 84% thought
that we should have National Parks in Scotland.
When a local MP whose constituency borders Loch Lomond sought in 1991 to
introduce legislation enabling National Parks to be designated in Scotland, his
proposals were blocked by Ministers who introduced instead a new designation of
Natural Heritage areas.
Perhaps these would be more appropriate to the Scottish situation, but the
failure to make any significant progress in even defining what these should be,
let alone designating any particular area as a National Heritage Area in the
four-and-a-half years which have followed, appears to show the Government's
real motive - to frustrate the wishes of the Scottish people for bodies to be
set up with adequate powers and resources for the management of the most
popular mountain areas of Scotland.
What can possibly be the justification for Scotland to have separate
legislation from the remainder of the UK when it is used by the Government in
Westminster to deny the Scottish people a facility they want and which has been
enjoyed by the people of England and Wales for 46 years?
John Harvey,
Tarbet House, Loch Lomond,
Arrochar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prison nurse blamed himself over suicide</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PRISON nurse who examined a teenager hours before she hanged herself in her
cell said yesterday that he blamed himself for her death.
Mr William Rock, 46, told the Corton Vale hangings inquiry that Kelly Holland
was ``quiet and apprehensive'' when she arrived at the jail from Hamilton
Sheriff Court on June 22.
Mr Rock, a prison nurse for 22 years, said he did not consider Holland, 17, to
be a suicide risk but he placed her on 15-minute observations for alcohol
withdrawal.
He told procurator-fiscal John Miller, who is conducting the inquiry into the
deaths of Holland and another prisoner, Arlene Elliot, that even with hindsight
he considered his assessment reasonable.
However, he said he would have put Holland on suicide watch in a bare cell if
police had sent a ``special risk'' form to the jail with her.
Mr Miller asked Mr Rock: ``What was your reaction when you heard Kelly had
died?'' He replied: ``I was blaming myself.''
He said that, after the two deaths, he went on a two-week suicide prevention
course but learned nothing that would have made him act differently.
Mr Rock said a psychiatrist had tried to get Elliot, also 17, admitted to a
psychiatric hospital eight weeks before she hanged herself but she was still at
the prison on May 24 when her sentence ended.
Medical notes revealed that on May 2 she was ``very upset, pulling her hair and
hearing voices telling her to hurt herself''.
She was readmitted to Cornton Vale on remand on May 30 and found hanged on June
26, after a prison doctor had taken her off strict suicide supervision.
Earlier, a doctor accused of dismissing Holland as an attention seeker defended
his judgment.
Police surgeon Michael O'Keefe said he examined her in the cells at Hamilton
Sheriff Court on June 7 after she was reported to have to tried to jump out of
an upstairs window in an empty flat.
He said Holland had told him the accusation was ``rubbish'' and ridiculed
suggestions that she might be suicidal.
She told him she had been drinking before the alleged incident in the flat.
Dr O'Keefe said: ``I found that Kelly did not have an acute psychiatric or
psychotic disorder but a personality disorder with addictive traits.''
The inquiry, at Stirling Sheriff Court, continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Titular elitism must be checked</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975143087</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST week's decision by the British Dental Association to sanction the
recommendation that newly qualified dental surgeons can assume the title of
``doctor'' cannot go without some form of comment. Indeed, the ballot, in which
95% of dental students voted in favour of this change, could be described as
little more than a farcical exercise at elevating the status of dental
practitioners.
What is particularly perplexing about this decision is that it confers to newly
qualified undergraduates a title which ordinarily has to be earned by
postgraduates after, in many instances, several years of punishingly demanding
research.
For those of us who have completed PhD research, and therefore rightfully
earned the title ``doctor'', it is somewhat insulting, if not insensitive, that
an undergraduate with very limited research experience and almost certainly no
peer-reviewed publications can gain entitlement to use this title.
While one recognises that general practitioners have long assumed the title
``doctor'' it must be made clear that there is a distinction to be drawn here.
Historically, the title ``doctor'' has become synonymous with the general
practitioner and therefore something with which the public can readily
identify. Contrastingly, there are many hospital consultants and surgeons who
prefer to be known as ``Mr''.
Titular elitism is nothing new and owes much to its American roots where every
conceivable medical, para and quasi-medically-qualified person prefixes their
name with ``Dr''.
However, standards must be maintained within tertiary education and
professional organisations should not be able to deem that an undergraduate
qualification confers some immediate right to the title of ``Dr''.
Furthermore, the right to confer the title ``Dr'' is one which universities
receive by virtue of their respective Royal Charters to confer degrees,
diplomas and certificates.
Victor J Furay,
BSc (Hons), Dip Ed, Ph D, LMIFM, MI Env Sc, FLS,
14 Strowan Square,
Abbotsgrange,
Grangemouth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951129-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951129-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>951129</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doctors welcome tobacco price rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>Budget</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975143088</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor's latest hike in tobacco prices produced predictable responses
from the respective sides of the smoking divide.
His announcement means a 15p increase on the price of 20 cigarettes, while
cigars rise by 6p and pipe tobacco by 8p. Duty on rolling tobacco was frozen to
deter smugglers.
Doctors said the increases could help to save 2500 lives, although both the
British Medical Association and the British Thoracic Society urged the
Government to go further by banning tobacco adverts and promotion.
Tobacco manufacturers and retailers warned that the tax increases would
encourage criminals to move into cigarette smuggling.
A BMA spokesman said: ``Fifteen pence on a packet of 20 will help doctors in
the battle to persuade smokers to give up and so reduce the 110,000 deaths from
smoking each year.
``Such a rise could save up to 2500 lives in the long run but the Government
must follow through this real commitment with other measures, such as a ban on
tobacco advertising and promotion.''
Professor John Moxham, of the British Thoracic Society, said: ``This is a
welcome step in the fight to cut future lung cancer and chronic lung disease
cases.'' He, too, called for a ban on tobacco adverts.
Ms Pamela Furness, chief executive of Action on Smoking and Health, said:
``This is a good day for public health in the UK.''
The pressure group Quit, which helps smokers to give up the habit, said:
``There is no doubt that the price increase will encourage some people to stop
smoking.''
However, the Tobacco Manufacturers' Association warned of a tide of cigarette
smuggling following the increase.
``UK cigarette duties are already among the highest in Europe and another
punitive increase is the last thing either smokers or the tobacco trade want or
need.''
Mr Paul Mason, national spokesman for the Tobacco Alliance which represents
independent tobacconists, said Mr Clarke had ``given smugglers a Christmas
bonus and retailers a stab in the back''.
Forest, which campaigns for people's freedom to smoke, said the price increases
were ``disappointing'' but not a surprise. Campaigns manager Juliette
Wallbridge said: ``Smokers are constantly being hit.''
</TEXT>
