<HEADLINE>Bruton flies in for dramatic Downing Street statement</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER,  BENEDICT BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143089</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ulster deal breaks
the IRA deadlock
THE deadlock in the Northern Ireland peace process was broken last night, with
Irish Prime Minister John Bruton making a dramatic flight to London.
After a day of intense diplomatic activity and negotiation the British and
Irish Governments settled their differences on how to move towards IRA
disarmament.
The announcement by Mr Major and Mr Bruton of the breakthrough cleared the way
for all-party talks by the end of February.
Mr Bruton flew to Britain for a hastily arranged late night news conference
with Mr Major at Downing Street to unveil their historic agreement to end the
peace logjam.
The deal was struck on the eve of US President Bill Clinton's arrival at
Heathrow this morning for his visit to Britain and Ireland.
Before he left Washington, Mr Clinton hailed the new initiative. ``The United
States is proud to support the peacemakers,'' he said, adding that it ``brings
the people of Northern Ireland one step closer to the day when the only
barriers their children will face are the limits of their dreams.''
He said as the arms issue was being addressed, political talks would be
organised ``in which all parties will be invited to participate.''
Mr Clinton saluted Mr Major and Mr Bruton for their ``vision and courage''. He
said their agreement ``demonstrates that the will for peace is more powerful
than bombs and bullets, and it reminds us once again that with courage and
resolve bitter legacies of conflict can be overcome.''
Mr Major and Mr Bruton agreed to set aside remaining differences in order to
agree the final details of a ``twin-track'' approach to peace.
At the Downing Street conference, Mr Major called on all parties in the
conflict - and Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams in particular - to find the
courage to take risks for peace.
He said: ``No one is being asked to abandon a principle. But if we are to reach
agreement and carry the process further forward everyone will need courage to
take risks in the search for peace. That includes Mr Adams.''
However, he said he would not be prepared to meet Mr Adams until the IRA had
started to hand over their weapons. He said: ``In due course, the time will
come, but it is not here yet.''
Under the agreement, an international body will be established to provide
independent advice on decommissioning arms - rather than overseeing the process.
The creation of the body resolves the main obstacle in the peace process which
had been over decommissioning of IRA arms.
There had been differences between London and Dublin on Britain's insistence
that the IRA must start decommissioning its weapons before Sinn Fein could join
all-party talks.
Mr Major announced that US Senator George Mitchell would chair the body of
three members and said approaches were being made to two other eminent people.
Sitting with Mr Bruton at the news conference in Downing Street's state dining
room, Mr Major declared: ``Reaching this agreement has been neither easy nor
quick.
``In fact it has been an extremely difficult agreement to reach. But for both
of us the most important thing has been to reach the right agreement, an
agreement that in our judgment is going to generate further momentum in the
peace process and help us address some of the difficult issues that lie ahead.
``That, we think, is the way to take us closer to negotiations on a lasting
settlement involving all the political parties.''
Mr Major stressed that both governments had consulted widely over the agreement
and it did not represent the views of any one party.
He said it was founded on principles in the Downing Street Declaration,
unveiled almost two years ago.
``We hope that this agreement we've reached will attract the widest possible
co-operation on the part of everyone who genuinely wishes to consolidate peace
in Northern Ireland,'' he said.
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams said last night: ``When Sinn Fein is briefed on
the detail of tonight's agreement we will explore this positively as we have
all other propositions to re-establish the peace process.
``We will come to this on the basis of our analysis and integrity.''
Mr Bruton declared: ``What we need now is to move towards political structures
that will give political expression to the feelings of the people, feelings
that are expressed in terms of a yearning for peace, a yearning for
reconciliation and a yearning for a way of life that entrenches mutual
respect.''
He said: ``We are now taking the steps necessary to restore momentum in the
peace process.
``We are setting out on a road which is designed to overcome the difficulties
which have prevented us up to now from setting a date by which we will be
aiming to commence all-party discussions.''
Mr Major warned that although it was 15 months since the IRA ceasefire, there
were still daily episodes of violence and intimidation by paramilitary
organisations.
``We are now approaching a second successful, peaceful Christmas throughout the
whole of Northern Ireland.
``It is beyond question that life in Northern Ireland has been transformed and
that the people of Northern Ireland want both a just and a permanent peace,''
he said.
``This initiative that we are launching this evening is about generating the
confidence that will help us to achieve that lasting peace.
``No one is being asked to abandon a principle. But if we are to reach
agreement and carry this process further forward, everyone will need courage to
take risks in the search for peace and I hope that they will be prepared to do
so.''
The joint communique issued by the two premiers said they had agreed to launch
a ``twin track'' process with the aim of securing all-party talks by the end of
February.
All parties will be invited to intensive preparatory discussions with an open
agenda to reach widespread agreement over the structure, format and agenda for
the talks.
They would also look at whether and how an elected body could play a part, a
key demand of the Ulster Unionists.
The communique also gave details of the proposed new international body which
will provide ``an independent assessment of the decommissioning issue''.
It will be asked to report on the arrangements necessary for the removal of
arms from the political equation.
In particular, the body will be asked to ``identify and advise on a suitable
and acceptable method for full and verifiable decommissioning''.
It would also be asked to ``report on whether there is a clear commitment on
the part of those in possession of such arms to work constructively to achieve
that''.
The body will be asked to submit its report by the middle of January but
neither government is bound to accept its recommendations.
The two governments have agreed to meet again in mid-February to review
progress in the preparatory talks.
If the commission can produce a formula for handing over arms acceptable to the
IRA and loyalist para-militarities, the way could be open to starting all-party
talks on the future of the province although the Unionist parties will want
hard evidence that a substantial amount of IRA weaponry has been collected.
They may also insist that the IRA disclaims any desire to return to violent
methods if the all-party talks do not go its way.
Mr Bruton, deputy Irish premier Dick Spring and their team of advisers left
Dublin's government buildings at about 8.30pm for the London meeting.
They were flying in the Dublin government's executive jet from Baldonnel
military airfield on the outskirts of the Irish capital.
Indications that Mr Major and Mr Bruton might be on the point of agreement
emerged early today from Washington after their governments had appeared to be
drifting apart amid acrimony in the wake of failed weekend negotiations.
The mood was apparently transformed by contact that went on until the early
hours between civil servants from the two governments and with a strong
Washington input.
White House sources said they were increasingly confident of a successful end
to the talks between the two prime ministers.
The key moment was thought to have come when the leaders spoke together on the
telephone about the peace process at lunchtime for the sixth time in a week.
Their conversation lasted almost an hour and made what Dublin officials called
``tremendous progress''.
Mr Major is now likely to join Mr Clinton in Belfast tomorrow, according to
Government sources.
It appeared Mr Major would join the president at a reception in Queen's
University to which the leaders of all Northern Ireland's political parties,
including Mr Adams and the fringe loyalist groups, have been invited.
There was also speculation in the city that Mr Bruton would travel to Belfast
so that the three political leaders could stamp their authority on new moves in
the peace process.
However, there was a warning note last night from Conservative MP David
Wilshire, a member of the Northern Ireland Select Committee and British-Irish
Inter-Parliamentary Body, who described          the agreement as ``a classic
fudge''.
He warned that it might represent a long-term defeat for the British Government
for the sake of a short-term gain.
He predicted that, although the new international commission is intended to
have an advisory role only, the Government might find itself unable to reject
its advice in February.
</TEXT>
