<TEXT>
It's still a buyer's market
And the hills are
alive with Hooray
Henrys once more,
writes Property
Correspondent
Stewart McIntosh
A THREATENED species is making a comeback to the Highlands. Though the property
crash drove the species to the brink of extinction, the wealthy buyer of
Scottish estates and country houses is undergoing a recovery.
The cry of Hooray Henrys and Henriettas, backed by the yap of the yuppie, can
be heard once again in the bens and glens. Strutt &amp; Parker, an agent which
specialises in Highland estates and large east coast farms, has declared that
we are in the midst of ``a tartan property boom''.
However, Jamie Macnab of rival agent Savills says that, although the market is
recovering, it is still ``fickle''.
A particular problem is Scotland's ``sealed bid'' purchase system which is
mistrusted by would-be buyers from other countries. ``Giving all interested
parties one opportunity to make their best offer at a closing date is disliked
and treated with suspicion by the majority of buyers from outside Scotland,''
says Macnab.
As a result, buyers are circumventing the system and few of the large country
houses sold by Savills this year have gone to closing dates. ``Either a buyer
has materialised at the outset of the sale and has made a premium offer to take
the property off the market, or the property has remained on the market for
four or five months before being sold by negotiation,'' says Macnab. ``This has
been to the advantage of buyers who have known where they stood throughout.''
Indeed, buyers have held the clout throughout this year. ``A handful of
particularly desirable properties have changed hands very quickly - either
privately or as soon as they have reached the market - and at very high prices.
But most properties have taken longer to sell than in other years, and prices
have been reasonable but not high. On the whole, it's still a buyer's market.''
This year has seen an odd trend where more country properties were sold outwith
the traditional selling seasons than within them. Scottish country properties
are usually sold at two peak periods - between April and the end of June, and
between mid-August and October. During the summer holidays and the winter
months the market generally goes to ground.
But Savills got off to a flying start at the beginning of this year by selling
a dozen large houses in January and February - traditionally a dormant period.
These included houses snapped up before they could get to the market as well as
some which remained unsold from the autumn of 1994. Around 75% of the sales
went to buyers from outside Scotland - ``and the prices achieved were good''.
In sharp contrast, the main spring selling season from mid-April to July
produced far fewer sales. ``The reaction to quality properties was good in
terms of the number of enquiries from advertisements and the number of
viewers,'' says Macnab, ``but it proved very difficult to achieve deals.''
In two cases Savills had no fewer than five notifications of interest, but
no-one offered at the closing dates. Both houses were subsequently put under
offer after negotiation with individuals. ``But this demonstrates the lack of
genuine confidence on be-half of local buyers,'' says Macnab. His message to
buyers is that there is a good supply of quality country houses on the market -
and they are generally on the market for a longish period, usually four to six
months, before selling.
And his message to sellers is: ``Don't give up hope because houses are selling,
though the time needed to find the right buyer is longer than it used to be.''
Further upmarket, the message is even more upbeat. Strutt &amp; Parker's tartan
property boom is happening ``despite the problems in Lloyds and the threat of
devolution'', says the firm's latest UK market report. There are three types of
buyer interested in purchasing bens and glens . . .
Wealthy people based in the UK who want an estate for sport and privacy;
conservation and environmental groups (in four transactions, conservation
groups purchased a total of 150,000 acres); and foreign purchasers, of whom
Strutt &amp; Parker has several on its books, seeking substantial estates (one
American paid more than the #3m asking price for one of the largest on the
marker).
</TEXT>
