<HEADLINE>Observatory is star feature of Scots Renaissance house</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART McINTOSH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Photograph</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143189</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE conversion of Glenburn House offers a rare opportunity to live in a
building designed by one of Scotland's foremost architects.
Built in 1887 at Currie in the shadow of the Pentand Hills, Glenburn was
designed by Robert Rowand Anderson - a remarkable man who combined a career in
architecture with an important role as a military engineer.
Educated in the law in Edinburgh, he turned his back on a legal career and
trained with Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect who designed the Albert
Memorial and Glasgow University's buildings.
Like Scott, Anderson loved working in the Gothic style.
He designed classical additions to Glasgow's Pollok House and Edinburgh
University's Medical School.
In domestic architecture he was to play a leading role in the revival of 17th
century Scots architecture.
Glenburn House was designed in that Scots Renaissance style, and features a
galleried hall, an astronomical observatory, and a billiard room. The grounds
include the Poet's Glen - allegedly named after an Edinburgh equivalent of
McGonagall - which runs alongside the house. The conversion of Glenburn has
produced four individual terraced properties, each with three bedrooms. They
all have accommodation on ground and first floors.
The properties incorporate many original features, but the most noticeable are
the original observatory tower and the billiard room.
Two new four-bedroom houses with a gallery feature have been built in the
grounds.
Glenburn stands in several acres of protected green belt land in the Pentland
foothills at Currie, six miles from the centre of Edinburgh. The property has
panoramic views of the city and the Firth of Forth.
Glenburn House is approached via a tree-lined driveway a short distance from
the village of Juniper Green.
Prices range from #110,000 for the conversions to #215,000 for the new houses.
The sale is being handled by Edinburgh agents O'Neill.
</TEXT>
