<HEADLINE>Terrorism trial told seized Filofax detailed peace talks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975143190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETAILS of the peace talks between loyalists and Northern Ireland Minister
Michael Ancram were discovered in an alleged terrorist's Filofax, a court heard
yesterday.
The thick file was seized by police after the arrest of Progressive Unionist
Party official Lindsay Robb, who took part in the talks at Stormont in March.
The detective, who said he found the Filofax in a house in Ayr where Mr Robb
had been staying, told the High Court in Glasgow of other things it contained.
q An Ulster Volunteer Force plaque and a UVF pen;
q A handwritten UVF statement similar to one used by hooded paramilitaries
when they addressed Scots loyalist functions;
q The visiting card of a US senator from Massachusetts and another of a
British Labour MP.
Mr Robb, 28, a leading member of the Progressive Unionist Party, is on trial
with five other men accused of plotting to further the aims of the UVF by
acquiring guns and ammunition, intended, it is alleged, to endanger lives in
the UK and the Republic of Ireland.
The five other men are Mr John Johnston, 49, from Laurieston, Falkirk; Mr
Francis Hives, 45, of Liverpool; Mr William McArthur, 41, of Bonnybridge; Mr
David White, 29, of Airdrie; and Mr Alexander Davidson, 23, of Lurgan.
Evidence of the discovery of Mr Robb's Filofax after his arrest in an Ayr house
in July was given by Detective Constable Michael Tuckerman of Central Scotland
Police.
He read out the UVF statement in Mr Robb's handwriting which said: ``Loyalist
people of Scotland. It has been a long road. It has been a bloody road. We have
won the battle but the war is yet to be won.
``With the help of our fellow comrades in Scotland we will win the war. With
the help of the Scottish people we will gain an honourable settlement in our
land.
``Many men and women of the Ulster Volunteer Force have laid down their lives
and liberty in the name of Ulster.
``We the Ulster loyalist people owe our fellow loyalist people of Scotland a
debt of gratitude.
``The Mid Ulster UVF will not hesitate to maintain self sacrifice in the name
of the cause For God and Ulster.''
Mr Tuckerman told Mr Ian Bonomy QC, prosecuting, that the Filofax also
contained the names of several of Mr Robb's co-accused.
Entries told of visits to an Airdrie bar and loyalist functions in the Falkirk
area plus a visit to a man in Barlinnie Prison, and visits to Liverpool and
Scotland with a schoolboy football team.
However, Mr Tuckerman admitted to Mr Robb's QC, Mr Donald Findlay, that if the
Filofax contained anything illegal or sinister it would have been foolish to
leave it around openly on view.
He also agreed it was precisely the sort of thing someone involved in the
political world would have and that there were a number of entries relating to
his peace process meetings.
There was also nothing in the Filofax to suggest bombs or guns and the entries
were a reflection of what had been going on in Northern Ireland for a number of
years, with Mr Robb expressing his thoughts on the peace process, his
disappointment at the lack of progress, and the need to take a stronger line.
The trial, before Lord Sutherland, continues.
</TEXT>
