<TEXT>
THE definition of contaminated land, of those affected by it, and of the
circumstances in which pollution arises, is no simple task. The drafters of the
Environment Act 1995 have succeeded in creating a statute which, for the first
time, defines succinctly the subject matter but leaves deeper exploration to
``guidance'' by the Department of the Environment (in Scotland, our own
Secretary of State).
The new Act is designed to remedy, or at least minimise, the worst effects of
historic land contamination, identify responsibility, and penalise the
polluter. It is the first Act to tackle purposefully historic pollution. It has
led to the constitution of the Scottish Environment Protection Agency (SEPA),
which assumes the functions of the river purification authorities, HM
Industrial Pollution Inspectorate, and the Waste Regulation bodies.
One may question the need for yet more legislation of this kind: we have the
Environmental Protection Act 1990, the Control of Pollution Act 1974, the
Public Health (Scotland) Act 1897 (soon to disappear), and the age-old Common
Law of Nuisance - to say nothing of European legislation to which we are now
subject.
However, the 1995 statute is essential if we are to deal responsibly with the
waste we have created with the poisonous residues of derelict industry. The
very nature of contaminated land now receives definition: ``Any land which
appears to relevant local authorities to be in such a condition (by reason of
any substance in, on, or under the land) that significant harm is caused or
there is a significant possibility of significant harm being caused.''
These concepts are left largely undefined and the responsibility for amplifying
them will lie initially with the Secretary of State for Scotland (who is so
empowered to issue guidance on this and most other salient issues arising under
the legislation).
Indeed, draft guidance from the Department of the Environment is already
circulating. This is just as well because it is really in the draft guidance
issued in May this year that we perhaps see the underlying Government policy
(underpinning the new contaminated land laws) which has a little more
appreciation of the needs of industry, business and the economy generally than
is addressed by the bald provisions of the 1995 Act.
Since the shelving of the dreaded ``Register of Land put to a Contaminative
Use'', it has been recognised that the response to our industrial heritage
should rely as far as possible on market forces. This is already implicit in
the operation of town and country planning. It is increasingly common for
``brownfield'' sites to receive regeneration through new development.
The draft guidance talks of a ``suitable for use'' principle, in terms of which
consideration must be given to whether contamination represents an unacceptable
risk to the environment and whether there exist appropriate and cost-effective
means of remediation which take account of the actual or intended use of the
relevant land.
Furthermore, the authorities may only require ``reasonable'' remediation. In
judging what is reasonable in the circumstances they must weigh up the likely
cost against the seriousness of the pollution.
That said, the legislation will, inevitably, be enforced widely. Its primary
target is the polluter - the party who has caused or knowingly permitted the
contaminative substances to be on, in, or under the land.
However, given we are largely dealing with historic contamination, the polluter
may be nowhere to be found. If this is the case, then it will be the owner or
occupier of the land who will step into the firing line. Such is the wide
definition here of ``owner'' that a bank or other lending institution which
attempts to enforce fixed security over the land, and possibly also receivers
and other insolvency practitioners, are at risk. In some circumstances, it may
even be cheaper to write off the bad debt rather than risk direct involvement
with the land.
In most insolvency cases, of course, it will be necessary to take on the
property. Here, the receiver and the appointing bank must go in with their eyes
open and have at least a reasonable understanding of the condition of the land
and its potential to give rise to pollution.
Obviously, the ``suitable for use'' principle is relevant here, but failure to
inform oneself and adopt any necessary measures will easily lead to such an
``innocent party'' being deemed to have ``knowingly permitted'' resultant
pollution.
Failure to comply with a remediation notice involves criminal liability (with a
maximum penalty on summary conviction of a #20,000 fine, but with daily fines
applying thereafter) and will allow the authorities to exercise their own wide
powers of clean-up and cost recovery against the unfortunate ``owner'' or
``occupier''. Moreover, pollutants are known for their migratory tendencies.
Liability will not be confined to your own land.
An essential step in the purchase or lease of, or taking security over, land
which may be contaminated should be some form of environmental audit of past
and present use; identifying the nature and extent of any contamination,
current or historical; and potential liabilities of both ownership and
occupancy.
While water and air-borne pollution can be readily detected in most instances,
buried contamination is usually invisible, lying as a toxic sub-stratum until
inadvertently released by demolition or construction works.
Finally, it should be borne in mind that, in substance, there is nothing
radically new in these provisions. For centuries now the common Law of Nuisance
has existed and often been used to protect landowners from the misdemeanours of
their neighbours. The trouble with the common law is that it depends upon
individual citizens having the inclination and finance to go to court.
These new laws are an attempt to put effective public regulatory machinery in
place to tackle the problems of contaminated land. I have no doubt they will be
used to some effect.
As they say, and with good reason: ``Caveat emptor - let the buyer beware.''
n Vincent Brown is a partner in Dorman Jeffrey and Co.
</TEXT>
