<TEXT>
MY God, it must have been awful for Robert Liston. The stench of the blood
splattered over the floor, patients held down as their legs, breasts, arms, or
whatever were hacked off on the operating table, sometimes without even a swig
of brandy to help them. So bad in fact that, as Glasgow University's professor
of pathology Hugh Simpson told the Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh,
Liston once walked out intent on switching to something only slightly less
ghastly . . . the law.
Fortunately, the fastest cutter of his generation didn't, and later proved a
model for James Young Simpson, whose knock-out parties for colleagues
eventually came up with ether as a medical anaesthetic.
Penitent's stool
WE got it wrong. The Diary is indebted to Bryan Douglas for pointing out the
error. The first non-white lawyer within the Scottish Bar was not Dr Raj Jandoo
but Albert Mkandawire who was admitted in 1963.
He was born in Nyasaland, now Malawi, where at least the Faculty, the Bar
Council, and the English Law Society have made a positive impact. It was their
delegation, and particulary Jane Deighton, whose intervention in the case of
lawyers Orton and Vera Chirwa which prompted the first moves for democratic
change in Malawi - unlike the Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh which in
1991 bestowed its highest honour on the Malawian dictator Hastings Banda after
he had written out a large cheque.
Maybe Liston made the wrong choice, after all.
Bar crime
SOUTH Africa was just one pit stop for Ross Harper in his globetrotting duties
as president of the International Bar Association. Straight on to the plane
after meeting its lawyer President, Nelson Mandela, he jetted off to launch the
IBA year of Latin America in Brazil.
``The IBA is committed to the rule of law and the right to live under the rule
of law,'' he told the assembled gathering. Unfortunately his two presidential
gifts, an IBA tie and set of cufflinks, both portraying the scales of justice
and the hand of fellowship, had been pinched by a tea leaf in Johannesburg.
``The best I can do is offer a firm handshake, a note of thanks, and a promise
to send out replacements as soon as possible,'' El Presidente Harper meekly
added.
Tales from
the Bench
A WOMAN aged 28 was reluctantly giving evidence at a trial at Edinburgh Sheriff
Court concerning a man who had allegedly been beaten up and robbed of 32p at a
boozy party. Shown a photo of the victim, she spluttered ``uuuurgh'' then told
the depute fiscal, Anne Keenan, ``that is a face I would never forget . . . I
have never seen him before in my life''.
Later Sheriff Andrew Bell demanded to know why she was claiming she did not
remember being quizzed by police when she had told the jury she just said ``F .
. . off, F . . . off, F . . . off'' when being interviewed by the constabulary.
``That's what I always tell the police,'' she candidly replied.
Haunting case
THE horrors of Cromwell Street will live on forever for the surviving victims
of Rosemary West. It might be argued that lifetime incarceration among the
likes of Myra Hindley may be a depraved dyke's heaven, particularly for someone
whose sexuality extends to appalling sadism.
The London-based hacks who dutifully chronicled the 31-day trial may now find
themselves in trouble with the Attorney-General over pre-trial publicity. That
would not have happened here and, arguably, the Crown could not have won
convictions up in Scotland because of the lack of corroboration.
Own counsel
THE jury and others have been offered post-traumatic stress counselling. Did
this extend to Mr Justice Mantell QC, who won unanimous praise for the way he
handled the trial?
``Good question,'' said the Lord Chancellor's office. Theoretically, it is
still open to him, but he seems to be made of the right stuff. Not even a wee
holiday for the senior presiding judge of the Western Circuit: he wasr back on
the Bench in Winchester this week presiding over a mundane five-day civil case.
