<HEADLINE>Justice delivered on the dot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT DICKSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975143196</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNTIL recently the proceedings in every sheriff, jury, and high court trial had
to be noted by a shorthand writer. Certain courts are now using recording
equipment instead, and eventually all court officials will be trained in the
use of the machines. I feel some regret at this change.
I have always found it helpful, both as a solicitor and a sheriff, to be able
to ask that the notes be checked to see exactly what a witness said previously
if a dispute has arisen. I have great admiration for the skill and dedication
of the small army of ladies and gentlemen who quickly can find the correct
passage among all the squiggles and dots and read back the exact words used.
When both lawyers and the judge are trying to follow the evidence and also ask
questions it is difficult for them accurately to note the exact words the
witness has used. This can lead to a verbal clash if 20 minutes later it is
suggested a police officer has said something ``may'' have occurred rather than
it ``probably'' happened.
I for one will miss having the help of a shorthand writer in dealing with such
situations; re-winding a tape recorder and trying to find the correct passage
may, I fear, be a poor substitute.
Some judges do know and understand shorthand and for them accurate note-taking
may be easier. One such person was the late Mr Justice Cassels who before going
to the Bar had been a newspaper reporter. He took all his own notes using
shorthand, except when he was presiding over a murder trial. In the 1940s and
50s, when the death penalty was still in use, it was compulsory for all judges
in England when presiding over a capital case to make their trial notes
available for the Appeal Court and the Home Secretary.
As nobody but Sir James Cassels could read shorthand, he required to adapt his
style if he was trying an alleged killer. Only when he pointed out that a
verbatim version of what was said was already available from the court
shorthand writer (it became universal in England and Wales in 1935) was he
allowed to dispense with exhibiting his notes to the Appeal Court. He reverted
to shorthand for every case.
His ability to understand and write shorthand did, however, bring one case to
an abrupt halt when he himself was sitting in the Criminal Appeal Court.
Counsel for the appellant, P H Lawton KC, had claimed a trial judge had
misdirected the jury in a case when he referred to ``these'' cases of stolen
property, when in fact only six out of hundreds of cases of purloined whisky
had been proved.
Sitting with the Lord Chief Justice, Lord Goddard, Cassels pointed out that in
shorthand ``six'' and ``these'' are very similar and a mere dot distinguishes
them. An examination of the actual notes showed the original judge had used the
correct words and an error had arisen in the transcription. ``I seem to have
been defeated by a dot,'' commented Lawton as his client was returned to prison.
A dot also led to the downfall of a corrupt post office official. In June 1934
a firm of bookmakers noticed a Mr Abrahams, a professional racing
correspondent, always seemed to be successful with his bets when he placed by
telegram at one post office but equally invariably lost money if he used
another method of communication. They investigated the position and found
almost all the successful telegrams had been handled by a young clerk, one
William Harvey.
Harvey was believed to be of impeccable character and in a long statement,
every page of which he initialled, he told the police he had never had any
financial dealings with Abrahams and had received the telegrams in the normal
way, stamping them to record the time of receipt and passing them through the
system. He denied any part in the alleged fraud.
The bookmakers decided to try to prove the telegrams had been time-stamped
before the winning horse's name had been added and money had been paid by the
punter to the young post office clerk in return for this service. They finally
traced a #5 note which had been undoubtedly paid by a bank to Abrahams but
which was presented later to a tobacconist near where Harvey worked.
Could they prove the note had been spent by William Harvey? It was noticed that
the store-keeper required any customer presenting him with a Treasury note to
put their initials on the back and this particular one had ``W H'' in pencil in
the corner.
Harvey denied all knowledge of the money. He claimed the letters ``W H'' were
not his. Handwriting experts gave lengthy evidence, some favouring the view the
initials had been made by Harvey, others the contrary. All, however, accepted
there was considerable doubt in the matter.
As the case was drawing to a close, Sir Patrick Hastings, KC, acting for the
bookmakers, picked up Harvey's police statement and while perusing it noted
that on each page Harvey had placed a dot after his last initial; the
significance of the dot was apparent when it was realised it was not in the
usual place of a full stop but nearer the top of the ``H''. In every case the
dot was in exactly the same place.
The #5 was sent for and re-examined by each expert. There, unnoticed before,
was the fatal dot. The experts who had been in doubt before were unanimous in
their view Harvey had initialled the #5 note. The connection between him and
Abrahams was proved beyond doubt and both were imprisoned for their part in an
ingenious fraud.
As shorthand notes are replaced by tape machines in the courts,
Robert Dickson makes a case for the letters of the law
